<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 00:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vignettes From 72nd Academy Awards  </HEADLINE>
By ANTHONY BREZNICAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Oscar bandits weren't about to get a second chance.
</P>
<P>
   The dozens of Academy Awards statuettes that junkman Willie
Fulgear rescued from the trash last week arrived at Sunday night's
awards ceremony in a van surrounded by armed guards.
</P>
<P>
   ''We weren't going to risk anything at this point,'' said Ric
Robertson, the Academy's executive administrator. He was vague
about just how many extra guards he employed.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's Oscars were a mixture of the ones that were stolen and
then recovered, and replacements that were quickly ordered after
the first batch disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't clear which winners would be going home with the ones
Fulgear pulled from the trash.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Following the lead of Jennifer Lopez, one of the ''South Park''
guys decided to let it almost all hang out.
</P>
<P>
   Trey Parker, co-nominated for best original song with composer
Marc Shaiman for ''Blame Canada,'' arrived at the Oscars wearing a
green tropical-print, low-cut outfit that was the spitting image of
the one Lopez stunned spectators with at last month's Grammy
awards.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was just blessed with a beautiful body and it hangs
perfectly. ... I don't use tape,'' Parker said when asked the same
thing everyone wondered of Lopez: How do you keep it in place?
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, he ran his hand from the top of his hairy chest to
his navel, where the dress came together before opening again to
reveal a pair of hairy legs.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The director of ''The Sixth Sense'' says he may have had a
paranormal experience on the eve of the Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   M. Night Shyamalan said he found a miniature Oscar statuette
inside a church while scouting locations for his next film,
''Unbreakable.''
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the crew members just found it at my feet,'' he said,
holding up the miniature as he walked down the red carpet to the
Shrine Auditorium for Sunday's Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's a sign from God. Either a concession prize or an
omen, a sign of things to come,'' said Shyamalan, nominated for
best director for the film about a boy who sees dead people.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   For Michael Clarke Duncan and Lucy Liu, the roar of adulation
only made them want more.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan, the towering actor nominated for his supporting role in
''The Green Mile,'' thundered up and down the red carpet, waving at
fans and urging them to cheer even louder as his fellow celebrities
paraded into the Shrine Auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   ''It just wasn't enough for me, you've got to work the audience
here,'' said the former ditch digger from Chicago, who grinned and
cheered along with the spectators.
</P>
<P>
   Liu had a section of her fans cheering and screaming as she
approached two young blond men wearing T-shirts reading ''I Love
Lucy.''
</P>
<P>
   The ''Ally McBeal'' co-star allowed each one to kiss her hand
before moving on.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Tom Cruise, nominated as best supporting actor for ''Magnolia,''
says he was always a fan of the movies but not always of the
Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   ''We watched a lot of movies, but I actually never saw the
Oscars until I became an actor,'' he said, reminiscing briefly as
he headed into the Academy Awards for Sunday night's ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ''Then I started watching them for some reason,'' he quipped.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be a big-deal Hollywood event without at least a
couple of protests. As celebrities arrived for Sunday's Academy
Awards, scores of demonstrators stood outside the Shrine Auditorium
waving signs.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-abortion protesters demonstrated against ''The Cider House
Rules,'' in which Michael Caine, in a role that won him an Oscar,
portrays a kindly doctor at a New England orphanage who also
performs abortions.
</P>
<P>
   One protester held a sign proclaiming, ''Cider House Reeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Not far away, other protesters demonstrated against movies that
are filmed outside the United States to take advantage of tax
breaks and cheaper labor in countries like Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bring Hollywood Back to Hollywood'' read one of their signs.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ''Toy Story 2'' director John Lasseter brought three of his best
friends to the Academy Awards: Woody, Buzz Lightyear and Jessie the
Cowgirl.
</P>
<P>
   The toy-sized versions of the movie's stars were on hand to
present the Oscar for best animated short film.
</P>
<P>
   Buzz wore his usual spaceman attire, highlighted with a bow tie,
while Woody and Jessie bowed to Oscar fashion and donned sequined
Western garb.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   She grew up seeing Oscar at her grandmother's house, says
actress Angelina Jolie, whose father, Jon Voight, won one for
''Coming Home'' in 1978. But she never got to touch the award until
she claimed her own on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Jolie, who won for best supporting actress for ''Girl,
Interrupted,'' said her father's Oscar was kept under a fishbowl at
his mother's house, where it was made clear to her that she was not
to touch it.
</P>
<P>
   ''I never actually held one,'' said Jolie. ''It was always just
this strange thing in your grandma's house.''
</P>
<P>
   Jolie almost didn't get to hold her own Oscar on Sunday.
Arriving late after the Oscar show started, she and her brother had
to talk their way past security guards, who allowed them to sprint
to their seats while the cameras were focused on host Billy
Crystal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-27-00 0001 </TRAILER>
