<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hillary Clinton picks up first third-party endorsement  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton has picked up the
first political party endorsement of her Senate campaign against
New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   The endorsement of the first lady from the Working Families
Party came Sunday as a statewide poll reported that Giuliani's lead
of three weeks ago had disappeared and that the race was now a
statistical dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   ''I consider this the beginning of a partnership,'' Clinton told
the Working Families Party convention in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Promising to be 'a voice and a vote'' in the Senate for working
families, the first lady said ''my opponent and his fellow
Republicans want us to do a U-turn back to the 1980s where we had
skyrocketing deficits and disinvestment ... I'm not just someone
who says I'm for family values, I'm for valuing families.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Clinton left the heavy Giuliani bashing to others at
the gathering of the small, labor union-backed third party.
</P>
<P>
   ''They say if you want to keep the beer real cold, put it next
to Rudy's heart,'' said Jim Hightower, a radio talk-show host and
former Texas agriculture commissioner, to the cheers of the almost
1,000 party loyalists on hand.
</P>
<P>
   Greeting those attending the party convention were some fliers
made up to look like wanted posters and featuring a caricature of
the Republican mayor. The fliers charged the New York City mayor
with ''crimes against humanity'' and said ''he has been known to
use the alias Adolph.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Moskowitz, labor coordinator for the Working Families
Party, said ''we absolutely do not subscribe to this'' and
maintained that if party leaders had seen those passing out the
fliers, ''they would have been stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   The fliers purported to be from a group called the Citywide
Coalition to Stop Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   The Working Families Party was created in New York two years ago
to push the Democratic Party toward the left.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton has shunned the liberal label, insisting she is a
''New Democrat'' with a middle-of-the-road agenda, the backing of
the Working Families Party provides the Giuliani camp with another
opportunity to paint her as a left-leaning politician.
</P>
<P>
   Minor party endorsements can be valuable in the race because
unlike other states, New York allows major party candidates to add
votes cast for them on third party ballot lines to their overall
vote total. That can make the difference in close elections.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is expected to have the Democratic Party endorsement
while Giuliani appears to have a lock on the Republican line.
</P>
<P>
   The support for Clinton came as a New York Post poll conducted
by Zogby International showed the first lady favored by 45 percent
of likely voters to 42 percent for the New York City mayor, a
statistical tie. A Zogby poll conducted three weeks ago had
Giuliani leading the first lady, 49 percent to 42 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Pollster John Zogby attributed the shift, in part, to voter
dissatisfaction with the mayor's handling of the shooting 10 days
ago of an unarmed black man, Patrick Dorismond, by New York City
police.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's handing her the race,'' Zogby said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has come under fire for having police release
Dorismond's criminal record, including sealed juvenile records,
instead of consoling the family. On Saturday, after Dorismond's
funeral, mourners and police clashed in New York City leaving
people injured on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Zogby's telephone poll of 710 likely voters was conducted Friday
and Saturday and has a margin of error of plus or minus 4
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Two other statewide polls -- by Marist College's Institute for
Public Opinion and by the Quinnipiac College Polling Institute --
taken before the Dorismond shooting had shown Giuliani with slight
leads over the first lady. A CBS News-New York Times poll had shown
the race even.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in an interview with the issue of New York magazine
due out today, Clinton said one of the advantages she brings to the
Senate campaign and her potential service in the Senate is a thick
skin.
</P>
<P>
   ''Part of what I bring is that there is nothing anybody can say
about me that will hurt my feelings, '' she told the magazine. ''I
cannot be insulted. You know, I just can't be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
