<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schumer asks Clinton to tap federal oil reserves  </HEADLINE>
By L. ANNE NEWELL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- U.S. Sen. Charles Schumer said tapping
federal oil reserves could force OPEC into releasing more oil to
the United States and other petroleum-hungry countries in its
semi-annual meeting today.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer's announcement came on the eve of what many describe as
the Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries' most
important meeting in 20 years. OPEC ministers will meet in Vienna,
Austria today to review global oil markets.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, a Democrat, asked President Clinton to utilize the
Strategic Oil Reserve for the first time in nearly a decade through
a swap program that would replenish supplies when prices fall. It
would also nearly double the size of the reserve, stockpiling 1
billion barrels.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is our last chance to get gas prices back down before the
summer driving season,'' Schumer said. ''We should immediately tell
OPEC nations that if they don't increase their output to two
million barrels a day, we will tap the Strategic Oil Reserve.''
</P>
<P>
   OPEC oil ministers are expected to reach an agreement that would
boost petroleum supplies, but have not shown willingness to boost
production by the 2 million to 2.5 million barrels per day that the
United States and other industrial powers want.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, analysts predict OPEC will raise its daily output by
about 1 million barrels, an amount many say won't be enough to
simultaneously replenish depleted oil inventories, meet seasonal
needs for gasoline and push down prices. Kuwait's oil minister,
Sheikh Saud Nasser al-Sabah, said Sunday OPEC could raise its
official production by as much as 1.7 million barrels of crude a
day.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has previously said it will not
decide until after the OPEC meeting whether to draw some of the
nearly 570 million barrels of oil in the Strategic Oil Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   The reserve, created in 1975 after the Arab oil embargo, is
intended to provide a stopgap in case of disruptions in oil
imports. It has been used only once, during the Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer began petitioning Clinton to release the federal
reserves in September and co-introduced legislation to allow easier
access to the reserves two months later. He said Sunday the
administration may have been reluctant to release reserves because
it didn't want to use strong-arm tactics with OPEC.
</P>
<P>
   ''They may have thought diplomacy would work,'' Schumer said.
''But look at its effects.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer predicted gasoline prices will rise to as much as two
dollars a gallon this summer if neither the federal reserves are
tapped nor OPEC supplies increased.
</P>
<P>
   He also predicted it could undermine upstate New York's economy
-- with residents paying as much as $2,000 a year for gasoline -- and
lead to increased federal taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only argument against (my plan) is that it may not work,''
Schumer said. ''My answer is nothing else has worked.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
