<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 12:20 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, March 27, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Putin Wins Russian Elections
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Vladimir Putin scored a convincing victory Monday in Russia's
presidential election with his promise to clean up the country after years of
political chaos and restore it as a global power. With 94 percent of the vote
counted, Putin had an unassailable lead with 52.5 percent of the vote, according
to election officials. Communist Gennady Zyuganov, who presented a surprisingly
strong challenge, was in second place with 29.45 percent. Although Putin managed
to avoid being forced into a runoff vote against Zyuganov, his victory was less
than the huge win that had been expected for the former KGB officer.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Michael Caine Takes Home Oscar
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Michael Caine, the kindly orphanage headmaster in ''The
Cider House Rules,'' won his second best supporting actor Oscar Sunday. Angelina
Jolie, the disruptive mental patient in ''Girl, Interrupted,'' won for
supporting actress -- a generation after her father, Jon Voight, took home an
Oscar. ''The Matrix,'' the story of a computer hacker who discovers life is a
big illusion, won four Oscars -- for film editing, sound, sound effects editing
and visual effects. Pop star Phil Collins scored the best original song award
for his sentimental ''You'll be in My Heart'' from the animated Disney film
''Tarzan.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Plan Would Create House Fund
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore has drafted campaign finance reform
proposals that include a $7.1 billion endowment to pay for House and Senate
campaigns and rules that would have identified the pro-George W. Bush financiers
of controversial primary-season TV ads, his campaign aides said Sunday. Gore,
who recently said he was putting campaign reform front-and-center in his
Democratic presidential race, planned to unveil the proposals during a campaign
stop Monday in Milwaukee. As first reported in Monday's editions of The
Washington Post, Gore was proposing to create a ''Democracy Endowment,'' new
disclosure rules for lobbyists and outside groups that pay for political ads,
and mandatory free ''rebuttal'' air time for candidates targeted by such
third-party ads.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton, Assad Fall Short on Talks
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   GENEVA (AP) -- President Clinton and Syrian President Hafez Assad failed to
nail down an agreement Sunday to restart talks between Israel and Syria for a
landmark peace treaty. Syrian presidential spokesman Jubran Kourieh said that
during three hours of face-to-face talks Assad stressed the importance of
Syria's long demand for an Israeli pullback to the country's 1967 borders. White
House spokesman Joe Lockhart said the meeting as ''very useful.'' But, he added,
''we don't believe it would be productive'' for Syrian-Israeli talks to resume
at this point.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Study: Cops Fail To Report Force
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Police in Louisville don't always report their use of
force against suspects, and the system for monitoring that use of force has
serious flaws, according to a 10-month investigation by The Courier-Journal.
Arrests reports obtained by the newspaper for a story today show officers
routinely ''struggle with,'' ''tackle,'' ''fight,'' ''wrestle with'' or ''pepper
spray'' people without filling out a use-of-force report.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Castro: Elian Will Return to Cuba
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- President Fidel Castro declared Sunday that the Miami
relatives of 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez had lost their battle to keep the child
in the United States and that it was only a matter of time before the boy was
reunited with his father in Cuba. ''The Cuban mafia has lost,'' an animated
Castro insisted before hundreds of pro-government university students gathered
to press for the child's return to his communist homeland. U.S. District Judge
K. Michael Moore's dismissal on Tuesday of the family's lawsuit seeking to block
Elian's repatriation was ''just and moral,'' Castro said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japan Stocks Rise
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks rose Monday at the end of the morning session.
The Nikkei gained 11.52 points to 19,969.60 points. On Friday, the average
closed up 253.48 points.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Florida Defeats Oklahoma St. 77-65
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- Florida wore down yet another higher-seeded, more
experienced team, with a 77-65 win Sunday over Oklahoma St. in the East Regional
final. The Gators will play resurgent North Carolina, which beat Tulsa 59-55 in
the South Regional final, in Indianapolis. Wisconsin, like North Carolina an
eighth seed, will play Michigan State, the only No. 1 seed left, in the other
semifinal.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Knicks Defeat Trail Blazers 93-89
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Allan Houston, Patrick Ewing and Latrell Sprewell each
scored 19 points as the New York Knicks nearly blew a 17-point third-quarter
lead but held off the Portland Trail Blazers 93-89 Sunday night. Larry Johnson
added 16 points for the Knicks, who pulled into a tie for first place in the
Atlantic Division because Miami lost to Orlando.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
