<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'All About My Mother' Wins Oscar  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Just like last year, you could guess by the
presenters who would win the Oscar for foreign language film
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   After Spanish-speaking actors Penelope Cruz and Antonio Banderas
read the five nominees, Cruz announced the winner was fellow
countryman Pedro Almodovar's ''All About My Mother.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Pedro!'' shouted Cruz, who appeared in the film. It was a
scene reminiscent of last year's excited pronouncement by Sophia
Loren when she revealed ''Life is Beautiful'' had won by
exclaiming, ''Roberto!'' -- the first name of fellow Italian Roberto
Benigni.
</P>
<P>
   This year's winner was no surprise. ''All About My Mother,'' the
story of a woman in search of her dead son's father, was widely
praised as Almodovar's best film in years. It also gave Spain its
third foreign language Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   Almodovar, previously nominated for his wild 1988 comedy ''Women
on the Verge of a Nervous Breakdown,'' struggled with his English
through a rambling acceptance speech. At one point he thanked his
fellow countrymen who were watching the awards show in Spain at
''six years in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This is for Spain,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Almodovar's characters tend to run on, the director's
speech ran overtime, prompting the orchestra to start playing while
he was still speaking. When Almodovar ignored the music, Banderas
tugged at his arm to jokingly pull him off stage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-27-00 0048 </TRAILER>
