<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 00:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suns 90, Warriors 82  </HEADLINE>
By BOB BAUM, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- Penny Hardaway scored 27 of his season-high 33
points in the first half and the Phoenix Suns nearly blew a
25-point lead before pulling out a 90-82 victory over the Golden
State Warriors Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway made all 10 of his field goal tries as Phoenix took a
63-40 halftime lead, but the Suns fell apart in the second half,
scoring a season-low 27 points and committing 14 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Marion added 15 points, 14 rebounds and five blocked shots
for Phoenix, in its second game since starting point guard Jason
Kidd broke his left ankle. But Marion was scoreless, going 0-for-5
from the field, in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Donyell Marshall scored 28 points and grabbed 11 rebounds for
the Warriors, who lost their fifth in a row and 13th in their last
14 games. Larry Hughes added 16 points but made just four of 15
shots.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway's two free throws gave the Suns their biggest
first-half lead, 62-37, 24.3 seconds before the break.
</P>
<P>
   But Golden State outscored Phoenix 15-4 to start the third
quarter to cut the Suns' lead to 67-55 on Marshall's two free
throws with 3:35 to go in the period.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix, which has won six of seven, re-built a 75-60 lead after
three quarters, but the Warriors came back again, outscoring the
Suns 13-4 to start the fourth quarter and cut it to 79-73 when
Marion was called for goaltending on Marshall's shot with 7:41 to
play.
</P>
<P>
   Despite turnovers and missed free throws, the Suns pulled it
out. Randy Livingston's two free throws with 5:13 to play gave
Phoenix an 84-75 lead, then Hardaway scored on a breakaway layup to
make it 86-75 with 3:29 to go.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes' 3-pointer sliced the lead to 86-78 with 3:08 to go, but
Hardaway sealed the victory by making four consecutive free throws.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns were 9-for-34 (26 percent) from the field in the second
half after shooting 60 percent (24-for-40) in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, Marion was 6-for-7 from the field, grabbed 10
rebounds and blocked four shots. But he was overshadowed by
Hardaway, who put on a dazzling array of offensive moves against
Hughes and Vontego Cummings.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix took charge with a 27-6 surge, including 14 consecutive
points, to go up 57-33 on Hardaway's three-point play with 2:49
left in the half.
</P>
<P>
@Notes: Kevin Johnson, coaxed out of retirement the day after Kidd
was injured, was on the Phoenix bench in street clothes. He got a
standing ovation from the crowd when he was introduced in the third
quarter. ... Johnson will accompany the Suns on their four-game
road trip and may play at Miami on Tuesday. ... The Suns are 30-6
at home. ... Phoenix has beaten the Warriors 10 consecutive times
at America West Arena. ... The Suns were 0-for-12 from 3-point
range.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
