</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000327.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 01:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Hopes To Revive Mideast Talks  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration says it still hopes
to revive stalled peace talks between Syria and Israel, including
reaching out to Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak for help. But the
failure of President Clinton and Syrian President Hafez Assad to
make progress is casting fresh doubts on the prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ''Significant differences remain and were not narrowed,'' White
House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Sunday, expressing the
administration's disappointment after three hours of talks between
the two presidents in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's Middle East adviser, Dennis Ross, was heading to
Israel today to brief Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak on the
session. The president called Barak before and after the meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had stopped in Geneva on his way home from a 10-day tour
of South Asia hoping that personal diplomacy could produce
something that two months of private negotiations had not: a
breakthrough to permit the talks, stalled since January, to resume.
</P>
<P>
   When the inconclusive meeting ended, Clinton headed quickly for
the airport -- leaving Lockhart behind to face reporters. Had there
been an agreement to announce, the president was expected to make
it himself.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't believe it would be productive'' for Syrian-Israeli
talks to resume at this point, Lockhart said. ''It is impossible to
predict when those talks might resume.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the president understands that the differences that
remain are significant,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Syrian spokesman Jubran Kourieh said that during the talks,
Assad stressed the importance of Syria's longstanding demand for an
Israeli pullback to the country's 1967 borders.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders discussed pending issues and the peace process and
the ''obstacles that Israel has put up and is still putting up,''
Kourieh said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Since yesterday, nothing earth-shattering happened in the
peace process,'' he said. ''At the same time, no one put down any
goals that were not realized.'' He did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   In Jerusalem, Israeli Deputy Defense Minister Ephraim Sneh said
in a telephone interview that the main sticking point in Geneva was
Syria's demand for a prior commitment to cede the strategic Golan
Heights plateau.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact that Syria insists upon dictating an agreement and
not obtaining an agreed-upon agreement is what made the resumption
of the talks impossible,'' Sneh said. ''They are quite intransigent
about what they are supposed to give in terms of security
arrangements, and they have different ideas about normalization.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to seal his eight-year presidency with a Middle East
peace deal covering the entire region, Clinton has been pressing
hard to arrange a land-for-peace deal between Israel and Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Under the broad outlines, Israel would give up a strategic
border enclave, the Golan Heights, in exchange for a peace treaty
and a normalizing of relations.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations for the Geneva session had been high, partly
because the 69-year-old Assad rarely travels and flew to Geneva
especially to see Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Clinton sees Egypt's Mubarak as perhaps the last best
chance for getting the Israel-Syria peace talks back on track,
administration officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak, who has been in Washington since Friday, will meet with
Clinton on Tuesday and also plans to confer with Vice President Al
Gore and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are leaders within the region that play an important
role. President Mubarak is clearly one of those,'' White House
spokesman Lockhart said. ''So, I suspect that an important part of
the discussion on Tuesday with President Mubarak would be a
discussion of how we move this process forward.''
</P>
<P>
   After U.S.-brokered talks between Israel and Syria in
Shepherdstown, W.Va., broke down in mid-January, the administration
turned to secret diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   Syria wants Israel to withdraw to its boundaries before the 1967
Six-Day War. That would include patches of land that were within
Israel's international border, but which Syria captured in 1951 --
and would also allow Syria access to the Sea of Galilee, a source
of Israel's precious water supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's Barak has signaled his willingness to surrender at
least some of the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's session was the first full-scale talks between Clinton
and Assad since 1994. The two leaders met at a luxury hotel
overlooking Lake Geneva.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
