<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chaplains Long Presence in Congress  </HEADLINE>
By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The chaplains of the House and the Senate are
trustees of one of the oldest traditions in the American
experiment. But even a venerable institution can raise a dust
storm.
</P>
<P>
   Such a storm whipped through the House this winter, propelled by
hotly denied accusations that anti-Catholic bias swayed the
Republican leadership to select a Protestant clergyman as the
chamber's 59th chaplain.
</P>
<P>
   A Roman Catholic priest had been considered the front-runner by
many and the storm burst when he was bypassed.
</P>
<P>
   ''All hell -- perhaps all Hell -- has broken loose,'' columnist
William Safire wrote in The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   There hasn't been anything to match this clamor in all the years
since 1789 when the House and Senate -- following even older
precedents -- started appointing chaplains to pray for divine
guidance.
</P>
<P>
   The fracas was plastered over last week after four months of
partisan acrimony.
</P>
<P>
   The original choice, the Rev. Charles Wright, a Presbyterian
minister, stepped aside. Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., who
accused House Democrats of exploiting the controversy in ''an
unseemly political game,'' quickly appointed the Rev. Daniel
Coughlin, a Catholic priest from Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   When he was sworn in Thursday, Coughlin became the first
Catholic to be named House chaplain. In 211 years, the Senate has
elected a Catholic chaplain just once, in 1832.
</P>
<P>
   The question of a chaplain of one faith praying for legislators
of many religious traditions rose early in American history.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1774, Sam Adams of Massachusetts proposed that each
session of the new Continental Congress be opened with prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Objections were raised, but John Adams, a cousin, responded: ''I
am no bigot. I can hear prayers from a man of piety and virtue, who
is at the same time a friend of his country.''
</P>
<P>
   Some historians say there were political as well as spiritual
motives. John Adams told friends that ''a respectable Anglican
priest'' would be useful to demonstrate the legitimacy of the
Congress and ''to hurl psalm verse at the British.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon afterward, the Rev. Jacob Duche, the Episcopal pastor of
Philadelphia's Christ Church, was opening the Congress with prayer
and pelting the British with scripture.
</P>
<P>
   On July 8, 1776, just days after the Declaration of Independence
was adopted, Duche prayed for divine aid for ''our American states,
who have fled to thee from the rod of the oppressor.''
</P>
<P>
   When the House of Representatives met for the first time in
1789, its members chose the Rev. William Lynn, a Presbyterian, as
their first chaplain. The Senate elected Samuel Provoost, the
Episcopal bishop of New York, who then offered prayers at George
Washington's presidential inaugural.
</P>
<P>
   Chaplains continued their prayerful duties when the government
moved to Washington in 1800.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-four years later, responding to criticism that the
chaplains breached the constitutional wall separating church and
state, the House Judiciary Committee declared them indispensable.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there be a God who hears prayer -- as we believe there is --
we submit there was never a deliberative body that so eminently
needed the righteous prayers of righteous men as the Congress of
the United States,'' the committee observed.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1900s, Senate chaplain Edward Everett Hale, a
Unitarian, was asked whether, in light of the state of the country,
he prayed for the senators. ''No,'' came the famous reply. ''I look
at the senators and pray for the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Peter Marshall, perhaps the most famous congressional
chaplain in the 20th century, was profiled in the book and movie,
''A Man Called Peter.'' In opening a prayer in the late 1940s, he
said before senators: ''Forgive us for making so many mountains out
of molehills, and for exaggerating our own importance and the
problems that confront us.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, the late chaplain Richard C. Halverson prayed for
virtually everyone in the extended Senate family: the youthful
pages, the Capitol police, the cafeteria workers, the reporters
taking notes and the people who emptied the trash and cleaned
senators' offices.
</P>
<P>
   And of course he prayed for senators, too. ''Guide them in these
critical hours that they will do nothing that they will later
regret,'' Halverson once said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, after atheists filed a lawsuit contending that the laws
passed by Congress to pay and maintain its chaplains were
unconstitutional, the House voted 388-0 to support the practice of
naming a chaplain as one of its officers.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Rep. Tom Foley, D-Wash, a co-author of the
save-the-chaplain resolution, Speaker Thomas P. O'Neill Jr. told
the House: ''Tom and I are good Catholics and we're prepared to go
to jail to defend our Lutheran chaplain.''
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court made that unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clearly the men who wrote the ... religion clause did not view
paid legislative chaplains and opening prayers as a violation,''
Chief Justice Warren Burger wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The practice of opening congressional sessions with prayer has
''continued without interruption'' and become ''part of the fabric
of our society,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Lawrence L. Knutson has reported on the White
House, Congress and the history of Washington for more than 30
years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-27-00 0142 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
