<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Plan Would Create House Fund  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA SOBIERAJ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore is proposing new
campaign finance reforms -- a ''Democracy Endowment'' and strict
disclosure rules -- in his effort to attract John McCain supporters
and inoculate himself against George W. Bush's repeated attacks on
Gore's past fund-raising abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who said he was putting campaign reform front-and-center
in his Democratic presidential race after reform proponents McCain
and Bill Bradley dropped out, planned to unveil his plan at a
campaign appearance today in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   He was calling for creation of a $7.1 billion endowment to pay
for House and Senate campaigns, new disclosure rules for lobbyists
and outside groups that pay for political ads, and mandatory free
''rebuttal'' air time for candidates targeted by such third-party
ads.
</P>
<P>
   The package is meant to ''break the link between money and
political influence,'' according to a draft of the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   The measures amount to, in equal parts, a drive for
reform-minded independents who had supported McCain in the
Republican primaries and a pre-emptive strike against Texas Gov.
Bush, the presumed GOP nominee who has already made Gore's
fund-raising record a hot campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
   In an excerpt of Gore's speech text provided to The Washington
Post and The New York Times, Gore acknowledges his potential
credibility problem, given fund-raising tactics in 1996 that he has
called ''mistakes.'' They include participation in a fund raiser at
a Buddhist temple and the use of White House telephones in
soliciting campaign cash.
</P>
<P>
   ''I understand the doubts about whether I personally am serious
on campaign reform,'' Gore says in the draft speech. ''And I
understand all too well the irony of our current fund-raising
system. Men and women of good intentions and high ideals want to
protect the public interest but have to raise private money in
order to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Russell Feingold, D-Wis., cosponsor with McCain of major
campaign finance legislation pending before Congress, was expected
to be at the vice president's side for the announcement at
Marquette University.
</P>
<P>
   Gore would pledge to make the long-stalled bill, which bans
unlimited ''soft money'' donations that corporations and labor
unions give to political parties, the first piece of domestic
legislation he submits to Congress as president, a campaign aide
said late Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has long supported the bill, but many Republicans,
including Bush, contend it would unfairly help Democrats because
unions still could spend members' dues money on anti-GOP ads.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore aide, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
so-called Democracy Endowment is designed to function like a
university endowment. Businesses and individuals would receive a
100 percent tax deduction for contributions that would pay for
House and Senate general election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates receiving funds from the endowment could not accept
money from other sources.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is consistent with Gore's long support for taxpayer
financing of federal campaigns. Aides projected that a $7.1 billion
fund could be built over seven years, with interest on the
principal generating the money for congressional candidates in the
eighth year.
</P>
<P>
   Another proposal is specifically aimed at an issue that cropped
up with great controversy during Bush's nasty primary fight with
McCain. Two Texas brothers and prominent Bush supporters, Sam and
Charles Wyly, spent some $2.5 million on ads in key states
attacking the Arizona senator's environmental record.
</P>
<P>
   Bush denied any connection with or prior knowledge of the ads.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's proposed new rules would require public identification of
those paying for any political ad that airs within 60 days of
Election Day and, in the case of an organization-paid ad, the names
of the group's financial backers.
</P>
<P>
   Tax-exempt political groups such as the National Abortion and
Reproductive Rights Action League, which already plans a
pro-Democratic ad campaign, would be required to file ''statements
of organization'' disclosing their donor lists.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Gore proposal, lobbyists also would be required to
make monthly disclosures -- posted on the Internet -- of all their
lobbying contacts, what topics they discussed and what political
contributions they made.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-27-00 0144 </TRAILER>
