<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 01:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diana's bodyguard moves on  </HEADLINE>
By SHARON L. CRENSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- It's easy to like Trevor Rees-Jones, rugby
player, weekend beer-drinker, a guy who seems to make friends
easily and keep them a long time.
</P>
<P>
   The only person to live through the wreck that killed Princess
Diana, he is at last telling his story. Having shunned
million-dollar tabloid offers, he waited more than two years to
publish ''The Bodyguard's Story: Diana, the Crash, and the Sole
Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   Readers beware: This is not the spicy tell-all of Princess Di's
romance with Egyptian suitor Dodi Fayed.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it is the story of a simple, hardworking man, who took
his job seriously and played hard on his time off, volunteered to
work overtime for a buddy and wound up physically shattered. It is
the story of a few days in the company of the world's most
photographed woman and the frightening tale of how three minutes
can change a family's life.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers nothing after driver Henri Paul, who was legally
drunk, pulled the blue Mercedes carrying Diana, Fayed, and Trevor
away from the Hotel Ritz in Paris and sped toward the tunnel where
three of the four were killed.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time Trevor was desperate to remember, for himself,
for ''the Boss'' (Dodi's father, Egyptian millionaire Mohamed Al
Fayed) and yes, for the world. But he has given up now.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you think about it too much, you think about 'if onlys' and
what could have gone on and what has happened. You know, you go mad
doing that,'' he told The Associated Press in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Now he thinks whatever is locked in his mind about the accident
is destined to stay there, probably because the crash disrupted the
brain activity that would have put the details in long-term memory.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever might come to him now, doctors tell him, would likely
be tainted by all he has read and seen on television about the
early morning hours of Aug. 31, 1997, the morning Diana, Princess
of Wales, died.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only thing I'd put me name by now if I had to stand up in
court would be what I said to the judge on that first meeting in
(the) hospital, from the intensive care,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the book, his answer to the judge's first question
set the tone of the interview:
</P>
<P>
   ''I remember getting into this car, and I do not remember
anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   What is amazing about Trevor's story is his own physical
recovery, and the way his hometown, his mother, stepfather and one
friend in particular sheltered him from the pressure of superrich
Mohammed Al Fayed, the British and French governments and a legion
of media.
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived at the Paris hospital where he would spend the
first few weeks after the accident, he was so seriously disfigured
his mother, Jill, recognized only his legs and rugby-battered ears.
</P>
<P>
   Every bone in his face was broken, the eyes pushed from one to
two inches apart, the jaw dislocated in a way the doctors had never
even read about. Skin flapped freely from his cheek. The nose
pushed flush with the rest of his face.
</P>
<P>
   When the reconstructive surgeon operated, he found ''a landscape
of fractured, free-floating bones and bone debris, of teeth cracked
and skewed crazily from their orderly rows. It was mush.''
</P>
<P>
   And it was happenstance that he wound up at the center of it
all. He was supposed to be off the week leading up to the accident,
but volunteered to take the place of a fellow bodyguard who didn't
want to make the trip with Dodi.
</P>
<P>
   Today some scars remain, but a passerby wouldn't look twice. The
left eyelid is a little bumpy. There's a shallow, jagged line
across the top lip and left cheek. It could be from rugby.
</P>
<P>
   Rubbing his hand across his face, Trevor says it feels a little
like he's wearing a Phantom of the Opera mask. The wrist he broke
in three places gets sore sometimes, and his back stiffens up on
occasion. The long-term worry is arthritis, but other than that,
he's normal.
</P>
<P>
   The dreams have stopped, he's working in security again and just
bought a new two-bedroom Victorian house in his hometown of
Oswestry, England. When strangers show up looking for him,
neighbors run interference until they can call Trevor and figure
out if the visitor is another intrusive reporter.
</P>
<P>
   There's a new girlfriend, too, though he's clearly protective of
her identity. He says he's not even thinking about marriage at this
stage, left gun-shy, perhaps, by the divorce that was already in
process when the accident happened. (His ex-wife sold her story to
the News of the World six months after the crash. ''That didn't
help Trev. He no longer trusted anyone,'' stepfather Ernie Jones
recalls in the book.)
</P>
<P>
   It's still hard to trust.
</P>
<P>
   Mohamed Al Fayed turned on him after Trevor said once and for
all he could not collaborate Fayed's theory that Diana and his son
were the victims of a conspiracy by the British royal family. Then
Al Fayed lashed out at the bodyguards -- both Trevor and Alexander
Wingfield, the other man assigned to protect Dodi and Diana on
their last night.
</P>
<P>
   Wingfield, known by the nickname ''Kez,'' has since left Al
Fayed's operation and helped write ''The Bodyguard's Story.'' He
and Trevor were in New York last week promoting the book together.
They settled somewhat uncomfortably in a posh suite at Le Parker
Meridian hotel in Manhattan, and ran a four-day media blitz, their
only planned publicity.
</P>
<P>
   Trevor described the pampering as ''unnatural'' for the two of
them. Kez said he worried about tidying up before the maid came.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's quite bizarre, really,'' he said with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   Both men are hoping the book will put away their part of the
Diana story. But the experience has bound them together. Trevor is
even hoping to hire Kez as part of the security force he's working
on for a new employer.
</P>
<P>
   It's guys like Kez who have kept this well-known, unknown person
sane.
</P>
<P>
   ''People at home, people that matter to me -- that's family, and
Kez, my mates back home -- you know, they knew us before we were
involved in all this,'' Trevor said. ''If you start to get your
feet above your station, they'll soon pull you down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-27-00 0145 </TRAILER>
