<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 02:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, beset by drugs, enlists help from New York rehab program  </HEADLINE>
By LUKAS I. ALPERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Faced with a flourishing drug trade and an
increasing number of addicts, the People's Republic of China has
been forced to look for new methods to battle drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
   And in a twist in its warming relations with the United States,
the Communist nation's search led it to the capital of capitalism,
New York City, where Daytop Village has gained praise for its drug
and alcohol rehabilitation center.
</P>
<P>
   The addiction problem has forced the normally ideological
Chinese government to become more pragmatic. Monsignor William B.
O'Brien said this was apparent in his first dealings with China's
health officials.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were overwhelmed but honest enough to say, 'We don't know
what to do,'' explained O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   Since the days of the Communist takeover in 1949, when parts of
China were swamped with opium addicts, the formula for tackling the
drug problem has been much the same: locking up addicts in
military-style camps to break their habit.
</P>
<P>
   But what little statistics are available showed the old ways
didn't work. Chinese authorities report the number of known addicts
has been cut by 23 percent since 1991. But that still left 596,000
registered addicts in 1998, the latest year for which statistics
were available, and independent researchers say the number of
addicts is likely much higher.
</P>
<P>
   China's southernmost province of Yunnan lies along the route
from Southeast Asia's Golden Triangle, a major source of illegal
drugs, and Yunnan has been stung by wrenching economic reforms --
all of which have contributed to a major drug problem.
</P>
<P>
   After traveling within the province, O'Brien said, ''We realized
that the kids we met there were just like the kids we had met in
the United States and were faced with similar problems.
</P>
<P>
   ''People don't realize that China is not so different from here
so families there are really dealing with a lot of the same
problems,'' O'Brien said.
</P>
<P>
   Daytop Village, which operates 25 centers in the United States,
has been instrumental in the development of substance abuse centers
on the world and in training councilors in new approaches to
treatment. China first consulted the organization in 1989 and has
since adapted its programs on a widespread basis.
</P>
<P>
   ''Daytop helped give us direction and a good plan,'' said Yuan
Xiaobo, the executive director of the Yunnan Institute for Drug
Abuse, a center that opened in January under the tutelage of
Daytop.
</P>
<P>
   The center, based in Yunnan's capital of Kunming, is the first
of its kind in China, and health officials hope that it may become
the model for other centers around the country, Yuan said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Daytop has helped train over 500 counselors in
China as well as 11 more in the United States on new approaches to
treatment and prevention of drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the boot-camp method previously used, the new Daytop
model stresses addicts taking responsibility and confronting their
feelings. It slowly reintroduces recovering addicts to the outside
world.
</P>
<P>
   The program focuses on a family style atmosphere with a
hierarchical structure.
</P>
<P>
   ''The most important focus of this program is that on the family
structure,'' O'Brien said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Daytop literature, recovering addicts work under
staff supervision to clean their quarters, cook meals and confront
each other when they make mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Through the structure, the recovering addict learns how to
function drug free and to work and behave on the job.
</P>
<P>
   ''By focusing on the structures of the family, the program helps
those afflicted get the confidence to lead drug free lives,''
O'Brien said.
</P>
<P>
   With the addition of the center in Kunming, Daytop's method has
been used to train counselors in 59 facilities around the world.
</P>
<P>
   And clearly the need is there. Many of those in training at
Daytop's New York center are from countries not thought of as
having major drug problems, such as the Maldives, Indonesia and
Malaysia. But these countries are hit with the problem because they
serve as transit points for narcotics smuggling networks.
</P>
<P>
   Faisal N. Afdhal, who operates a drug treatment facility in
Jakarta, Indonesia, said he was particularly attracted to the
Daytop method because ''the program is not just about stopping
using drugs, but to improve the quality of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Others said that resources in their country often are used for
stopping smuggling but that money for treatment and training is
limited.
</P>
<P>
   ''This will really be helpful for us,'' Abdullah Faseeh of the
Maldives said of the Daytop training. ''As a small country, we
don't have the great universities and many trained people, so
getting a chance like this is a real help.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-27-00 0200 </TRAILER>
