<HEADLINE> 'King Gimp' Wins Best Documentary  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- When ''King Gimp'' was announced the winner
for best documentary short at the Academy Awards Sunday, the
writer, Dan Keplinger, rocked with joy in his wheelchair in the
Shrine Auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   In the film, Keplinger chronicles his battle with cerebral
palsy, from childhood until his early 20s.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have followed Dan Keplinger for 13 years. He's an amazing
spirit in a body that society may not have included,'' Susan Hannah
Hadary, one of the producers, said in accepting the award.
</P>
<P>
   ''But tonight he is included and he's honored as an artist and
we thank the academy for giving him this honor,'' she said, nearly
in tears.
</P>
<P>
   Director and co-producer William A. Whiteford added, ''Dan's
spirit touches us all.''
</P>
<P>
   Thrown over his mother's shoulder or pushed in a wheelchair,
Keplinger goes everywhere and does it all. But he truly enters the
world when he discovers art, a way to communicate his emotions.
</P>
</TEXT>
