<HEADLINE> Poll Gets Most Oscar Winners Right  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A Wall Street Journal survey that angered the
Motion Picture Academy by polling voters correctly predicted all
but one of the top Oscar winners.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal narrowly picked Denzel Washington in ''The
Hurricane'' for best actor, but Kevin Spacey took the Oscar Sunday
for ''American Beauty.'' The Journal accurately predicted
''American Beauty'' for best picture, Hilary Swank for best
actress, Sam Mendes for best director, Michael Caine for best
supporting actor, and Angelina Jolie for best supporting actress.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper predicted winners after polling 356 of 5,607
voting members of the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences.
Many of the voters polled asked to remain anonymous, but several
openly discussed their picks.
</P>
<P>
   The Academy urged its members not to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Stevens, entertainment editor of the Weekend Journal, said
the survey was simply a way to explore the voting process for
readers. ''We make no claims to scientific accuracy,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
