<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda Rulers Eliminate Opposition  </HEADLINE>
By HRVOJE HRANJSKI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIGALI, Rwanda (AP) -- Political assassinations, army desertions
and a growing opposition pose the latest challenge to Rwanda, where
the behind-the-scenes rulers have again showed they are not yet
ready to tolerate dissent for fear of letting the country slip into
turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   President Pasteur Bizimungu's recent resignation was only the
latest in a long line of departures of both Hutu and Tutsi
politicians who have voiced opposition to the power in Rwanda being
concentrated in the hands of a select few.
</P>
<P>
   The handful of young military leaders who run the country --
impoverished and traumatized by the 1994 genocide that left more
than 500,000 Tutsis and politically moderate Hutus dead -- follow a
Spartan discipline and are committed to national reconciliation and
free-market economics, but not to outright democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The government is struggling to build a consensus among bitter
Tutsi genocide survivors, the majority Hutu population -- who
largely feel ostracized -- and almost a million Tutsi returnees who
spent more than 30 years in exile in Uganda, Burundi, Tanzania and
Congo. The diaspora returned with different languages, mentalities
and social customs.
</P>
<P>
   Security -- established only recently after years of Hutu rebel
attacks -- has given rise to a political opposition, coming
unexpectedly from the Tutsi genocide survivors who feel excluded
from power by the Tutsi returnees and the Hutu business elite, some
of whom have links to extremists responsible for the genocide.
</P>
<P>
   The genocide survivors want a complete break with Hutu political
parties in the government and parliament, swift justice for 125,000
jailed genocide suspects, including public executions, an apology
and financial compensation.
</P>
<P>
   But the inner circle of Maj. Gen. Paul Kagame -- the former rebel
commander, vice president, minister of defense, and undisputed No.
1 politician in Rwanda -- has not tolerated such demands.
</P>
<P>
   Kagame led the Tutsi-dominated Rwandan Patriotic Front from the
refugee camps where they grew up in neighboring Uganda to eventual
victory over the former government in July 1994. His troops stopped
the 100-day genocide orchestrated by the former extremist Hutu
government.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the RPF officially shares power with a half-dozen
other political parties, Kagame now has the real authority.
</P>
<P>
   Supported by the United States and other Western governments,
the RPF has been running a social laboratory, carefully balancing
the different groups vying for power. Yet critics say the RPF has
either tried to silence opponents or send them into exile.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Sebarenzi Kabuye, a popular Tutsi and former speaker of
the National Assembly, fled in January after he was accused of
planning the return of the exiled Tutsi monarch to challenge
Kagame.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, another prominent survivor and presidential adviser,
Assiel Kabera, was gunned down in front of his house in downtown
Kigali, apparently by men in uniform. No arrests have been made.
</P>
<P>
   The government has been equally harsh with its Hutu opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, parliament became the weapon for attacking ministers
and legislators suspected of graft and mismanagement. The first to
go were three Hutu ministers and former Prime Minister
Pierre-Celestin Rwigema, also a Hutu, who resigned on Feb. 28 on
charges of corruption.
</P>
<P>
   All were political survivors of the late Hutu President Juvenal
Habyarimana's government.
</P>
<P>
   Bizimungu, a 49-year-old Hutu technocrat who made a personal
fortune before he fell out with Habyarimana in 1990, accused
parliament of selectively going after Hutus -- an explosive
allegation in the country where ethnicity is often used as a
political tool.
</P>
<P>
   But his speech attracted little sympathy and only exposed him to
allegations that he was trying to hinder an anti-graft campaign
that RPF leaders promised would spare no one, Hutus or Tutsis. The
allegations led to his resignation, but again demonstrated the
RPF's intolerance of dissent .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
