<DOCNO> APW20000327.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 05:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Erin Brockovich' Leads Box Office  </HEADLINE>
By MICHELLE DeARMOND, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- With Hollywood's eyes on a guy named Oscar, a
gal named ''Erin Brockovich'' quietly captured the top box office
spot for the second week in a row.
</P>
<P>
   The legal drama starring Julia Roberts grossed an estimated $19
million for the weekend, closely followed by the newly released
action film ''Romeo Must Die'' with $18.6 million, according to
studio estimates released Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Academy Award-winning films ''American Beauty'' and ''The Cider
House Rules'' benefitted from an ''Oscar bounce'' as moviegoers
rushed to see the films before Sunday's annual Academy Awards
ceremony, said Paul Dergarabedian, president of Exhibitor Relations
Co. Inc., which tracks movie attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ''American Beauty'' pulled in $3.9 million in the No. 7 spot,
bringing its cumulative earnings to $108.4 million. ''Cider House''
grossed an estimated $2.8 million in ninth for a cumulative gross
of $49.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   ''American Beauty'' dominated the Oscars, taking the best
picture award. The film's star, Kevin Spacey, won for best actor
and Sam Mendes won best director. ''Beauty'' also won for original
screenplay and for cinematography.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Caine, the kindly orphanage headmaster in ''The Cider
House Rules,'' won an Oscar for best supporting actor. The film
also earned the best adapted screenplay Oscar for John Irving.
</P>
<P>
   ''Erin Brockovich'' is based on the real-life story of a
California woman who took a clerical job with a legal firm and
uncovered a pollution scandal involving Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric Co.
Brockovich led a crusade for 650 residents whose water was
contaminated by the utility and won a $333 million settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a film that certainly is benefitting from great word of
mouth,'' Dergarabedian said. ''There's no question this is a crowd
pleaser.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Erin Brockovich'' has grossed a cumulative $56.3 million in
its two weeks of release and is the second all-time top-grossing
film for March. ''Liar, Liar'' from 1997 holds the record for the
month.
</P>
<P>
   The second place ''Romeo'' is a tale of Asian and black gang
families vying for control of an American waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   The horror story ''Final Destination,'' a tale of teen-agers
stalked by death, was third for its second week in release with
$7.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Two films that competed -- along with ''Final Destination'' -- for
the teen market opened in the fifth and sixth box office slots.
''Here on Earth'' grossed an estimated $4.6 million, followed by
''Whatever it Takes'' with $4.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Estimated ticket sales for Friday through Sunday at North
American theaters, according to Exhibitor Relations. Final figures
were to be released today.
</P>
<P>
   1. ''Erin Brockovich,'' $19 million.
</P>
<P>
   2. ''Romeo Must Die,'' $18.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   3. ''Final Destination,'' $7.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   4. ''Mission to Mars,'' $5.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   5. ''Here on Earth,'' $4.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   6. ''Whatever it Takes,'' $4.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   7. ''American Beauty,'' $3.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   8. ''My Dog Skip,'' $3.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   9. ''The Cider House Rules,'' $2.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   10. ''The Whole Nine Yards,'' $2.1 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
