<HEADLINE> Columbine Gun Supplier To Appeal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- The man who sold a gun to the Columbine High
School killers plans to appeal his six-year sentence, saying he did
not know how they planned to use it.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Phil Cherner filed a notice with the Colorado Court of
Appeals of intent to appeal Mark Manes' sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think it is excessive,'' Cherner said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson County District Judge Henry Nieto made fundamental
errors in sentencing Manes in November, Cherner said.
</P>
<P>
   Manes, 23, deserved a lighter sentence because he had no idea
how Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold intended to use the semiautomatic
TEC-DC9 handgun he sold them, Cherner said. With the gun and other
weapons, they killed 13 people at the high school before committing
suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Manes pleaded guilty in August to supplying a weapon to a minor.
He had sold the handgun to the killers for $500 in January 1999,
three months before the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson County's probation department had recommended a
lengthy probation rather than prison. But Nieto said during the
Nov. 12 sentencing that selling the gun was intrinsically tied to
the consequences at Columbine High.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
