<HEADLINE> 78 Million People Watch Oscars  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- An estimated 78 million Americans watched at
least some of the lengthy Academy Awards telecast, with overnight
ratings drooping slightly from last year, Nielsen Media Research
said today.
</P>
<P>
   The Oscar telecast drew a 31.7 rating and 48 audience share,
down 1 percent from its overnight ratings the year before.
</P>
<P>
   The overnight ratings measure the audience in 47 markets metered
by Nielsen, comprising two-thirds of the country. Full national
ratings are due later this afternoon, and they tend to be lower
than in the big cities.
</P>
<P>
   With ''American Beauty'' and its lead actor, Kevin Spacey,
winning the big awards, the Oscar telecast stretched to more than
four hours. That came despite promises from producers to move
things along.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 show's ratings were itself a dropoff of 21 percent from
the year before, when ''Titanic'' swept the awards. The Oscars are
traditionally the highest-rated entertainment special of the year,
with fluctuations in viewership dependent on the popularity of its
honored movies.
</P>
<P>
   ''Anytime you can get a 31.7 rating, where a third of the
country is tuning in to your program and watching your commercials,
we're happy,'' said Larry Hyams, ABC's chief researcher.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
