<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oscar Brings Joy to Farming Town  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM BROWN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain (AP) -- Spanish director Pedro Almodovar's Oscar
won tears of joy from his aunt, congratulations from Barcelona's
mayor and a sleepless night for the small farmtown where he was
born.
</P>
<P>
   Almodovar's Oscar for Best Foreign Language Film for ''All About
My Mother, ''made me cry, laugh and scream,'' said Cecilia
Almodovar, the director's elderly aunt in Calzada de Calatrava, the
farming community of 5,000 people where Almodovar was born.
</P>
<P>
   Cecilia, one of 11 sibling of Almodovar's recently-deceased
mother, said she stayed awake all night to watch the awards
ceremonies along with many other residents of the town located 100
miles south of Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   She told state news agency Efe that she expects a visit from her
nephew later this week and will accompany him to pay respects to
the patron saint of the town.
</P>
<P>
   Almodovar on Sunday became the 10th Spaniard to win an Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   The last Oscar for a Spaniard, also for Best Foreign Language
Film, came in 1994 for director Fernando Trueba and his ''Belle
Epoque.''
</P>
<P>
   Almodovar's films were the first to register success outside of
Spain after the 1975 death of dictator Gen. Francisco Franco
ushered in democracy and a resurgence of the arts.
</P>
<P>
   Spanish State Secretary for Culture Miguel Angel Cortes
predicted the Oscar would ''give a boost to Spanish cinema outside
of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Cortes said the award ''recognizes (Almodovar's) talent as a
director as well as the talent of the whole team that made it
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Joan Clos the mayor of Barcelona -- where the film is set -- sent
Almodovar a letter of congratulations. The mayor had earlier
expressed hopes that the film could boost his city's international
reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after the awards, which were broadcast after 2 a.m. in
Spain, prominent Spaniards sent Almodovar telegrams of
congratulations while radio and television buzzed with the news.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
