<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 12:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Than 25 Bombs Hit South Sudan  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) -- The Sudanese government bombed two
civilian hospitals in rebel-held areas of southern Sudan last week,
rebels and aid agencies said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Gideon Gatele, logistics officer for U.S.-based aid group,
Samaritan's Purse, said up to 14 bombs aimed at a hospital the
organization runs in Lui, 85 miles northwest of Juba, were dropped
on March 22 and 23.
</P>
<P>
   Juba is the largest town in southern Sudan still under
government control.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth time the hospital has been targeted this year,
Gatele told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's (the bombing) all in the same region and looks like
systematic bombing or targeting,'' he said. ''It could be a prelude
to more fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   Gatele said the bombs in the latest attack missed the 120-bed
hospital and there were no casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Sudanese authorities were unavailable for comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Eight bombs were also dropped on a camp for displaced people in
Kotobi on Friday, another eight targeted a hospital in Tali on
Saturday, and an unknown number were dropped in Kaya and Morobo on
the Ugandan border during the last week, according to Samson Kwaje,
spokesman for the Sudan People's Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   Kwaje said the hospital in Tali, 80 miles north of Juba, is run
by ZOA Refugee Care, a Dutch organization. He said there were no
details of casualties, but people in Tali had been told to evacuate
the town. It was not immediately possible to contact ZOA.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Aloo, security officer for Norwegian People's Aid, which
has a food relief camp in Tali, confirmed the bombing and said a
pregnant woman was killed in the attack.
</P>
<P>
   In Uganda, Capt. Shaban Bantariza, a spokesman for the Ugandan
army, told The Associated Press that Sudanese government bombs had
also landed on the East African country's territory.
</P>
<P>
   Uganda broke diplomatic relations with Sudan in 1994, accusing
it of aiding rebels fighting in northern Uganda and others
operating from mountain bases in western Uganda and eastern Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Sudan says Uganda has supported the Sudan People's Liberation
Army, which is fighting for increased autonomy in Sudan's
predominantly Christian and animist south. Nearly 2 million people
have died in Sudan's 17-year civil war and another 4 million have
been uprooted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-27-00 1219 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000327.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 12:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Search Ends for Two Teens in Pacific  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHELTER COVE, Calif. (AP) -- The Coast Guard on Monday called off
its search for two Canadian teen-age boys who tried to rescue a
woman after she was swept into the frigid Pacific and drowned.
</P>
<P>
   There had been no signs of the boys in the 48-degree water since
the incident Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The ocean is unpredictable, and there's no way to know where
they may surface,'' Coast Guard Petty Officer Michael Burgess said.
</P>
<P>
   The victims were part of a group of 18 students and six adults
who had traveled from William Aberhart High School in Calgary,
Alberta, to hike along the isolated coast 220 miles north of San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Clement, 45, was caught by a wave and pulled out to sea.
The two 17-year-old students, David Elton and Brodie Macdonald,
jumped into the water to try to rescue her.
</P>
<P>
   A few moments later, teacher Martin Poirier, 37, and a third
student, Jordan Nixon, 17, tried to rescue the boys and Clement.
</P>
<P>
   All four were captured by the powerful rip tide. Clement
drowned, while Poirier and Nixon were dragged out of the pounding
waves by fishermen. Macdonald and Elton were presumed dead.
</P>
<P>
   Locals said the stretch of beach is extremely dangerous because
of the strong undertow, rip currents and unpredictable waves.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's been vehicles washed off that beach,'' said Pete
Winkler, who was fishing for salmon when he heard the Coast Guard's
call for help and joined in the search.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
