<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 26 More Die in Sir Lanka Fighting  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) -- Tamil guerrillas launched an attack to
capture a strategic causeway linking the mainland with Jaffna
Peninsula, killing 11 soldiers and losing 15 fighters, an army
spokesman said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Another 23 soldiers were wounded in fighting that began Sunday
and continued to rage Monday, said Major J.D.A. Gunasekera, the
military spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Since November, the rebels have been trying to regain Jaffna,
which had served as their stronghold until the military took
control in 1996. Jaffna is linked to the mainland by the narrow
Elephant Pass causeway.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas pounded military positions with mortars and
artillery during the night Sunday. The navy destroyed two rebel
vessels that tried to reach the eastern shore of the peninsula,
said Gunasekera, the military spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, in a statement faxed from
their London office, said Sri Lankan troops suffered heavy
casualties.
</P>
<P>
   More than 61,000 people have been killed since the war erupted
in 1983. The guerrillas have been fighting for a separate homeland
for the minority Tamils, accusing the majority Sinhalese of
widespread discrimination in education and jobs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-27-00 1229 </TRAILER>
