<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sound Bites: Audio Reviews  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ''As Long As You're Living Yours: The Music of Keith Jarrett''
(RCA Victor) -- Various Artists
</P>
<P>
   Tribute recordings can squeeze the life out of the original
compositions, sometimes through over-interpretation, sometimes
through the wrong selection of artists and genres (just because you
could have a heavy metal interpretation of a Duke Ellington
standard is no reason to do so).
</P>
<P>
   ''As Long As You're Living Yours: The Music of Keith Jarrett''
mostly avoids the pitfalls to give some clever reworkings of music
from across Jarrett's vast catalog. One of the most prolific modern
20th century jazz composers and a pianist without parallel, Jarrett
is at home with any number of styles, from standards to
improvisational, classical and even sacred.
</P>
<P>
   ''As Long As You're Living Yours'' doesn't venture into
improvisational jazz, but does touch the classical. Violinist Nadja
Salerno-Sonnenberg teams with contemporary jazz pianist Bob James
for a beautiful reading of ''Book of Ways 9.''
</P>
<P>
   Other renditions of note include straight-ahead versions of
''Innocence'' by saxophonist George Garzone and ''Shades of Jazz''
by hornmen Joe Lovano and Tom Harrell; Nueva Rhumba's
Latin-flavored ''So Tender'' and pianist D.D. Jackson's soulful
take on ''Everything That Lives Laments.''
</P>
<P>
   -- By James Reindl, Associated Press Writer
</P>
<P>
   ''Love Stories'' (Columbia) -- Frank McComb
</P>
<P>
   My, my, my, what a joyful way to quench a thirst!
</P>
<P>
   Frank McComb's Columbia debut, ''Love Stories,'' is a slow-wine
salute to classic rhythm and blues, sprinkled with a little bit of
gospel and a hungry-man helping of jazz. Thoughtful and deeply
personal, this disc relies on the singer's talents, rather than
calling on the cheap give-it-to-me-baby/bump 'n' grind gimmicks
that dilute so many ''romantic'' tunes receiving airplay now.
There's not a ''sex sells'' parachute to soften the disc's landing;
the production stands on its own merits.
</P>
<P>
   McComb takes it to church on the introduction of ''Love
Stories,'' a sanctified rendition of ''His Eye is on the Sparrow''
anchored by his lush vocals, and a wisely muted piano that afford
the words space to breathe. When McComb rips up a funky cut (check
out ''They're Gonna Be Looking at You''), it's easy to have fun
with him. (Listen for a special treat at the end of a hidden track
on the disc, an all-too-brief but hilarious and dead-on Al Green
impersonation). Other songs like ''Listen to Your Heart,'' ''If
This is Love'' and ''Wasting Your Time'' are soft and romantic. The
understatement of these gems is a refreshing departure from some
abrasive mainstream hits.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most poignant offering here is the simple ''Wedding
Song.'' He's a young man, but McComb sounds mature when he sings
about the blessed union of a husband and wife. It's about pure
love, sans raunchy details.
</P>
<P>
   ''Love Stories'' is an elegant debut from a pure artist.
</P>
<P>
   -- Candice Y. Rigdon, Associated Press Writer
</P>
<P>
   ''The Big Bang! Best Of The MC5'' (Rhino) -- MC5
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, electric guitars provided the soundtrack for a
revolution. With a thunderous squall, they inspired the young and
terrified the establishment. Ah, those were the days.
</P>
<P>
   This compilation of 21 tunes by Detroit's MC5 (short for Motor
City Five) is a reminder that rock once mattered. Beginning with
its debut live album in 1969, the band played as though it believed
it really could change the world, which made the group naive but
fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   The MC5 made its initial splash as the house band for the
radical White Panther Party, which endorsed free material goods and
''the end of money.'' It's unclear how the band promoted such ideas
while trying to sell records, but at any rate the MC5 struggled
commercially and folded after three albums.
</P>
<P>
   Musically the approach was also radical but deceptively simple:
Combine Chuck Berry and James Brown with Sun Ra and crank the
guitars up to 11. The results have influenced punk, heavy metal and
rap groups ever since.
</P>
<P>
   The Rhino set starts with three early sides that had been out of
print for more than 30 years. There are four cuts from the wild,
feedback-filled live album ''Kick Out The Jams,'' preceded by the
greatest stage introduction in the history of entertainment. The
band's subsequent songs for two studio albums were tamer but even
better, because the performances were more focused and less
political. Such bids for the Top 40 as ''High School'' and
''Shakin' Street'' sound a lot cooler than just about anything on
the radio then -- or now.
</P>
<P>
   -- By Steven Wine, Associated Press Writer
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-27-00 1301 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000327.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hyundai Founder Picks Successor  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL SHIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- The founder of South Korea's largest
conglomerate endorsed his fifth son as his successor Monday, ending
a two-week long feud for control of the Hyundai group.
</P>
<P>
   Chung Ju-yung, 84, selected Mong-hun, 52, as head of Hyundai in
a departure from the Korean tradition of favoring the oldest son as
the successor to a family business.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was announced after two weeks of bickering between
Mong-hun and his oldest brother, Mong-ku, 62, both of whom claimed
to have been chosen as successor. The elder brother will head up
the group's auto units, Hyundai Motors Co. and Kia Motors Co.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the family feud was likely to speed the breakup of
Hyundai, which has $70 billion in assets and had $75 billion in
revenues last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''The feud illustrates how important and urgent a task it is to
reform an inefficient Korean business style,'' said Lee Woo-yong,
an economics professor at Sogang University.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea's family-owned businesses, or chaebol, had expanded
recklessly for decades with cheap bank loans in collusion with past
military-backed governments. A dozen of them went under in 1997 as
Korea's economy was hit by a financial crisis and an economic
slowdown.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking office in early 1998, President Kim Dae-jung has
pushed chaebol to adopt modern management methods, shed
money-losing subsidiaries and trim their debt.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting of dozens of chief executives of group subsidiaries
Monday, Chung Ju-yung announced that Mong-hun would take over the
reins of the company immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The row began when Mong-ku, then co-chairman of Hyundai, demoted
Lee Ik-chi, a close confidant of his rival brother. The move was
seen as his effort to gain control of the group.
</P>
<P>
   Hyundai's internal dispute attracted much public attention in
Korea and touched off fresh debate over what critics call an
undemocratic management style at the chaebol groups.
</P>
<P>
   ''It reveals that a representative conglomerate of the country
still remains under the control of one man, without setting in
motion a modern management system,'' the Chosun Ilbo, the nation's
largest daily newspaper, said in an editorial.
</P>
<P>
   Hyundai currently has 33 subsidiaries producing ships, cars,
computer chips and a host of other products. All of the
subsidiaries are controlled by the Chung family.
</P>
<P>
   Hyundai announced last year that by 2003, it will be broken into
five mini-groups specializing in cars, electronics, heavy
industries, construction and finance.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials said the conglomerate will now be split and
owned 70 percent by the fifth son, 20 percent by the oldest son and
10 percent by other Chung offspring.
</P>
<P>
   Major subsidiaries under the fifth son's domain will include
Hyundai Electronics Co., Hyundai Engineering and Construction Co.
and Hyundai Merchant and Marine Co.
</P>
<P>
   The shipbuilding arm, Hyundai Heavy Industries, is controlled by
Chung Ju-yung's sixth son, Mong-joon, a legislator and a vice
president of FIFA, the world's soccer governing body.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-27-00 1334 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000327.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Retrial of Ex-Detroit Cop Begins  </HEADLINE>
By JIM SUHR, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Rapping a heavy police flashlight on the jury box
for emphasis, a prosecutor said Monday that a white policeman
decided ''again and again and again'' to use his flashlight to beat
a black motorist on his head in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Malice Green, 35, suffered a seizure and died after he was hit
on the head at least 14 times.
</P>
<P>
   Two white officers, Larry Nevers and Walter Budzyn, were
convicted of second-degree murder in 1993. But their convictions
were overturned five months apart in 1997 -- in part because the
jury watched the movie ''Malcolm X'' -- which contains footage of
the Rodney King beating -- during a break in deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   Budzyn was retried and convicted in 1998 of involuntary
manslaughter and is free today after the judge sentenced him to
time served. Opening statements began Monday in Nevers' retrial.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Doug Baker said Nevers hit Green with his police
flashlight at least 10 times on the head.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not talking about some deadly split-second decision to
use police force. We're talking about a protracted beating where
the decision was made again and again and again to inflict the
blows to his head,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevers' attorney, Neil Fink, said Nevers responded with the
flashlight only after Green began struggling with Budzyn. Fink also
said Nevers used the flashlight in a ''flicking motion'' but did
not bludgeon Green as prosecutors contend.
</P>
<P>
   ''It might mess up your face but it was not designed to be fatal
force,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-27-00 1335 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000327.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush, Gore Embrace Fathers' Goals  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIGITTE GREENBERG
Associated Press Writer
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- George W. Bush always had to contend with his
father's sizable shadow and the mocking comparisons -- Junior,
little George. When Al Gore, the senator's son, returned home from
Vietnam, he announced that he wanted nothing to do with politics.
</P>
<P>
   Both rebelled, for a time. Both tried to compete with their dads
at other times. And both were profoundly affected -- perhaps even
motivated to run for the highest office in the land -- by their
fathers' disappointments.
</P>
<P>
   ''Had my dad won the presidency in '92, I would not have run for
governor in '94, and had I not run for governor in '94, it is very
unlikely I'd be sitting here,'' the Texas governor said this year.
</P>
<P>
   When Gore's father died two years ago at the age of 90, the vice
president recalled how his dad lost his Senate seat from Tennessee
largely because he opposed the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   ''My father was brave. I mean really brave,'' Gore said. ''The
night he lost -- in 1970 -- he made me prouder still. He said:
'Defeat may serve as well as victory to shake the soul and let the
glory out.' And then he turned the old Southern segregationist
slogan on its head and declared: 'The truth shall rise again.'''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Gurian, a family therapist who has written several books
about father-son relationships, said seeing a father humbled can
jolt a son into action.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's called redeeming the father,'' Gurian said. ''Any way
that the father's image has been sullied means that the son's image
has been sullied because the image of the father is the image of
the son.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarities in image weren't always so clear for the Bushes.
Years ago, the friction between them was palpable. The younger Bush
admittedly drank to excess, and one time, with his 15-year-old
brother, Marvin, in the car, he drove home inebriated.
</P>
<P>
   George W., 26 at the time, barreled into a neighbor's garbage
can and dragged the clanking metal can down the street, according
to a 1989 Time magazine account. When he stumbled through the front
door of his house, his father wanted to see him in the den --
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hear you're looking for me. You want to go mano a mano right
here?'' George W. reportedly said before younger brother, Jeb,
intervened to block a physical confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, on the other hand, didn't openly defy his taskmaster
father, but relatives and friends said he did feel pressured. Sen.
Albert Gore was known to dance around when his son earned good
grades, require his son to do 50 push-ups every morning, and wake
him at sunup to do chores.
</P>
<P>
   Gore usually rose to his father's challenges. Friends have said
he was so dutiful that he went to Vietnam to help his father's
foundering bid for re-election, even though he was opposed to the
war.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until he came home that he set out on his own path.
Rather than go into politics, he started religious studies and then
became a newspaper reporter. When he did go into the family
business -- politics -- by running for Congress in 1976, he tried to
distance himself from his father.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want people voting for me because I'm Albert Gore's
son,'' he told a friend at the time, according to the biography
''Inventing Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Gurian surmised that the presidential bids by Bush and Gore may,
in part, be driven by competition, a ''relentless pursuit of
parity'' with their fathers.
</P>
<P>
   ''The high achieving son generally attempts to equal or even
supplant the father,'' Gurian said, ''so hypothetically, Al Gore
has already achieved being a senator, so he will attempt to be
president, and George Bush will attempt to be president and stay
for two terms.''
</P>
<P>
   For George W., living up to his father's achievements was a
daunting proposition from the start. The elder Bush, himself the
son of a U.S. senator from Connecticut, was an academic dynamo and
baseball star at Phillips Academy and at Yale, where he was Phi
Beta Kappa, president of his fraternity, and a member of an
exclusive secret society.
</P>
<P>
   As a Navy fighter pilot in World War II, he won the
Distinguished Flying Cross after his plane was shot down southwest
of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   George W. was no scholar, no athlete and no war hero.
</P>
<P>
   He went to Andover and Yale, but his academic and athletic
careers were less than stellar. He was on the Yale baseball team,
but he warmed the bench. He distinguished himself so little in
class that professors barely remember him. During the Vietnam War,
he joined the Texas Air National Guard and flew fighter jets in his
home state.
</P>
<P>
   Like his dad, George W. was fraternity president, but his
reputation was built on an affinity for toga parties and beer. His
college years were marked by a prank that got him arrested. He was
charged with disorderly conduct for stealing a Christmas wreath
from a storefront. The charge was later dropped.
</P>
<P>
   The disobedient high jinks aside, years later he would rally to
his father's side, calling the president's 1992 loss to Bill
Clinton ''death by a thousand cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Passionate action, even for sons who had rebelled at earlier
stages, isn't surprising, said Ken Canfield, founder and president
of the National Center for Fathering.
</P>
<P>
   ''When there's some sort of premature death, sons either kick
into higher gear ... or they can go into a very depressive state,''
he said. ''In both cases, their fathers suffering defeat, both boys
kicked in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
