<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Witness Describes Bosnian Camp  </HEADLINE>
By JEROME SOCOLOVSKY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) -- A Bosnian grandmother choked with
grief as she testified Monday about the rape of her daughter and
granddaughter and vividly described a camp where Muslim women and
girls were taken into rooms and sexually assaulted each night.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, identified as witness No. 62, testified in the U.N.
war crimes tribunal trial of Bosnian Serbs Dragoljub Kunarac,
Radomir Kovac and Zoran Vukovic. The three are accused of running a
network of so-called ''rape camps'' in Foca, southeast of Sarajevo
in Bosnia-Herzegovina. All three have pleaded innocent.
</P>
<P>
   The trial, which began March 20, is the first international
prosecution of sexual enslavement. Prosecutors say the widespread
and organized rapes were intended to humiliate the women and their
families and to terrorize Muslims into flight as part of a Serb
''ethnic cleansing'' campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Serb paramilitaries backed by Yugoslav leader Slobodan Milosevic
are accused of war crimes violations during the 3{-year war in
Bosnia, the worst carnage in Europe since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Some 200,000 Bosnians died or are missing, hundreds of thousands
became refugees, and an estimated 20,000 women were raped during
the conflict, which formally ended with the 1995 Dayton peace
accords.
</P>
<P>
   The trial's defendants were members of the regular and
paramilitary units that in April 1992 overran Foca, where 20,000
Muslims comprised slightly more than half the prewar population of
the city. After the war, no Muslims remained and the town was
renamed Srbnje. Today, it is believed to be a hide-out for other
suspected war criminals.
</P>
<P>
   In the town, scores of women were held in a high school, a
sports hall and a construction facility and taken out nightly to be
raped and gang-raped during the summer of 1992, according to
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Although witness 62 was apparently not raped herself, her face
and voice were scrambled on the video monitors in the public
gallery. Still, her emotional account gripped the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   When Canadian Prosecutor Dirk Ryneveld asked the woman to
confirm that her offspring were among the rape victims, the
microphone went silent for a seemingly interminable period.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sorry,'' Ryneveld said. ''I realize this is difficult, but
I have to ask the questions. What happened to your daughter and
granddaughter?''
</P>
<P>
   ''My granddaughter was raped and mistreated,'' she replied.
</P>
<P>
   ''And your daughter?'' the prosecutor asked.
</P>
<P>
   After another long pause, the witness said: ''They did the same
thing to her.''
</P>
<P>
   The grandmother said her husband was also killed by Serb
paramilitaries, who first cut his ears off.
</P>
<P>
   She recalled how women were herded onto trucks, ''just as you
would animals,'' and shuttled from one camp to the next. At her
third stop, Partizan Gymnasium, dozens of detainees were forced to
sleep on a wooden floor with no blankets. To eat, they would
occasionally get a broth, which she described as ''dishwater in a
jar, some swill.''
</P>
<P>
   Although most victims were raped in separate rooms and
apartments, the witness remembered one night when three men entered
the darkened sports hall and roused the woman sleeping beside her.
One of them raped the woman in front of her 10-year-old son and the
rest of the detainees, the witness said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He tore her clothes off and she cried, 'Please don't! Please
don't!'' the witness told the court. ''But he lifted up her legs
and continued for an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   In another trial, prosecutors Monday called a Dutch peacekeeper
to the witness stand to testify about the massacre of thousands of
Muslims at Srebrenica in the trial of Gen. Radislav Krstic, the
Bosnian Serb commander accused of ordering Europe's worst war crime
since the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav war crimes tribunal was set up by the U.N. Security
Council in 1993. It has delivered sentences of up to 45 years
against 14 commanders and subordinates from Serb, Croat and Muslim
forces in the Bosnia war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
