<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fair E. coli infection still affecting family  </HEADLINE>
o0006nyc--
r n AM-NY--E.ColiAftermath     03-27 1102
AM-NY--E.Coli Aftermath,Bjt,1094   
Fair E. coli infection still affecting family
AP Photo
AP Membership Enterprise, 
By THOM RANDALL
o0006nyc--
r n AM-NY--E.ColiAftermath     03-27 1102
AM-NY--E.Coli Aftermath,Bjt,1094   
Fair E. coli infection still affecting family
AP Photo
AP Membership Enterprise
By THOM RANDALL
The Glens Falls Post Star
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUDSON FALLS, N.Y. (AP) -- Kim Bishop gazed into the big, brown
eyes of her 3-year-old daughter, Cheyenne, with a sense of fear
over what the future may hold.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours earlier, Cheyenne's doctor had told the family some
unsettling news.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since Cheyenne lay almost lifeless in a
hospital bed last fall battling deadly E. coli poisoning, blood
tests indicated her impaired kidneys might be getting worse rather
than continuing to recover.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly seven months ago, Scott and Kim Bishop took Cheyenne,
their only child, to the Washington County Fair in Easton to see
the animals and enjoy a spin on the kiddy rides.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Aug. 29, was a hot day, and Cheyenne wanted a soda. So
the family stopped at a concession booth and had several sodas.
</P>
<P>
   Little did the Bishops know that the water mixed into food and
drinks that day contained a deadly strain of E. coli. In the days
that followed, the virulent bacteria killed two people, sickened
more than 1,000 and brought about a dozen children close to death.
</P>
<P>
   Cheyenne was among them. Her mother was also a victim.
</P>
<P>
   While people flocked to hospitals, researchers worked around the
clock to identify what was sickening so many.
</P>
<P>
   The state Health Department determined that rain water had
washed through cow manure, seeping into a well that supplied water
to food vendors. The incident unfolded as the nation's second-worst
E. coli epidemic, most severely affecting about a dozen children.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks that followed the fair, the E. coli bacteria
multiplied in Cheyenne's bloodstream, spewing out a toxin that ate
away at her capillaries and attacked her vital organs.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the Bishops and their parents gathered in Scott and
Kim's living room and recalled how their family nightmare had
unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   Kim was the first to experience the initial symptoms of the
poisoning: nausea, cramps, vomiting and diarrhea, which started on
the Tuesday after the fair visit and became worse each day. She was
hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, Cheyenne showed mild symptoms of cramps and
diarrhea.
</P>
<P>
   Cheyenne was in bed with her grandmother, Mary Bishop, when the
symptoms turned serious.
</P>
<P>
   ''Cheyenne threw up, then she had dry heaves. She was so hungry
and thirsty, but she couldn't keep anything down,'' Mary recalled.
''She couldn't swallow anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott took his child to the Glens Falls Hospital emergency room,
where she was later admitted.
</P>
<P>
   That night and every night in the following days, Scott, his
parents and Kim's mother kept a bedside vigil beside Kim and
Cheyenne.
</P>
<P>
   While the mother improved and was released, Cheyenne grew
increasingly ill and weak.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors decided Cheyenne needed a catheter, and inserting it
took four hospital employees to hold her down, Mary remembered.
</P>
<P>
   But the worst was yet to come.
</P>
<P>
   At about 8 p.m. on the second Thursday after the fair visit,
doctors decided Cheyenne needed the specialized care at Albany
Medical Center. Crying relatives kissed her goodbye. Aides set her
on a gurney and wheeled her down a hallway, Kim remembered.
</P>
<P>
   ''She was hysterical, screaming and crying, yelling for Mommy
and Daddy, wondering where she was going,'' Bishop said. ''She was
very scared.''
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, Cheyenne was at Albany Medical Center's pediatric
ward alongside a dozen other children sickened by the E. coli
epidemic, the first mass poisoning incident of its nature for the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The Bishops didn't know the anguish that lay ahead.
</P>
<P>
   One of the children was an 8-year-old girl who was screaming in
pain for well over two hours. Kim complained to the nurses, and
they said there was nothing they could do.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, doctors can do very little about the deadly 0157:H7
strain of E. coli. Antibiotics can increase the toxins in the
patient's bloodstream by killing off the friendly strains of
bacteria that can help the digestive system shed the deadly strain.
</P>
<P>
   Pain killers also make things worse. Plenty of fluids are
helpful in mild cases. Children, most vulnerable to the poisoning,
were put on dialysis to cleanse their blood of the poison, and were
given transfusions.
</P>
<P>
   For 10 days or more, teams of doctors and nurses rushed medical
equipment from one room to another to meet crisis after crisis,
family members recalled.
</P>
<P>
   They not only dealt with the E. coli poisoning, but
complications and secondary infections.
</P>
<P>
   The nights were tough, Scott said. He would sleep on a cot or on
the floor beside Cheyenne, and listen to her cries -- and the
screams from other children -- intermittently all night long.
Sometimes the screams would be simply for a glass of water, he
said, which was restricted when they were on dialysis.
</P>
<P>
   On one night, as other children were battling low blood pressure
and shrunken veins, Cheyenne's blood pressure soared and her
temperature rose to 105.9, Kim's mother, Linda Robitaille, said.
Cheyenne was throwing up medicine and bleeding through the nose.
</P>
<P>
   ''At first we were taking it one day at a time, but later, we
were dealing with it just one hour at a time,'' Robitaille said.
</P>
<P>
   Cheyenne's follow-up care included three weeks of dialysis and
biweekly blood tests. Her kidneys steadily improved, although one
is still operating at only 30 percent efficiency, Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   Cheyenne now follows a low-sodium, low-phosphorous,
low-potassium diet. Tomatoes, bananas, potatoes, oranges,
chocolate, dairy products and other foods are either forbidden or
restricted for Cheyenne and others with impaired kidneys.
</P>
<P>
   Kidneys excrete growth hormones and permanent kidney impairment
may mean future problems for Cheyenne, Robitaille said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Before this happened, Cheyenne was such a healthy girl, and
now we don't know if she'll grow to a normal size,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides a weakened immune system, which had led to infections
and flu in the past several months, there is continuing concern
about whether Cheyenne will someday need a kidney transplant to
lead a normal life and have children, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Bishop said after the initial media attention over E. coli
subsided, many people may have believed the problems were over.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not over, and everybody's not well yet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bishops have filed a lawsuit on behalf of Cheyenne and Kim.
The Bishops' lawyer, William Nikas, said the fair organizers,
Washington County and the state should have taken measures to
assure the water's safety.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
