<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Slips 76; Nasdaq Climbs 21  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed today as Microsoft fell in
advance of a judge's antitrust ruling, weighing on every major
market index. Strength in other technology companies helped keep
the Nasdaq in positive territory.
</P>
<P>
   In afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was down 76.01 at 11,036.71, having reversed an early gain.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Nasdaq composite index
was up 21.99 at 4,985.02 and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was
down 1.64 at 1,525.82.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft fell 5} to 105 15/16, and was the most actively traded
Nasdaq stock. Government lawyers reportedly have concluded
Microsoft's offer to settle its antitrust case was inadequate, and
they are preparing for U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson
to deliver a verdict Tuesday. Jackson has previously hinted he will
rule strongly against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Many other technology companies advanced today.
</P>
<P>
   IBM rose 4| to 126 after Morgan Stanley Dean Witter raised its
rating on the stock from ''neutral'' to ''outperform.''
</P>
<P>
   Unisys rose 3 9/16 to 28 15/16 after a German magazine reported
Deutsche Telekom is interested in acquiring it. Unisys declined to
comment to Dow Jones News Service, and called the report a rumor.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks before companies begin reporting their
first-quarter earnings, technology stocks are likely to lead the
market as investors buy them on the promise of strong earnings
growth, said John H. Shaughnessy, chief investment strategist at
Advest Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe stock selection should continue to focus on those
companies with strong earnings momentum,'' he said. ''This would
include technology stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   The earnings reporting season will gather momentum in mid-April.
Until then, traders said the market may remain in a fairly narrow
range with no clear catalyst to spark a major swing in either
direction.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of oil producers were trading actively as OPEC oil
ministers met in Vienna, struggling to reach a consensus about
boosting their petroleum output. OPEC members were considering
raising production by 1.5 million to 1.7 million barrels a day,
which would bring oil prices down from nine-year highs.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon Mobil was up 11/16 at 77 15/16 and BP Amoco was down 1\ at
49].
</P>
<P>
   Investment bank Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette fell 8 15/16 to 58]
after Morgan Stanley Dean Witter analyst Henry McVey downgraded the
stock to ''neutral'' from ''outperform.'' McVey cited concerns that
DLJ may have reached a peak in valuation.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 4-to-3 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 592.06 million
shares, well behind Friday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 0.98 to 574.99.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
