<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Existing-Home Sales Rose Last Month  </HEADLINE>
By JEANNINE AVERSA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Feeling prosperous, Americans pushed up sales
of existing homes in February after two consecutive months of
declines caused in part by higher mortgage rates.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of existing single-family homes bounced back by a modest
6.7 percent last month to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 4.75
million units, the National Association of Realtors said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   With plentiful jobs, rising incomes, stock market gains and low
inflation, Americans are feeling wealthy and in a mood to buy
despite an upswing in mortgage rates, economists said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The higher interest rate story is being overridden by the
amount of wealth potential homeowners have amassed,'' said
economist Richard Yamarone of Argus Research Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve last week raised interest rates for the
fifth time since June 30, making borrowing more expensive for
millions of consumers and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed did this to slow the red-hot economy and keep inflation
under control. Given continuing strong growth, many economists
believe the central bank will boost interest rates again on May 16.
</P>
<P>
   The average rate on a 30-year fixed-rate mortgage was 8.33
percent in February, up from 8.21 percent the month before. In
February 1999, the average rate on a 30-year mortgage was 6.81
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact sales improved in the face of continuing increases in
mortgage interest rates demonstrates the very high demand for
housing in the United States,'' said Dennis Cronk, president of the
Realtors association.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the gain, however, February's sales are 7.6 percent
lower than the 5.14 million-unit sales rate posted in February
1999.
</P>
<P>
   In January, existing-home sales fell 13.4 percent, sharper than
previously reported. Economists had blamed the earlier-reported
higher mortgage rates and a record low 2.6-month supply of homes
available to sell in January. In December, existing-home sales
dropped by 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The stock of existing homes for sale rose in February but
remained at a low 2.8 months, meaning it would take 2.8 months to
exhaust the supply at February's sales pace.
</P>
<P>
   ''The extremely low inventory of homes for resale is undoubtedly
playing a major role in the trend of lower sales,'' said First
Union's chief economist David Orr. ''It is still a seller's
market.''
</P>
<P>
   Economists expect home sales to slow this year but still remain
at healthy levels.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Realtors is projecting sales to
total 4.74 million units in 2000. While that would mark the
third-highest sales on record, it would represent an 8.7 percent
drop from the all-time high of 5.20 million sold last year.
</P>
<P>
   By region, the South saw existing-home sales rise 10.7 percent
last month to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.97 million
units.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, sales rose 8.7 percent to a rate of 1.12 million
units, and in the Midwest they grew by 5.7 percent to a rate of
1.12 million units. But sales fell 6.9 percent in the Northeast to
a rate of 540,000 units.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the median existing-home sales price, meaning half
sold for more and half for less, was $131,100 last month. That was
0.8 percent lower than January's median price but was 2.3 percent
higher than the median price recorded for February 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: National Association of Realtors site:
http://nar.realtor.com/news
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-27-00 1524 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000327.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge To Rule on Reform Party Head  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE KELLMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Whoever emerges as the head of the Reform
Party, federal election officials say he needs to keep the
government better informed of where the organization's millions of
taxpayer dollars are kept.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, U.S. District Judge Norman K. Moon was picking
between two rivals claiming to be the legitimate chairman of the
party: Jack Gargan, who was ousted last month during a rowdy party
meeting in Nashville, Tenn., and the man who took his place, Pat
Choate, the 1996 running mate of party founder Ross Perot.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly $2.5 million in public money that was granted the third
party for its nominating convention was not stored in the
Martinsville, Va., bank that party officers had named in their
application for the funding, according to an advisory brief filed
with the judge by the Federal Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   According to court documents, most of the money was spread among
at least four bank accounts from Virginia to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ''The court should ... order the prevailing parties to provide
the commission with notice of any changes in the information
provided in its application for federal funds,'' including where
the money has been deposited, the FEC said in its March 21 brief.
</P>
<P>
   The FEC urged Moon to not only pick a Reform Party chairman but
to state specifically who should be in charge of the federal
funding. In addition, the agency suggested that Moon require the
prevailing officers to agree in writing to keep the FEC apprised of
the money's whereabouts as a condition of receiving it.
</P>
<P>
   As for the two would-be chairmen, Gargan contends that the
Nashville meeting was convened illegally and that the vote to oust
him and install Choate was invalid.
</P>
<P>
   Choate, meanwhile, argues that Gargan's refusal to step down and
his continuing claim to the chairmanship is hurting the party's
ability to make a meaningful White House bid.
</P>
<P>
   The chairmanship aside, the departure of the party's
highest-ranking elected leader, Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura, and
the void created by Perot's absence have left the party a patchwork
of state organizations caught up in a variety of fights waged in
courtrooms and cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas billionaire and two-time presidential candidate
refused Monday to comment on the suit or answer questions about
whether he plans to jump into the race and compete for his party's
nomination against former Republican Pat Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I'm ready to say something, I'll let you all know,''
Perot said, following a speech to the Federation of American Health
Systems in Dallas. In that speech, Perot blamed Medicare, the
federal health program for the elderly, for failing to change
enough since its inception more than 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, meanwhile, is being sued by New Hampshire Reform Party
Chairman John Talbott, who says the conservative columnist is
illegally using the party's name and trying to elect his own
convention delegates at a meeting in Manchester on Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
