<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. May Buy Sugar Surplus  </HEADLINE>
By PHILIP BRASHER, AP Farm Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Got a sweet tooth? Uncle Sam wants you! The
government is thinking of buying 250,000 tons of surplus sugar to
pump up its domestic price. But then what will officials do with
all that sugar, enough to fill up two-thirds of the Empire State
Building?
</P>
<P>
   One idea is to donate it overseas, although no country has
indicated any interest in it. Another is to sell it at a deep
discount for refining into ethanol, a gasoline additive usually
made from corn. Whatever course is taken, taxpayers could get stuck
with a $100 million tab.
</P>
<P>
   The problem stems from a government program that guarantees U.S.
growers a minimum price for their sugar. Until now, the Agriculture
Department has managed to keep domestic sugar prices three times
higher than the world price simply by regulating supplies. But the
department is fast losing control of the situation because of
bumper domestic crops and rising imports.
</P>
<P>
   Prices that farmers get for sugar have dropped 25 percent since
last year, and growers are threatening to forfeit to the government
as much as $550 million worth of sugar that was pledged as
collateral on federal marketing loans.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a mess,'' said Dan Colacicco, a senior Agriculture
Department analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Economists say the forfeitures are a virtual certainty unless
USDA buys some sugar to boost the domestic price.
</P>
<P>
   ''The situation is dire,'' said Mark Weber, executive director
of the Red River Valley Sugarbeet Growers Association in Fargo,
N.D.
</P>
<P>
   ''Certainly there will be critics,'' Weber added. ''We've had
critics for a long time against sugar policy, and they'll use this
to poke us in the eye.''
</P>
<P>
   The sugar program normally doesn't cost the government anything.
But it's still controversial because it increases costs for candy
and breakfast cereal makers -- and ultimately consumers -- while
benefitting large sugar cane farms in Florida, Louisiana and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   It's also frequently cited as an example of American
protectionism when U.S. negotiators try to persuade other countries
to lower their trade barriers.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the sugar program are urging USDA to let sugar
prices fall. The farmers ''contributed to the current oversupply
and should cope with the problem on their own,'' the Consumer
Federation of America said in a letter to Agriculture Secretary Dan
Glickman.
</P>
<P>
   The government guarantees farmers a minimum price for domestic
sugar through the loan program and quotas on imports. Growers who
put their sugar up as collateral for a federal loan have the right
to forfeit the crop to the government if prices fall below the
guaranteed price.
</P>
<P>
   Since the early 1980s, USDA has avoided any such forfeitures by
keeping imports low enough to stabilize domestic prices. But now
U.S. production is expanding -- up 25 percent from 1997 -- as farmers
switch to growing sugar from less lucrative crops. Meanwhile,
imports are also increasing, especially from Mexico, because of
U.S. obligations under international trade agreements.
</P>
<P>
   About 1.3 million tons of sugar are now under government loan
and subject to forfeiture. The first forfeitures could begin in
July. Prices for raw cane sugar are expected to be about 19 cents a
pound then, more than 4 cents below the rate at which USDA expects
forfeitures.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. growers say food and candy makers are profiting from the
lower prices at the farmers' expense.
</P>
<P>
   ''Prices this low are a terrible financial blow to me and my
family,'' said Everett Gabel, who farms 240 acres of sugarbeets
near Billings, Mont. ''It would be some consolation to us if this
low producer price meant lower sugar and sweetened product prices
at the grocery store, but it does not.''
</P>
<P>
   Glickman hasn't said what, if anything, he is going to do.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think there's anything we can do in this situation to
avoid costs'' to taxpayers, said Colacicco, the USDA analyst.
''There's far too much sugar out there.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: USDA: http://www.usda.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
