<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Auto Mergers Sign of Times  </HEADLINE>
By HANS GREIMEL, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Alliances unveiled Monday by
DaimlerChrysler AG and Volkswagen AG take Europe's two largest
automakers in opposite directions but fulfill the same goal --
rounding out their product lines to stay alive in the latest round
of global consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler shelled out $2 billion for a 34 percent stake in
Japan's Mitsubishi Motors Corp., giving the German automaker new
inroads in Asia but also the technical edge needed to push its new
line of smaller, more fuel efficient cars.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Volkswagen, known for subcompact hits like the Beetle,
filled in a big gap as it laid out $1.6 billion for a controlling
stake in Swedish bus and truck maker Scania AB. That gives the
German passenger car giant an outlet for making anything with more
four or more wheels -- from cheap cars for first-time buyers to
40-ton cargo-hauling trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Both deals give the companies something they each have long
sought, a well-rounded product line capable of an international
reach and the depth needed to ride out slumps in business cycles.
</P>
<P>
   ''With the giant footprint of this group in the worldwide
automotive market, we're now where we always wanted to be,''
DaimlerChrysler chairman Juergen Schrempp said in announcing the
Mitsubishi deal at a news conference Monday in Frankfurt. ''I'd
like to say another acquisition isn't necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler shares finished down 0.2 percent at 70.05 euros
($67) in Frankfurt trading, while shares of Mitsubishi rose 12
percent in trading in Tokyo to close at 470 yen ($4.40)
</P>
<P>
   Volkswagen finished up 1.35 percent to 45.10 euros ($43.75),
while U.S. shares of Scania were up $1.25 to $30 on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   In a world where few merger candidates still exist, companies
such as DaimlerChrysler and Volkswagen are racing to pair off with
weaker players -- building global auto empires at the same time they
offer smaller companies a parent company with deep pockets.
</P>
<P>
   Scania will be looking to Volkswagen for its expertise in
marketing and purchasing, only weeks after a deal with Volvo fell
through. Authorities shot down Volvo's bid for its smaller rival
Scania, saying it would give Volvo a stranglehold on the
Scandinavian market.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the DaimlerChrysler deal buoys debt-ridden Mitsubishi
with an infusion of badly needed cash as the troubled automaker
digs its way out of 1.75 trillion yen ($16.4 billion) in debt.
</P>
<P>
   But more importantly, it catapults DaimlerChrysler to the No. 3
spot in world automaking behind General Motors Corp. and Ford Motor
Co., and gives it a leg up in small, mass volume cars -- the
Mercedes-maker's traditional Achilles' heel.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the move was crucial for positioning
DaimlerChrysler to cash in on the growing demand for small cars in
the developing markets of Asia and Latin America -- not to mention
Europe, where tight European Union fuel efficiency standards are
pressuring automakers to clean up their engines or pay heavy fines.
</P>
<P>
   ''All cars will have to develop small, cleaner engines in the
near future and that's where DaimlerChrysler stands to benefit
because Mitsubishi has proven expertise there,'' said Mark Little,
an auto analyst with Deutsche Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi is bringing its pioneering gasoline direct injection
technology to the table. That's an area where the company has
failed to exploit its leadership and could benefit from
DaimlerChrysler's vast resources, deep pockets and technical
know-how, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.DaimlerChrysler.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.Mitsubishi.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www2.vw-online.de/international/english/index--2.htm
</P>
<P>
   http://www.scania.se
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
