<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Firefighter To Help Epileptic Rower  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONOLULU (AP) -- A freighter is leaving Tuesday to bring food and
medicine to Andrew Halsey, who is trying to become the first
epileptic to row alone across the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Halsey left San Diego in July in a 27-foot rowboat on
what was expected to be an eight-month, 7,500-mile trip to Sydney,
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   But after missing favorable weather patterns early on, he was
swept back and forth off the Mexican coast for months.
</P>
<P>
   Although Halsey now is making better progress, backers fear his
food and medical supplies are getting low. The 42-year-old former
bricklayer is prone to severe seizures.
</P>
<P>
   Halsey was estimated to be 1,200 miles south of Hawaii and 980
miles east of Christmas Island.
</P>
<P>
   A 180-foot freighter was scheduled to leave Honolulu on Tuesday
for a rendezvous with Halsey's backers on Christmas Island. They
then hope to acquire a skiff or inflatable craft to take the
supplies to Halsey, fearing the freighter would swamp the rowboat
if it got too close.
</P>
<P>
   Halsey has no means of voice communication. The only way backers
know he is alive is from the intermittent satellite locator signals
he is sending.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-27-00 1542 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
