<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Group Supports Land-Protection  </HEADLINE>
By MATT KELLEY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton's willingness to protect
federal lands by declaring them national monuments has gotten the
attention of Western Republicans in Congress, a group normally
opposed to land-use restrictions but now offering their own
protections.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has bypassed Congress to create three new monuments and
expand a fourth in Arizona and California this year. Interior
Secretary Bruce Babbitt has said he will recommend more monuments
elsewhere if Congress fails to act.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, Western Republicans have contended that new limits
on logging, mining, grazing or recreational use hurt people who
depend on federal lands for their livelihoods. By offering
legislation, they hope to set terms for protection rather than have
the Clinton administration impose them.
</P>
<P>
   Even Rep. Scott McInnis, R-Colo., who has railed against ''ivory
tower bureaucrats'' who want to restrict usage of the 23 million
acres of federal land in his district, is sponsoring
land-protection bills.
</P>
<P>
   McInnis said some of his bills are the result of Babbitt's new
willingness to discuss land management with Republicans rather than
circumvent Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can't ignore him, but I think for the first time he
understands he can't ignore us. That's what's brought us both to
the table, and I think we're moving in a positive direction,''
McInnis said.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt joked at a recent House Resources subcommittee that some
Westerners ''advise their neighbors to batten down the hatches and
protect their firstborn'' when he comes to town. He said he prefers
to have Congress make land preservation decisions but reiterated he
will ask Clinton to intervene if Congress won't.
</P>
<P>
   Congress may protect lands as wilderness areas, conservation
areas or national monuments. A president has authority only to
declare an area a monument.
</P>
<P>
   Wilderness areas are the most restrictive, with almost all uses
banned except low-impact activities such as hiking. Congress has
wide latitude in deciding restrictions for monuments and
conservation areas, and the Republican proposals generally are less
restrictive than what Clinton has imposed.
</P>
<P>
   Among the GOP plans:
</P>
<P>
   --California Rep. Mary Bono wants to create a 272,000-acre Santa
Rosa and San Jacinto Mountains National Monument near Palm Springs.
</P>
<P>
   --Arizona Rep. Jim Kolbe is calling for creation of a
207,000-acre Las Cienegas National Conservation Area southeast of
Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   --Utah Rep. Jim Hansen is proposing wilderness status for about
2.4 million acres in his home state. The bill, drawn as a
compromise between Babbitt and Utah's Republican governor, Mike
Leavitt, covers wilderness zones in national parks, as well as
broad swaths of the state's western deserts.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, McInnis took up a cause started by Sen. Ben
Nighthorse Campbell, R-Colo., and helped push through legislation
to create the Black Canyon of the Gunnison National Park in
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   McInnis now is backing plans to create the 18,000-acre Spanish
Peaks Wilderness near La Veta, Colo., and expand the Great Sand
Dunes National Monument near Alamosa, Colo., and upgrade it to a
national park.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists say they are encouraged but wary of the GOP's
new willingness to embrace land protections.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a lot of potential for protecting some special areas
this year,'' said Melanie Griffin of the Sierra Club. ''But it's
going to be a long year, because there are a lot of people who
don't want to see these victories move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Bureau of Land Management: www.blm.gov/
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Scott McInnis: www.house.gov/mcinnis/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
