<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Candidates Stayed Focused on Message  </HEADLINE>
By WILL LESTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The two winning candidates in this year's
presidential primaries focused their messages more effectively than
their rivals, according to a study that says George W. Bush was
more consistent than any of the other candidates in emphasizing one
issue -- in his case, taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Also, while they campaigned against each other for their party's
nomination, Bush and fellow Republican John McCain both kept a
steady stream of criticism on Democrat Al Gore -- a move that could
help Bush in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ''The primaries provided a launching pad for the general
election campaign for Bush that they did not provide for Gore,''
said Kathleen Hall Jamieson, a lead researcher on the study
released Monday by the Annenberg Public Policy Center.
</P>
<P>
   She said polling showed that residents of states with intensive
primary campaigns such as New Hampshire, South Carolina and
Michigan, learned significantly more about the candidates, their
personal stories, character qualities and positions than people in
other states. Iowa did not show the same level of public knowledge
about the campaign as the states with primaries, possibly because
caucuses draw a lower number of participants, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Campaigns do matter,'' Jamieson said, adding that the rush to
hold primaries early in 2000 created a system of ''political haves
and have-nots'' when it comes to voter information about the
campaigns and the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   What may be good for political parties in wrapping up the
nomination early, is not necessarily good for the voters or for the
democratic process, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The general perception from recent polls has been that Gore was
helped and Bush hurt by the primaries. The vice president is
perceived as a stronger candidate, and Bush lost support among some
key groups of swing voters, national polls found. But the Annenberg
study suggested Bush may see some long-term benefits from the
primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ''Although there's a widespread perception that the Republican
primaries were more contested than the Democratic primaries, Bush
managed to stay on message and he and John McCain held their focus
on Al Gore as they argued that one of them was more qualified than
the other,'' said Jamieson, director of the public policy center at
the University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the governor of Texas, consistently told voters during the
primary season that he wanted to cut taxes, and the issue appears
to have been a bigger factor in his crucial victory in South
Carolina than the support of Christian conservatives, the study
said.
</P>
<P>
   Polling in South Carolina suggested that support for McCain, a
senator from Arizona, dropped steadily throughout the February
campaign among those seriously interested in the tax issue.
</P>
<P>
   The study analyzed the candidates' messages and found that Bush
focused most heavily on taxes both in ads and in debates, Gore most
on education. Neither McCain nor Democrat Bill Bradley focused as
heavily on any one issue as either of the two winners, according to
the study.
</P>
<P>
   The study was based on analysis of debates and ads, as well as
polling of 30,000 respondents between mid-November and the Super
Tuesday primaries. Between 1,500 and 4,000 people were polled
weekly, and the error margin was plus or minus 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Jamieson said the time that Bush spent positioning himself
against Gore on issues like campaign fund-raising abuses could pay
off later.
</P>
<P>
   ''Gore hasn't put a comparable set of indictments in place
against Bush,'' the researcher said, adding that Bush's
concentration on taxes will only be effective if taxes turn out to
be a strong issue. National polls have raised questions this year
about how badly voters want tax cuts, however.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Bush is wrong about the issues, then it's not an
advantage,'' Jamieson said. ''He's laid in place the basis to build
his campaign. But if taxes turn out not to be a good issue, then he
squandered an opportunity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-27-00 1615 </TRAILER>
