<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conoco To Pay $26M in Settlement  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Conoco agreed to pay $26 million to settle
court and administrative claims that the company underpaid
royalties for oil it produced from leased federal and Indian land
since 1988, the Justice Department said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement settles both administrative claims and a False
Claims Act lawsuit originally brought against the Ponca City,
Okla., oil company by two private whistle-blowers on behalf of
taxpayers. The federal government has joined the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ''This settlement brings us one step closer to restoring to the
taxpayers and Indian tribes of the United States the money due for
production of oil on public lands,'' said Mike Bradford, U.S.
attorney for the eastern district of Texas. ''We commend the
company for settling this matter in a way that avoids further
litigation, and we will continue to press forward with the
prosecution of this False Claims Act lawsuit against other
companies that have underpaid their royalty obligations.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department already settled with several other oil
companies for underpayment of royalties, including Mobil Oil, for
$45 million; Oxy USA Inc., for $7.3 million; and Chevron, for $95
million.
</P>
<P>
   Federal leases administered by the Interior Department require
Conoco to report each month the amount and value of oil produced on
federal and Indian land. The company pays royalties based on the
value of the oil it reports. The claims alleged the company
systematically underreported the value of oil it produced.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement was signed by representatives of several Indian
tribes, the federal government and Conoco.
</P>
<P>
   Two private whistle-blowers, J. Benjamin Johnson Jr. and John
Martinek, who filed the False Claims Act lawsuit, will share more
than $4.2 million of the $26 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
