<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Army sergeant blamed for sharing free presidential phone service  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- President Clinton's work-related phone bills
rose more than $50,000 after an Army sergeant gave the White House
long-distance calling code to people in the Bronx and New Jersey,
federal prosecutors said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone caper culminated Friday in the arrest of David
Gilmer, 30, of Woodbridge, Va., an Army sergeant assigned to the
Presidential Communications division of the White House
Communications Agency.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White alleged in court papers filed in
U.S. District Court in Manhattan that Gilmer gave phone access
numbers to others, helping them make 9,400 unauthorized calls
between Dec. 5 and Feb. 8.
</P>
<P>
   According to court papers, they were tapping into the same
telephone service provided to the president, vice president, White
House senior staff, the National Security Council, U.S. Secret
Service and others given access to the system by the White House
Military Office.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Smilon, a spokesman for White, said there was no
indication that those who obtained the access codes could have done
anything more than make free phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   The people, some at pay phones, tapped into the Private Branch
Exchange, a computerized telephone system owned by private
companies but operated by the White House Communications Agency to
which Gilmer was assigned.
</P>
<P>
   They were able to punch in a sequence of numbers and get a dial
tone through the White House telephone system, allowing them to
make calls anywhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
   A criminal complaint accused Gilmer of giving out the access
codes knowing that those who had it could obtain free telephone
service from the AT&AMP;T Co., which provides long-distance service to
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   More than a week ago, federal investigators searched six
locations in the Bronx, one in Manhattan and one in New Jersey to
gather evidence in the case.
</P>
<P>
   During the search in New Jersey, agents discovered evidence of
telephone fraud and interviewed an individual who admitted having
received the access codes from Gilmer, according to the complaint
signed by Secret Service Agent J. Alexander Pickett.
</P>
<P>
   The individual then agreed to allow federal agents to tape a
telephone call in which the individual asked Gilmer for an
additional access code to make a telephone call, the complaint
alleged.
</P>
<P>
   During a second taped phone call with the individual, Gilmer
admitted that he had provided access codes to others, according to
the complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Gilmer was held for an initial court appearance in Alexandria,
Va.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-27-00 1627 </TRAILER>
