<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Off 86.87; Nasdaq Off 4.90  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Microsoft deflated every major stock market
index today, falling steeply after the government reportedly
rejected the company's offer to settle their antitrust case.
Microsoft's decline masked strength in other technology issues.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 86.87 to close at
11,025.85. The blue-chip index lost an early gain due to
Microsoft's weakness and profit-taking in the financial shares that
soared last week.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators closed modestly lower. The New York
Stock Exchange recorded its lowest volume of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index fell 4.90 to 4,958.13, and the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 3.67 to 1,523.79.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 4-to-3 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, with 1,704 down, 1,284 up and 487
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE volume totaled 876.26 million shares as of 4 p.m., vs. 1.03
billion in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 0.38 to 573.63.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, the most actively traded Nasdaq stock, fell. Sources
have told The Associated Presss that government lawyers have
concluded Microsoft's offer to settle their antitrust case was
inadequate, and they are preparing for U.S. District Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson to deliver a verdict as early as Tuesday. Jackson
has previously hinted he will rule strongly against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Microsoft shares rose as much as 12 percent amid
reports that the company was nearing a settlement with the
government.
</P>
<P>
   ''Microsoft ran way up in anticipation of some good news over
the weekend,'' said Scott Bleier, chief investment strategist at
Prime Charter Ltd. ''Did it get ahead of itself? Yes. Investors are
still waiting to see what the government has to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Many other technology companies advanced today.
</P>
<P>
   IBM rose after Morgan Stanley Dean Witter raised its rating on
the stock from ''neutral'' to ''outperform.'' Cisco Systems and Sun
Microsystems rose as portfolio managers scrambled to add them to
their portfolios before the end of the first quarter on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The stocks that are the institutional favorites continue to
power higher,'' Bleier said. ''There's a major markup of large-cap
technology stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Unisys rose after a German magazine reported Deutsche Telekom is
interested in acquiring it. Unisys declined to comment to Dow Jones
News Service, and called the report a rumor.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks before companies begin reporting their
first-quarter earnings, technology stocks are likely to lead the
market as investors buy them on the promise of strong earnings
growth, said John H. Shaughnessy, chief investment strategist at
Advest Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe stock selection should continue to focus on those
companies with strong earnings momentum,'' he said. ''This would
include technology stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   The earnings reporting season will gather momentum in mid-April.
Until then, traders said the market may remain in a fairly narrow
range with no clear catalyst to spark a major swing in either
direction.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of oil producers trading actively as OPEC oil ministers
adjourned their meeting in Vienna without reaching an agreement on
production increases. OPEC members are considering raising
production by 1.5 million to 1.7 million barrels a day, which would
bring oil prices down from nine-year highs.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon Mobil fell and BP Amoco was down.
</P>
<P>
   Investment bank Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette fell after Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter analyst Henry McVey downgraded the stock to
''neutral'' from ''outperform.'' McVey cited concerns that DLJ may
have reached a peak in valuation.
</P>
<P>
   Other financial stocks, which rose after the Federal Reserve
announced its decision to raise interest rates modestly last
Tuesday, fell as investors took profits. American Express was down.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
