<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giuliani's reaction to shooting hurting him in polls  </HEADLINE>
By TIMOTHY WILLIAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A new poll suggests that Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's unsympathetic response after the latest police shooting
of an unarmed black man is hurting him in his Senate race against
Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The Zogby International poll taken over the weekend shows
Giuliani's 7-point lead has vanished following the killing of
26-year-old Patrick Dorismond on March 16. Clinton now has 45
percent to Giuliani's 42.3 percent advantage -- within the poll's
3.8-point margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also shows that the Republican mayor would receive just
28 percent of the vote in the city he leads -- down from 44 percent
three weeks ago. Giuliani's support has also tumbled in several key
demographic areas, including among upstate voters, Jews and
Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty percent of the people polled said the mayor should have
offered condolences to the victim's family, and one in four said
the issue would be a factor in whether they vote for Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's handing her the race,'' said pollster John Zogby. ''It's
not that she's doing better, it's that he's doing worse. We've seen
the tide turn.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, known for his combative responses to criticism,
brushed aside the poll results Monday at a news conference in
Albany.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm absolutely destroyed by it,'' he joked. Turning serious,
he said: ''No. I'm not concerned about it at all. I think that if
you've been through tough elections, as I have, you expect to be up
in the polls, you expect to be down in the polls and you expect to
be statistically tied in the polls.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorismond, a security guard and son of a prominent Haitian
singer, was killed by an undercover officer in a botched police
drug sting. It is unclear whether the officer fired by accident.
</P>
<P>
   He became the fourth unarmed black man shot to death by New York
City police in the past 13 months, including Amadou Diallo, who was
killed in a barrage of 41 bullets in 1999. After each case,
Giuliani has defended the police involved and blamed the victim.
</P>
<P>
   After the Dorismond shooting, Giuliani released the man's
criminal record, including supposedly sealed documents about an
arrest when he was 13. The mayor repeatedly suggested that
Dorismond was a violent person who brought on his own death.
</P>
<P>
   He again defended police Saturday against charges they may have
provoked clashes after Dorismond's funeral, in which 23 officers
were injured and 27 civilians arrested.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton campaign has made Giuliani's handling of the
shooting Exhibit A in its effort to paint him as too ill-tempered
for the Senate, but Giuliani has refused to soften his stance. He
has said the news media are unable to cover police shootings
fairly.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think I handled it appropriately, appropriate to the
situation and appropriate to what had to be done in order to make
sure that the public got information that the media to this day is
still suppressing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier polls have shown Giuliani with as little as 5 percent
support among black voters, and observers believe the mayor's
hard-edged response to the shooting could generate a large turnout
of Democrats in a state where they outnumber Republicans by about
5-3.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Giuliani's statement that the city's police are among
the nation's most ''restrained'' in firing their weapons, a Daily
News-New York 1 poll found that 72 percent of respondents believed
that ''the use of deadly force has gotten out of hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Republican political consultant Jay Severin said he
doubts the Dorismond shooting will have much effect on the roughly
15 percent of voters who are undecided.
</P>
<P>
   ''The worst thing that's going to come out of this is that
Rudy's going to appear to be tough on crime and Hillary's going to
appear to be too weak on crime,'' he said. ''I don't think the
undecideds are going to vote for someone they perceive as being
weak on crime.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-27-00 1641 </TRAILER>
