<HEADLINE> Clinton: Probe Needed in Chechen War  </HEADLINE>
By PAULINE JELINEK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton called Russian
president-elect Vladimir Putin on Monday to congratulate him on his
victory at the polls and press again for an end to suffering in the
war-ravaged Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said in a statement issued at the White House that he
stressed Russia must launch ''impartial and transparent
investigations of reported human rights violations'' in Chechnya,
and allow prompt, full access to the province for international
relief organizations and the press.
</P>
<P>
   ''We hope that the new Russian government will find its own way
towards achieving a political solution in Chechnya,'' State
Department spokesman James Foley added later in the department's
regular briefing.
</P>
<P>
   ''Until that happens, we have a serious and profound
disagreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Putin's uncompromising tactics in pursuing the
rebellion in the Caucasus region played well with Russian voters in
the months before the election. But it has also brought widespread
international criticism and repeated calls for a negotiated end to
the conflict because of the deaths and suffering it has caused
since September among the civilian population.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've not seen movement on the Russian side, we've not seen a
recognition ... on their part that they need a political process,
that there is no military solution,'' Foley said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's statement also stressed issues on which the United
States hopes to work cooperatively with Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ''President-elect Putin has an opportunity to translate his
electoral mandate into concrete steps to advance economic reform,
to strengthen the rule of law, to intensify the fight against crime
and corruption, and to join with us on a broad common agenda of
international security including arms control, nonproliferation and
regional peace and stability,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore congratulated the Russian people ''for
once again demonstrating their commitment to hard-won democratic
freedoms by turning out to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope that the President-elect will seize this opportunity to
strengthen the foundations of Russia's democracy, economic
recovery, and international integration,'' Gore said in a
statement. ''I also urge Mr. Putin to work toward a lasting
political solution in Chechnya. ''
</P>
</TEXT>
