<HEADLINE> Customs Service Has Most Wanted List  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Watch your back FBI. Your 10 Most Wanted
Fugitives list is getting some competition from another law
enforcement agency: the U.S. Customs Service.
</P>
<P>
   Customs released its own Most Wanted list Monday -- something it
hasn't done since 1991. In the past, the agency sporadically put
out a Most Wanted list but had trouble getting it disseminated
internationally.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the customs service is posting the list on its Web
site -- www.customs.gov -- and officials hope the Internet posting
will give it more visibility.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI's Most Wanted list, which recently turned 50 years old,
is posted on the Web, too: www.fbi.gov.
</P>
<P>
   Customs' current list represents a cross-section of some of the
top criminals in the international arena, said Customs Commissioner
Raymond Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   On the list are alleged: international narcotics money
launderer, Jose Alvarez Tostado; arms dealers, Frans Van Anraat and
Houshang Amir Bagheri; child pornographers, David Creamer and
Timothy Allen Groves; international transporters of stolen goods,
Mohamad Reda Tabbara and Luar Vetus Lorrett; and narcotics
traffickers, Sidney Lewis, Juan Carlos Arboleda and John Innocent
Okayfor.
</P>
</TEXT>
