<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
Monday, March 27, 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dow Ends Off 86.87; Nasdaq Off 4.90
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Microsoft deflated every major stock market
index today, falling steeply after the government reportedly
rejected the company's offer to settle their antitrust case.
Microsoft's decline masked strength in other technology issues. The
Dow Jones industrial average fell 86.87 to close at 11,025.85. The
blue-chip index lost an early gain due to Microsoft's weakness and
profit-taking in the financial shares that soared last week.
Broader stock indicators closed modestly lower. The New York Stock
Exchange recorded its lowest volume of the year. The Nasdaq
composite index fell 4.90 to 4,958.13.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Leads Stocks Down
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (ap) -- Microsoft, the most actively traded Nasdaq
stock, fell 7| to 104 1/16 today. Sources have told The Associated
Press that government lawyers have concluded Microsoft's offer to
settle their antitrust case was inadequate, and they are preparing
for U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson to deliver a
verdict as early as tomorrow. Jackson has previously hinted he will
rule strongly against Microsoft. Last week, Microsoft shares rose
as much as 12 percent amid reports that the company was nearing a
settlement with the government.
</P>
<P>
   Financial Figures
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures at the close:
Dow Industrials:        11,025.85  - 86.87
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1,284  Declines 1,704  Unchgd  487
NYSE Volume:         881,271,890
Most Active NYSE issue:         America Online74\   + 3]  
S&AMP;P 500:         1,522.67  - 4.79
AMEX Mkt Value Index:         1023.87  - 8.64
Nasdaq Composite Index       4,958.13  - 4.90
Gold(final) -    $280.10    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Mon.
Silver(final) -   UNCH    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Fri.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan Prods Hill on Surpluses
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan told a
Senate committee today nothing could have a better impact on the
nation's ability to meet the expenses of baby boomers' retirements
than saving big government surpluses to pay down the national debt.
He said saving the surpluses -- if politically feasible -- is, in his
judgment, ''the most important fiscal measure we can take at this
time to foster continued improvements in productivity,'' Greenspan
said he had no strong views on whether future income taxes should
be transferred directly to Social Security and Medicare -- something
President Clinton has proposed, but Republicans and some moderate
Democrats object to.
</P>
<P>
   Existing-Home Sales Rise in February
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Mortgage rates are up, but that hasn't
prevented sales of existing homes to go up too -- by 6.7 percent in
February. The sales were at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of
4.75 million units last month after having fallen a sharper than
previously reported 13.4 percent in January, the National
Association of Realtors said today.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Watch Latin America Lending
</P>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- The loan policies of Latin America's largest
lending institution should be improved to reduce widespread poverty
in the region and help countries recover more quickly from natural
disasters, U.S. Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said today.
Summers, who was named to a one-year term as chairman of the
Inter-American Development Bank's governing board, proposed a
yearlong lending policy review that he believes could also lead to
more private business loans.
</P>
<P>
   Jury Awards Ex-Smoker $20 Million
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A dying ex-smoker was awarded $20 million
in punitive damages today in her lawsuit against the nation's two
largest tobacco companies. The Superior Court jury ordered Philip
Morris and R.J. Reynolds to each pay $10 million to Leslie Whiteley
and her husband. The same jury awarded the couple $1.7 million in
compensation last week after finding that the companies deceived
the public about the dangers of smoking. That verdict was the first
for a smoker who took up the habit after the surgeon general's
warnings first appeared on cigarette packages in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC Discusses Oil Output
</P>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria a (AP) -- Iran accepts the need for OPEC to boost
petroleum output, the Iranian oil minister said Monday, but the
amount of an increase favored by his country might not be enough to
ease prices that have soared to nine-year highs. Iranian Oil
Minister Bijan Namdar Zangeneh spoke prior to a formal gathering of
all 11 OPEC oil ministers, who adjourned their first session late
Monday without reaching a decision on production. Iran is known to
favor boosting output by about 1.2 million barrels a day, which
probably would do little to reduce world oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;G Seeks Bids for Oxydol Brand
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI (AP) -- The Procter &AMP; Gamble Co. is soliciting offers
for its Oxydol brand laundry detergent, a mainstay of the consumer
products giant since 1927. ''Although Oxydol is a highly profitable
and recognized brand, it is no longer a strategic fit for us,''
Paul Polman, president of P&AMP;G's Global Fabric Care division, said
today. ''We are putting more focus against building brands that
offer the greatest potential for global growth.'' The
Cincinnati-based P&AMP;G, which also owns the top-selling detergent
Tide, said it would retain the Oxydol brand if it does not get an
acceptable offer.
</P>
<P>
   German Auto Mergers Round Out Lines
</P>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Alliances announced today by
DaimlerChrysler AG and Volkswagen AG take Europe's two largest
automakers in opposite directions toward the same goal -- rounding
out their product lines to stay alive in the latest round of global
consolidation. DaimlerChrysler shelled out $2 billion for a 34
percent stake in Japan's Mitsubishi Motors Corp., giving the German
automaker new inroads in Asia but also the technical edge needed to
push its new line of smaller, more fuel efficient cars. Likewise,
Volkswagen, known for subcompact hits like the Beetle, filled in a
big gap as it laid out $1.6 billion for a controlling stake in
Swedish bus and truck maker Scania AB.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese Women in Work Force Decline
</P>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The number of Japanese women in the work force
declined for the first time in 24 years, according to a government
report today. It blamed the country's economic slump for a fall of
120,000 to 27.6 million in the number of women who have jobs or are
actively seeking them. The Labor Ministry's White Paper on Women
also said unemployment among Japanese women rose to an all-time
high of 4.5 percent in 1999, up from 4.0 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   French Stock Market the Most Active
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The French stock market started the week
bullishly, in contrast to declines today on other key European
exchanges. The French Cabinet reshuffle, which elevated former
Premier Laurent Fabius to the finance portfolio, and reports of
further consolidation in the French telecom and media sectors
pushed the CAC 40 index up 1.4 percent to 6,450.85. Elsewhere in
Europe, London's Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was
down 0.8 percent to 6,687.2; Frankfurt's Xetra DAX Index was down
0.5 percent, at 7,892.49, and Italy's MIB30 index was off 0.2
percent to 32,819. The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index was up 0.92
points at 454.64 points. The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of shares in
European companies rose 0.01 points, to 402.37 points.
</P>
