<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Closing Arguments in Sharif's Trial  </HEADLINE>
By ZAHID HUSSAIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) -- The lawyer for Pakistan's deposed prime
minister wound up closing arguments Monday, saying prosecutors
failed to prove that Nawaz Sharif refused to allow an airplane
carrying the country's military chief to land.
</P>
<P>
   Khwaja Sultan tried to discredit prosecution witnesses and spent
much of the day reading out their written statements and court
testimony, citing discrepancies over persons named and the timing
of events.
</P>
<P>
   ''The prosecution has failed miserably to provide any
circumstantial evidence of hijacking,'' said Sultan, who represents
Sharif and four others charged with hijacking, terrorism, attempted
murder and kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the other two codefendants were scheduled to give
separate closing arguments Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The seven are accused of endangering the life of army chief Gen.
Pervez Musharraf by refusing to give his airliner permission to
land in the southern city of Karachi. The standoff occurred during
an Oct. 12 coup in which the military seized power in Pakistan
after Sharif dismissed Musharraf.
</P>
<P>
   Sultan earlier had argued that Musharraf was responsible for
putting the 198 passengers and crew at risk because he had ordered
his plane to remain aloft until his troops secured the airport. The
aircraft landed with only seven minutes of fuel remaining, the
pilot has testified.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict and sentencing by the antiterrorist court is
expected next week. The charges carry mandatory death sentences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-27-00 1729 </TRAILER>
