<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Friendly Ice Cream closing 150 restaurants  </HEADLINE>
By TRUDY TYNAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILBRAHAM, Mass. (AP) -- Friendly Ice Cream Corp. announced
Monday that it was closing nearly a quarter of the 604 Friendly's
restaurants in an attempt to boost returns.
</P>
<P>
   The company said 80 underperforming restaurants in 12 states
were shut immediately and another 70 would be closed over the next
two years. Twelve of the closed restaurants are on Long Island, one
is in Rockaway, Queens and three are in Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a crucial step towards strengthening the company's
core restaurant business,'' said Donald N. Smith, chairman and
chief executive officer, who organized a buyout of the publicly
held company from Hershey Foods in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The 65-year-old chain is also eliminating 110 administrative and
managerial jobs, including 40 out of a total of 400 at its
corporate headquarters in this Springfield suburb.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant workers would be offered jobs at other nearby
restaurants owned by the chain, said Vivian Brooks, a company
spokeswoman. ''All are within a mile or two of other Friendly's
restaurants,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The 80 closed restaurants had average sales of $520,000 last
year compared to average sales for the chain as a whole of
$958,000, she said. Excluding the closed restaurants, Friendly's
restaurants had average sales of $1.1 million in 1999, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a weeding out, but this is a company that is in trouble
with its performance and they are taking steps to produce a return
on investments,'' said Richard Papiernik, financial editor of
Nation's Restaurant News, a trade publication.
</P>
<P>
   Friendly's isn't alone, he said.
</P>
<P>
   With some notable exceptions, the entire ''family dining''
segment of the restaurant business, including such chains as
Friendly's and Denny's, has been struggling for the past two years,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, they have been squeezed by competition from
fast-food and ''casual dining'' chains, such as Applebee's and
Chili's, which offer additional amenities at a slight increase in
price, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Friendly's reported total revenues of $709 million during 1999,
up from $678 million in 1998, and a net income of $400,000 or 5
cents a share for 1999, compared to a loss of $5 million or 67
cents a share for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Friendly's sold 29 of its restaurants in New York to
a franchisee based in Rochester, N.Y. Currently about 100 of its
604 restaurants are owned by franchisees.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurants closed Monday were are all company owned and
included 27 in New York, 12 in Connecticut, 11 each in
Massachusetts and Ohio, five each in New Jersey and Pennsylvania,
three in Maryland, two in Rhode Island, and one each in Florida,
New Hampshire, Virginia and Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it expected an $18 million pretax write-down of
property and equipment and a $12 million restructuring charge in
the first quarter, because of the closings and an additional $8
million pretax savings because of its headquarters restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   The company did not release the locations of the 70 additional
restaurants that are to be closed. The company operates restaurants
in 15 states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-27-00 1757 </TRAILER>
