<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP May Add $4B for Defense Spending  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republican leaders have opened the door
to tacking $4 billion for additional Pentagon spending to a $9
billion bill to finance U.S. efforts in Colombia and Kosovo, House
aides said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   When the House debates the spending bill Wednesday, pro-defense
legislators will be allowed to offer an amendment to add the extra
military funds, said GOP aides, who spoke on condition of
anonymity. The amendment, with the support of House Speaker Dennis
Hastert, R-Ill., and other GOP leaders, and the overall bill are
expected to be approved, the aides said.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, for the fiscal year that runs through Sept. 30,
faces an uncertain fate in the Senate. The majority leader, Sen.
Trent Lott, R-Miss., considers the price tag too big.
</P>
<P>
   House leaders want to plow ahead anyway in hopes of reaching
agreement with the Senate, if even for a pared-down bill, aides
said. The extra defense money could be a chit for such
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The added defense money also is aimed at satisfying House
defense hawks. In behind-the-scenes efforts last week that
ultimately failed, they tried to add $15 billion to the $307
billion included for the military last week in the overall budget
for 2001, which begins Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   With their support, the House approved the budget Friday by a
211-207 margin. It contains $307 billion for defense, about $17
billion more than this year.
</P>
<P>
   The extra money is to be for Pentagon readiness and health-care
expenses, said an aide. Additional details were not immediately
available.
</P>
<P>
   Although the extra Pentagon funds would make pro-defense
legislators happy, it would further incense many other
conservatives who have said that even the $9 billion version of the
legislation is too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ''They've thrown everything but the kitchen sink into this''
bill, said conservative Rep. Pete Hoekstra, R-Mich., ''and it looks
like they're getting close to throwing the kitchen sink in as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Pentagon, the bill already contains $2 billion for costs
of U.S. peacekeepers in Kosovo; $1.6 billion for the military's
higher-than-expected fuel bill; and $854 million for the Pentagon's
embattled health-insurance system.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also has $2.2 billion for recovery costs from last
autumn's Hurricane Floyd and other domestic natural disasters, $1.7
billion to help the Colombian government's battle against drug
traffickers and its left- and right-wing allies, and other items.
</P>
<P>
   Lott has said he would prefer to scrap the legislation. He would
provide money for Colombia and Kosovo instead in spending bills
Congress will consider later this year for 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Senate Budget Committee Chairman Pete Domenici,
R-N.M., has all but settled a dispute with conservatives that had
delayed his plans to push a $1.8 trillion budget for 2001 through
his committee. The panel will begin considering the spending plan
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, a leader of the conservative group and
a member of the committee, had demanded procedural controls on
spending as the price for his vote. Without it, Domenici could not
push his budget through the committee, where unanimous Democratic
opposition is expected.
</P>
<P>
   Among procedures Domenici and Gramm agreed to is a $14 billion
limit on spending included in the 2001 budget that would count as
spending for 2002, not 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Crediting spending to a later year is a way of easing spending
pressure in a budget. The budget for fiscal 2000 counted $23
billion toward 2001. The House-approved budget for 2001 also would
allow up to $23 billion to be counted in 2002.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
