<HEADLINE> Life Sentence in Bounty-Hunter Case  </HEADLINE>
BY ELISA BONGIOVANNI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- A man who murdered a couple after posing as a
bounty hunter was sentenced Monday to life in prison without the
possibility of parole.
</P>
<P>
   David Brackney, 47, was one of five masked men who claimed to be
in search of a California bail jumper when they burst into the
couple's home in August 1997, according to prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Foote, 25, shot at the men as they tried to break
down his bedroom door. Brackney and the group's ringleader, Michael
Sanders, then fatally shot Foote and Spring Wright, 19, in the
couple's bed, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers claimed the men were on a legitimate bounty
hunting mission. But prosecutors noted that the bond they claimed
to be enforcing had expired and said bounty hunting was used merely
as a ruse to ransack Foote's house.
</P>
<P>
   The killings prompted a new Arizona law requiring bounty hunters
to be licensed and to get permission from a home's occupants before
entering
</P>
<P>
   Tom Foote Sr., Christopher Foote's father, said he was ''tickled
to death'' with Brackney's sentence: two consecutive life terms for
the murders plus 90 years for other felony charges.
</P>
<P>
   ''It won't bring my son back, but at least we are getting
justice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders was sentenced last year to two consecutive life prison
terms while another defendant pleaded guilty to second-degree
murder and awaits sentencing. The two other men, including
Brackney's 22-year-old son Matthew, are awaiting trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
