<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Off 86.87; Nasdaq Off 4.47  </HEADLINE>
By EILEEN GLANTON, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Microsoft deflated every major stock market
index Monday, falling sharply after the government reportedly
rejected the company's offer to settle their antitrust case.
Microsoft's decline masked strength in other technology issues.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 86.87 to close at
11,025.85. The blue-chip index lost an early gain due to
Microsoft's weakness and profit-taking in the financial shares that
soared last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index fell 4.47 to 4,958.56, and the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 3.60 to 1,523.86. Trading was quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, the most actively traded Nasdaq stock, fell 7| to 104
1/16, accounting for nearly 40 points of the Dow's decline. Sources
have told The Associated Press that government lawyers have
concluded Microsoft's offer to settle their antitrust case was
inadequate, and they are preparing for U.S. District Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson to deliver a verdict as early as Tuesday. Jackson
has previously hinted he will rule against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Microsoft shares rose as much as 12 percent amid
reports the company was nearing a settlement with the government.
</P>
<P>
   ''Microsoft ran way up in anticipation of some good news over
the weekend,'' said Scott Bleier, chief investment strategist at
Prime Charter Ltd. ''Did it get ahead of itself? Yes. Investors are
still waiting to see what the government has to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Many other technology companies advanced.
</P>
<P>
   IBM rose 6\ to 126~ after Morgan Stanley Dean Witter raised its
rating on the stock from ''neutral'' to ''outperform.'' Cisco
Systems gained 11/16 to 80 1/16 and Sun Microsystems rose 4} to 105
as portfolio managers scrambled to add them to their portfolios
before the end of the first quarter on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The stocks that are the institutional favorites continue to
power higher,'' Bleier said. ''There's a major markup of large-cap
technology stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks before companies begin reporting their
first-quarter earnings, technology stocks are likely to lead the
market as investors buy them on the promise of strong earnings
growth, said John H. Shaughnessy, chief investment strategist at
Advest Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe stock selection should continue to focus on those
companies with strong earnings momentum,'' he said. ''This would
include technology stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   The earnings reporting season will gather momentum in mid-April.
Until then, traders said the market may stay in a fairly narrow
trading range with no clear catalyst to spark a major swing in
either direction.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of oil producers traded actively as OPEC oil ministers
adjourned the first session of their meeting in Vienna without
reaching an agreement on production increases. OPEC members are
considering raising production by 1.5 million to 1.7 million
barrels a day, which would bring oil prices down from nine-year
highs.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon Mobil fell 47/64 to 76 33/64 and BP Amoco was down 1| to
49.
</P>
<P>
   Investment bank Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette dropped 9 9/16 to
57} after Morgan Stanley Dean Witter analyst Henry McVey downgraded
the stock to ''neutral'' from ''outperform.'' McVey cited concerns
that DLJ may have reached a peak in valuation.
</P>
<P>
   Other financial stocks, which rose after the Federal Reserve
announced its decision to raise interest rates modestly last
Tuesday, fell as investors took profits. American Express was down
5[ at 150{. Goldman Sachs fell 9 5/16 to 112.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 4-to-3 margin on the
NYSE, where consolidated volume totaled 1.10 billion shares,
compared with 1.25 billion in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 0.36 to 573.65.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 1.1 percent.
Germany's DAX index fell 0.5 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 lost 0.8
percent, and France's CAC-40 closed 1.4 percent higher.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
