<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congress May Compromise on HMOs  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID ESPO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional negotiators have made quiet
progress toward agreement on an appeals process for patients who
contend they were wrongly denied care by their HMO, a key
unresolved issue on a broader health bill, officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said staff
aides for Republicans and Democrats worked through the weekend and
during the day Monday. The goal was to forge an agreement on the
issue for presentation to lawmakers within a few days, they added.
</P>
<P>
   With no guarantee of success, negotiators are trying to draft
language to serve as a standard for use in determining whether a
denial of care should be reversed.
</P>
<P>
   In general, aides are discussing a two-step appeals process. The
first step would be under auspices of the HMO. A second, open to
some but not all patients whose internal appeals were denied, would
be conducted by an independent expert.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional aides in both parties said negotiators had not yet
agreed in what circumstances, if any, an independent reviewer
should be able to order coverage as medical necessity, even if it
were not required in the HMO's contract. Negotiators also were
trying to agree on a timetable for reviews.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not done, but there's been some progress,'' said Dennis
Fitzgibbons, a spokesman for Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich. He said
''nothing is secured'' until all points are in agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are making progress,'' said Gayle Osterberg, an aide Sen.
Don Nickles, R-Okla., who is chairing the formal House-Senate
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Sen. Edward M. Kennedy and Rep. Bill Thomas said they
had no information to offer.
</P>
<P>
   The HMO measure is one of the most contentious and political
important issues before Congress. President Clinton and many
Democrats favor legislation to grant numerous federal protections
to all Americans with private health insurance. Republicans
generally favor fewer federal protections, for a smaller group of
insured.
</P>
<P>
   The political situation is complicated, however, in that
dissident Republicans joined with Democrats and approved the White
House-blessed bill in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Aides in both parties said resolution of a review process could
be critical to passage of an overall deal on so-called ''patients
bill of rights'' legislation. One Democrat expressed surprise at
how forthcoming Republicans have been in seeking compromise in
recent days. Two Republicans suggested that resolution of the
external review snag would clear the way for further compromises.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, aides to lawmakers in both parties talked of a
possible tradeoff between Republican-backed provisions to make
health care more affordable and accessible on the one hand, and the
Democratic desire to extend patient protections to all Americans
with insurance.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, officials said compromise on a right to sue might
also become more feasible.
</P>
<P>
   The current round of discussions began Thursday as Republicans
presented an outline to Democrats for both an internal and external
review.
</P>
<P>
   Key lawmakers are tentatively scheduled to meet Thursday to
review staff-drafted compromises on access to care by specialists
and continuity of care after a patient's doctor has been dropped by
an HMO or a patient's employer has switched HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators earlier agreed on access to emergency room care.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-27-00 1810 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000327.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Davidians: Suit Should Include Agent  </HEADLINE>
By MICHELLE MITTELSTADT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- An FBI sharpshooter who is the only named
defendant in the wrongful-death lawsuit filed against the federal
government by relatives of Branch Davidians killed in the 1993 Waco
siege should not be dismissed from the case, one set of Davidians
said in a court filing Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the plaintiffs, who are represented by lead counsel
Michael Caddell, moved earlier this month to dismiss their case
against Lon Horiuchi, saying there was ''no credible'' evidence he
fired shots at the Davidians.
</P>
<P>
   But another group of Davidians, represented by former Attorney
General Ramsey Clark, said in a filing Monday in federal court in
Waco, Texas, that it would be ''premature'' to dismiss Horiuchi,
who gained notoriety in 1992 when he killed the wife of white
separatist Randy Weaver during a standoff at Ruby Ridge, Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   ''The facts are not fully known and are being developed,'' the
motion says, noting the government's conduct at Waco remains under
''intense investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It may well turn out that government agents fired at Branch
Davidians on April 19, 1993, and engaged in other serious
misconduct, including coverup and spoliation of evidence,'' the
Clark-represented group contends, offering no evidence to back up
their charges.
</P>
<P>
   Horiuchi's government lawyers say there is not a ''shred of
evidence'' he fired his weapon on April 19.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials say their agents fired no shots on the final
day of the seven-week siege, which ended when the Davidians'
retreat erupted into flames several hours into an FBI tear-gas
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Davidian leader David Koresh and some 80 followers died during
the inferno, some from the fire, others from gunshot wounds. The
government contends they died by their own hand.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs, whose civil suit goes to trial in mid-May, argue
that FBI infrared surveillance tapes taken during the final hours
offer definitive proof of government gunfire into the building as
it burned -- a charge the government denies.
</P>
<P>
   The Caddell-represented plaintiffs, in moving to dismiss
Horiuchi, said a forensic analysis of spent shell casings found at
the outpost occupied by Horiuchi's sniper team indicate the bullets
were ''most likely'' fired by agents of the Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms during the initial Feb. 28 gun battle that
began the 51-day siege.
</P>
<P>
   Separately Monday, the government asked U.S. District Judge
Walter Smith for temporary custody of the FBI's 1993 infrared
videotapes, which currently are in the hands of Waco special
counsel John Danforth. The move follows Caddell's accusation that
some of the evidence turned over by the government has been
withheld, tampered with or destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Although many of the allegations are baseless on their face,
in order to respond, the United States must have its own experts
examine the (Forward Looking Infrared) videotapes,'' the motion
says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
