<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: French Colonel Under Fire  </HEADLINE>
By PIERRE-ANTOINE SOUCHARD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- A French colonel was detained Monday on suspicion
he had leaked state secrets to the media about French peacekeepers
in the troubled Yugoslav province of Kosovo, judicial sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The classified documents described bitterness among some
peacekeepers toward Bernard Kouchner, U.N. administrator for
Kosovo. They also highlighted rifts within French forces in Kosovo
-- between the army and the gendarmerie, a national police forced
controlled by the Defense Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Michel Mechain, a colonel in the gendarmerie, was placed in
provisional detention and under investigation for ''divulging a
secret pertinent to national defense,'' according to judicial
sources who spoke on customary condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   If found guilty, Mechain, 46, could face seven years in prison
and a fine of $104,000. Mechain has said he is not guilty of
leaking the documents, and has not yet been formally charged in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Mechain's lawyer said Monday he would appeal the detention
order, probably before the end of this week. ''Placing someone in
detention for an intellectual offense is a monstrosity,'' lawyer
William Bourdon said.
</P>
<P>
   Mechain was the ''victim of a political-military controversy,''
Bourdon said.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper Le Monde reported Monday that Mechain planned to
ask that his military obligation to keep silent be lifted so that
he can defend himself against all accusations.
</P>
<P>
   A judicial inquiry was launched just over a week ago to find out
how two French weeklies got hold of the classified papers.
</P>
<P>
   According to the documents, Kouchner, who is French, was
perceived by French officers in Kosovo as anti-Serb and
pro-Albanian. The accounts were published in February by the news
magazine Le Point and the satirical newspaper Le Canard Enchaine.
</P>
<P>
   Mechain, a former judicial counselor to a French general in
Pristina, was abruptly recalled from Kosovo in mid-February.
Defense Minister Alain Richard said last week that ''there were
reasons not to keep him there,'' but did not specify those reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The colonel, who was judicial counselor to a French general in
Pristina, was detained for questioning on Friday, just days after a
bizarre street brawl linked to the leaks.
</P>
<P>
   A French female translator of Albanian origin, who had worked
with Mechain in Kosovo, was also held for questioning but released
on Saturday, judicial sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper reports have said the woman, like the colonel, is a
prime suspect in the leaks.
</P>
<P>
   Mechain came to blows last Monday night with investigators from
the Army's Defense Protection and Security unit, who were tailing
him as part of an internal inquiry into the leaks.
</P>
<P>
   Mechain filed a complaint after he was struck by one of the
eight men tailing him as he walked the woman home. Mechain struck
back, leading to two judicial complaints.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-27-00 1825 </TRAILER>
