<HEADLINE> Jets Owner Honors Keyshawn Contract  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY WILNER, AP Football Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Woody Johnson, the new owner of the New
York Jets, believes in the sanctity of a contract. That means he
thinks star receiver Keyshawn Johnson shouldn't be threatening a
holdout.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is a member of the team and has a contract with the team,''
Woody Johnson said Monday at the NFL's annual meetings. ''I think
contracts are a part of this society and contracts are important.
</P>
<P>
   ''You promise to do something and sign an agreement and you can
take that for what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Monday, coach Al Groh reiterated the team's intent not
to trade Keyshawn Johnson, who has two years remaining on his
contract. Nor do the Jets plan to renegotiate.
</P>
<P>
   The receiver believes he is underpaid and his agent, Jerome
Stanley, has cited the seven-year, $42 million contract Dallas gave
Joey Galloway, whose career numbers are similar to Johnson's.
</P>
<P>
   Keyshawn Johnson's deal averaged $2 million for the next two
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley sounded surprised when told of Woody Johnson's comments,
and had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   New York's offseason conditioning program has begun and Keyshawn
has not reported. The team has its first veterans' minicamp in May,
and unless progress is made on a new contract, it is unlikely the
receiver will attend.
</P>
<P>
   Woody Johnson has said he will leave all football decisions to
the likes of chief of operations Bill Parcells and Groh. He also
emphasized how close to the salary cap limit the Jets are, although
reportedly they have $2 million to spend. Of course, most of that
money must go to draft choices, including the team's two
first-rounders.
</P>
<P>
   ''We like Keyshawn, he is a great player. He is an impact
player,'' the owner said. ''But I don't think anyone can break a
season or a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Johnson wasn't involved in the NFL last year, he can be
excused for overlooking how the Jets' season was ruined when
quarterback Vinny Testaverde tore his Achilles' tendon in the
opening game. The same thing happened in Atlanta when Jamal
Anderson was hurt, and in Denver when John Elway retired.
</P>
<P>
   The owner was asked about the distractions created when a team's
best player threatens a holdout.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our job is to provide and field the best team and create
incentives for the team to achieve success,'' he said. ''I don't
think it is up to one player to determine if we fail or succeed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
