<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate to amend bill forcing parents to pay if kid sounds falsealarm  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY PARELLO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Parents, not taxpayers, should foot the
bill when their child sounds a false alarm, calling out bomb
squads, fire trucks and police, a state Senator said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But, there should also be an exception for parents who have done
everything right -- and still managed to raise an incorrigible
child, said Sen. John Matheussen, R-Gloucester.
</P>
<P>
   So, Matheussen decided to hold his bill, which was up for a
Senate vote Monday, that would have allowed towns and school
districts to sue parents for the cost of responding to a false bomb
threat, fire alarm or call to 911.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to work to see if we can come up with some form of a
compromise,'' said Matheussen. ''There are exceptions, and
sometimes a parent can do all they possibly can do, and yet still a
child goes wrong. And we want to make some exceptions for when that
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, taxpayers should not have to pay when parents
neglect their responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ''When that false alarm is pulled and that bomb scare goes off,
your taxpayers are paying, on average, about $7,500 for that one
day,'' Matheussen told his fellow senators. ''Now parents aren't
responsible, but taxpayers are.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill comes at a time when false alarms in schools are
increasing -- along with a rising cry for parents to be held
accountable for their children's actions.
</P>
<P>
   False bomb threats more than doubled from the 1996-1997 school
year to the 1997-1998 school year, going from 74 to 173, according
to Peter Peretzman, spokesman for the state education department.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for the increase was a spate of bogus threats
in one Camden County school district, Peretzman said, but he
couldn't say exactly how much of the increase was due to that one
district's troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Some think making parents pay is a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a cost,'' said Kenneth Trump, president of the
National School Safety and Security Service in Cleveland, Ohio.
''It's lost instructional time. It's heightened fear and panic.
It's costing you to mobilize the police. There should be some cost
attached to it and there should be a strong effort to make somebody
pay for it, whether it's the offender or the parent.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Belluscio, spokesman for the New Jersey School Boards
Association, said the association supports the measure, calling it
a natural extension of a 20-year-old court decision that allowed
school districts to seek restitution for vandalism.
</P>
<P>
   ''If a district closes for a day and loses the services of its
staff, that can be costly,'' said Belluscio.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Muniz, security chief in the Willingboro School District,
said students often don't realize that what they're doing is
against the law. Since September, the Burlington County school
district has had 11 bomb threats or other acts of violence.
</P>
<P>
   Muniz said a law holding parents accountable would show students
the seriousness of sounding a false alarm and could prevent some
kids from playing the prank.
</P>
<P>
   Others say there are other ways to prevent false alarms.
</P>
<P>
   Schools can take simple steps, such as installing caller I.D.,
said Trump.
</P>
<P>
   ''People are amazed to see that kids call from home or from a
pay phone in school,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   School officials should also publicize the penalties, Trump
said.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, juveniles can face jail time for a bomb threat.
They can also lose their driver's license for six months -- or have
to wait an additional six months to get a license if they're under
17 when they commit the crime, said Lee Moore, spokesman for the
attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   Also, adults should see the prank as a signal that a child might
need help.
</P>
<P>
   ''If a kid has made a bomb threat, the most important issue is
not getting money for the bomb threat,'' said James Fiscus of the
National Resource Center for Safe Schools in Portland, Ore. ''The
most important issue is getting help for the kid. That's one of the
real warning signs of trouble with that child and potentially with
that family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-27-00 1902 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
