<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cancun Takes Mexico Out of Break  </HEADLINE>
By NIKO PRICE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANCUN, Mexico (AP) -- Beyond the McDonald's, beyond the
Houlihan's, beyond the Papa John's Pizza, the Outback Steakhouse
and the Subway sandwiches, Cancun has a restaurant that serves
Mexican food.
</P>
<P>
   It's called Planet Hollywood, and if you look hard on the menu,
among the hamburgers and barbecued ribs there's a listing for
''Sizzling Fajitas.''
</P>
<P>
   As it quickly becomes a top Spring break destination, this
resort on Mexico's Caribbean coast is missing one element: even the
vaguest trace of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you go to vacation in Mexico, you want to get away from
it all. But this is just like back home,'' griped Matt Leiszler, a
19-year-old freshman from Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   More than 70,000 American college students have descended on
Cancun over the past month, leading many travel agents to dub the
resort the new capital of Spring break.
</P>
<P>
   The kids eat at American restaurants, shop at American stores
and grind the night away in discos whose DJs don't stock a single
Mexican CD.
</P>
<P>
   Hosts at the nightclubs don't ask which country people are from
-- they ask which state. And the contestants at the wet T-shirt
competitions are representing places like Chicago, Los Angeles and
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Mexicans, who in general are more socially conservative than
Americans, grimace at the writhing, semi-naked bodies at the
discos.
</P>
<P>
   ''I see this as the 51st state,'' said Miko Chavez, a Mexico
City native who works as an ''animator'' at the Melia Cancun Hotel,
organizing volleyball games and dispensing pingpong paddles at the
pool.
</P>
<P>
   For many visiting Americans, the U.S.-friendly atmosphere is one
of the resort's main draws.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you're bringing kids down, they have limited repertoires
of what they can eat,'' said Tom Retzinger, a doctor from Winona,
Minn., who accompanied his high-school daughter for a bit of fun in
the sun.
</P>
<P>
   His destination: The Hard Rock Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the students complain that they came down for a
taste of Mexico -- and found nothing but America on the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Leiszler said in his first three days in Cancun, the only
Mexicans he had a chance to talk to were the drivers of the taxis
he rode in. All spoke perfect English.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I'm going to Mexico, I'd like it to be more Mexican,'' said
Amir Redakhorshad, a 20-year-old junior at West Virginia University
in Morgantown.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason Cancun is so American is that it was built
not from a Mexican beach town -- but from nothing. Until 1970, this
L-shaped sand bar off the Yucatan Peninsula was barren.
</P>
<P>
   In a frenzy of government-sponsored construction that took place
over the screams of ecologists, Cancun has become one of the
world's top tourist destinations.
</P>
<P>
   ''Idaho in the house!'' the host screamed at one local disco as
he bent down from the stage to pour tequila into a conga line of
open mouths yelling out their hometowns.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the students said Cancun broadened their horizons by
allowing them to meet people from different places. Places like
Omaha, Nebraska, and Escanaba, Michigan, that is.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a good mixture of people,'' said Kate Roberts, a
21-year-old junior at the University of Tennessee at Knoxville.
''They come from all over the United States.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-27-00 1908 </TRAILER>
