<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bill to preserve high sheriffs passes to House  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK, Associated Press Writer
o0076nyc--
u n AM-CT-XGR--SheriffsShowd 1stLd-Writethru   03-27 0378
AM-CT-XGR--Sheriffs Showdown, 1st Ld-Writethru,340   
Bill to preserve high sheriffs passes to House   
Eds: SUBS lede to RESTORE dropped word ''proposed''; SUBS 2nd graf
to FIX garble; SUBS 3rd graf to CLARIFY bill does not specify
amount of pay raises   
By ADAM GORLICK
Associated Press Writer
agstf
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- The state's embattled high sheriffs now
have some proposed legislation on their side.
</P>
<P>
   On a 29-18 vote Monday, the Legislature's Appropriations
Committee passed to the House a bill which would maintain the
elected office of high sheriff. Other bills scheduled for debate in
the General Assembly call for a constitutional amendment that would
abolish the job.
</P>
<P>
   The bill passed Monday would make the sheriffs administrators
whose primary responsibilities would include hiring deputies and
special deputies and auditing the deputies. Currently, high
sheriffs also serve legal papers to supplement their incomes. The
bill also says the high sheriffs should get pay raises, but does
not specify how much the increases should be.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also would create Council of High Sheriffs, composed of
the eight elected sheriffs. The council would oversee the system
and set up training programs and standard procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers who want to dismantle the county sheriff system say it
is riddled with corruption and patronage, and want the jobs
performed by deputies and special deputies to be controlled by
state agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Special deputies guard courthouses and transport prisoners.
Deputies serve legal papers such as subpoenas and summonses.
</P>
<P>
   Several scandals during the past year have shaken the sheriffs
system, and two high sheriffs have pleaded innocent to criminal
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the sheriffs say getting rid of the system isn't
the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ''If something goes wrong, we should try to fix it,'' said Rep.
William Dyson, D-New Haven, co-chairman of Appropriations. ''We
shouldn't rectify problems just by getting rid of a whole system.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the bill said it does nothing to address the
problems with the current system.
</P>
<P>
   ''This bill is the one that preserves the system,'' said Rep.
Robert Farr, R-West Hartford. ''If you don't want to change the
system, this is the bill you want.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
