<HEADLINE> Puckett Wins Men's Giant Slalom  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN MOSSMAN, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSON, Wyo. (AP) -- Casey Puckett, refusing to settle for
second place, regrouped after a near crash on his second run to win
the men's giant slalom on Monday in the U.S. Alpine Ski
Championships.
</P>
<P>
   Puckett, 27, of Crested Butte, Colo., had a combined time for
two runs of 2 minutes, 7.40 seconds, just .07 seconds faster than
Erik Schlopy of Park City, Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Daron Rahlves of Truckee, Calif., was third in 2:07.74.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first career race victory at the nationals for
Puckett, who matched the feat of his older brother, Chris, who
posted his first nationals race win in Friday's downhill. Casey won
the national combined title in 1995, and Chris won the combined
three times, but neither had won a race until this year's event.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Puckett finished fourth in 2:08.04, and Jakub Fiala of
Breckenridge, Colo., was fifth in 2:08.54.
</P>
<P>
   Casey Puckett paced the first run in 1:00.78, which was .18
seconds quicker than Rahlves' 1:00.96. Andrew Martin of Warner,
N.H., stood third, .43 seconds off the lead, and Schlopy was
fourth, .57 seconds out.
</P>
<P>
   Warm temperatures created soft snow for the second run, but the
course held up well for the top 30 skiers who raced in reverse
order in the second run.
</P>
<P>
   Schlopy had the fastest time in the second run of 1:06.12 for an
aggregate time of 2:07.47 that momentarily took the lead. Martin
and Rahlves couldn't dislodge him from the top spot, but Casey
Puckett came across in 1:06.62 -- the third-fastest clocking of the
second heat despite nearly losing control.
</P>
<P>
   ''About halfway down, I went over the Pro Bump and got out of
balance,'' he said. ''I felt like I was upside down. I was in the
strangest position. One of my skis was up in the air. But I had to
keep going. I just barely pulled it out, but that's enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Puckett approached this year's nationals with a goal of winning
and ending his frustrating string of second-place finishes.
</P>
<P>
   ''As many second places as I've had -- I don't know how many -- I
started to think I was never going to win,'' he said. ''I was
always right there, top three, a contender. But I never was able to
get first place. Now I've got it and I'm happy.
</P>
<P>
   ''My mindset coming in here was: I want to win, I don't want
second place.''
</P>
<P>
   Puckett, the 1991 world junior slalom champion who finished
seventh in the slalom in the 1994 Olympics and 12th in a World Cup
giant slalom a year ago, now sets his sights on Wednesday's slalom
-- the concluding event.
</P>
<P>
   Puckett finished eighth in the downhill and second in the
super-G, giving him the inside track on another combined title.
</P>
<P>
   Schlopy, 27, said his half-second deficit after the first run
was too much to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that's where I lost the race, in the first run,''
Schlopy said. ''In the last couple of gates, I stuck my head in a
panel. I could have gone out easily, but I hung tough. It's better
to get second than go out, so I'm happy.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the second run, I made up a lot of time on the bottom half
of the course. But I didn't think it would be good enough to win.
Five-tenths is a lot to make up on this course.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was close.
</P>
<P>
   ''Seven-hundredths,'' Schlopy said. ''I mean, that's half an
arm's length.''
</P>
<P>
   The women's giant slalom is scheduled for Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
