<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Whitman wants constitutional amendment to help identify sexoffenders  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- The state's constitution must be changed to
allow ready access to information about sex offenders on the
Internet ''to ensure the safety of our community,'' Gov. Christie
Whitman said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey would join more than a dozen other states where
details about sex offenders -- including name, address and criminal
record -- are just a point and click away.
</P>
<P>
   Without a constitutional amendment, any legislative action, like
a vote Monday by the Assembly to create an Internet registry of sex
offenders, would be rejected by the courts, Whitman said. Judges
have ruled that information about sex offenders is generally
private and community notifications allowed by the law must be
strictly limited and controlled.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said there is a growing public demand for such
information and with the advent of the Internet, the state must
''take the next step'' to get those details into the community.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have always been sensitive to the privacy issue of the
court. But we're more sensitive to the privacy issue of the
community,'' Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whether you are hiring a new baby-sitter, Little League coach
or camp counselor, you will be able to use the Internet to confirm
that the person is not a convicted sex offender,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   If approved by the Legislature and then by voters, Whitman said
the amendment would give the public ''the maximum amount of
information to ensure the safety of the community.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's Megan's Law categorizes convicted sex offenders into
three levels, based on the perceived risk they present of
committing another sex crime.
</P>
<P>
   For those considered to pose a minimal risk, the amendment would
let the public submit a person's name and one other piece of
information, such as his home address, to see the Internet registry
about him.
</P>
<P>
   For those considered at moderate or high risk of re-offending,
the public simply would have to access the Internet registry. The
registry would contain the offender's name and aliases, any Megan's
Law offenses committed, his age, race, date of birth, height,
weight, hair and eye color, address and a photograph.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have pretty full disclosure now. This is making it easier
for people to access that information,'' Whitman told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, for those considered at least risk, prosecutors tell
police departments that the offender is living in the community.
For those perceived to be at moderate or high risk of reoffending,
the law allows prosecutors to provide an offender's name, address
and photo to residents, schools and day care centers in a carefully
defined area.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're talking about taking it another step,'' the governor
said, calling the amendment ''open enough'' to use the Internet and
any other new communication methods. It would be up to the
Legislature to decide the exact details of how the registry would
work.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly voted 55 to 0, with 16 members abstaining, to pass
a bill sponsored by Assemblyman Joel Weingarten, R-Essex, to create
an Internet registry of sex offenders.
</P>
<P>
   The governor gave her amendment to both houses of the
Legislature and she also submitted legislation directing the
superintendent of the State Police to prepare the Internet
registry.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said she was confident that the legislation would be
acceptable to federal courts.
</P>
<P>
   ''Other states have been doing this and not run into a
problem,'' the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest court challenge, a federal judge said in December
that authorities routinely allowed private information about sex
offenders to become public during community notifications. The
judge ordered the state to revise its regulations or have the
system shut down.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Attorney General John J. Farmer, Jr. released new
guidelines requiring people who receive notices to sign papers
promising to keep the information secret.
</P>
<P>
   Any amendment must win 27 votes in the Senate and 48 in the
Assembly. Then it must win voter approval in a statewide
referendum. Whitman said the measure would have to pass both houses
by August in order to be on the ballot in November's general
election.
</P>
<P>
   Both Senate President Donald T. DiFrancesco, R-Union, and
Assembly Speaker Jack Collins, R-Salem, said the amendment would
likely win legislative approval.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is for the protection of our children. Certainly people
are calling for additional protection as technology changes,''
DiFrancesco said.
</P>
<P>
   Megan's Law is named for Megan Kanka, a 7-year-old Hamilton
Township girl who was raped and murdered in July 1994 by a
convicted sex offender who lived across the street from her Mercer
County home.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer said at least 15 other states have established publicly
accessible sex offender registries on the Internet, and there are
at least another 80 regional sex offender Internet sites
established by local or regional law enforcement agencies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
