<HEADLINE> Juror Excused in Reggie Lewis Case  </HEADLINE>
By JIMMY GOLEN, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- A doctor being sued in the Reggie Lewis case
sought Monday to dismiss the lawsuit because a magazine article
tainted a prospective juror's views.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Thayer Fremont-Smith denied the request, but did excuse
the prospective juror, who said she had seen news reports in which
the former Boston Celtics star's widow compared herself to the
widows of six firefighters who died in a warehouse fire.
</P>
<P>
   ''You know, I think about those firefighters in Worcester. Lots
of money is being raised for those families, and I need to be taken
care of, too,'' Donna Harris-Lewis told Boston Magazine for its
April issue. ''Everybody has to say I'm greedy. But I do want my
money back this time around. Why should I lose?''
</P>
<P>
   Jury selection began Monday for the second malpractice trial of
Dr. Gilbert Mudge, whose first trial ended in a deadlocked jury.
Opening arguments are scheduled to begin April 3, and the trial is
expected to last four to five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors were asked the standard questions about whether they had
any relationship with the plaintiffs, defendants or their lawyers.
But they were also asked whether they would not be able to render
an impartial decision because of loyalty to the NBA team; only
three raised their hands.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis collapsed in April 1993 during a Celtics playoff game, and
doctors initially diagnosed the problem as a potentially fatal
heart arrhythmia. But Lewis and his wife were unhappy with the
diagnosis and transferred hospitals, hiring a ''Dream Team,''
including Mudge, who said the player suffered from a benign
fainting disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Mudge publicly pronounced in May 1993 that Lewis could play
basketball ''without limitation.'' On July 27, 1993, Lewis
collapsed at the Celtics' practice facility and died.
</P>
<P>
   Harris-Lewis sued four doctors for malpractice. John D.
Rutherford, of the University of Houston, settled the lawsuit out
of court in April 1999 for a reported $500,000; two other doctors,
Mark A. Creager and Peter L. Friedman, were exonerated last year
after a seven-week trial.
</P>
<P>
   But the same jury deadlocked on the claims against Mudge, who
claimed that Lewis admitted shortly before his death that he had
used cocaine. The lawyers said the revelations explained why an
accurate diagnosis of Lewis' condition was impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Harris-Lewis denied the drug use.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
