<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rockies' Cirillo Sidelined  </HEADLINE>
By AARON J. LOPEZ, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- A busy day in the minors may keep Colorado
Rockies third baseman Jeff Cirillo out of the majors on opening
day.
</P>
<P>
   Cirillo, expected to replace Dante Bichette as Colorado's
cleanup hitter, aggravated a strained right quadriceps Monday while
hitting eight times in a minor league game.
</P>
<P>
   ''The leg's not ready,'' Cirillo said. ''There's no pain, but
there's definitely something in there. I almost regret doing this
today. ... I do regret doing it. After my first at-bat, I was like,
'This is probably not a smart idea.' That's where I'm stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   The setback puts Cirillo's status in question for next Monday's
opener against Atlanta. He has missed three straight spring games
and will be out until at least Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Am I concerned about opening day? No. I'm concerned about
getting better in the next three days,'' he said. ''I do all this
other stuff -- exercises and strength work -- and feel fine. When we
get out there and start running and it's quick, it's not there.''
</P>
<P>
   Cirillo's absence hurts Colorado in the field and at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   A steady third baseman, Cirillo hit .326 with 15 home runs and
88 RBIs -- all career bests -- for Milwaukee last year. He was
acquired along with left-handers Scott Karl and Mike Myers in a
nine-player trade in December.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would be a big loss,'' Rockies first baseman Todd Helton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Utility infielders Terry Shumpert and Aaron Ledesma will fill in
at third for now, but manager Buddy Bell still has to figure out
who will protect No. 3 hitter Larry Walker in the batting order.
</P>
<P>
   When asked what would happen if Cirillo is not ready by next
week, Bell said, ''I don't even want to think about that. We're not
considering that at this point. If we get closer, we'll just go
with our extra guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Already without Cirillo, the Rockies got another scare Monday
when second baseman Mike Lansing fouled a ball off his left ankle.
Lansing hobbled off the field but does not expect to miss much
playing time.
</P>
<P>
   ''It didn't swell up too bad,'' Lansing said. ''It's just sore.
Nothing to be alarmed about.''
</P>
<P>
   Shumpert, who is hitting .333 while playing four different
positions this spring, replaced Lansing and homered in the sixth
inning of Colorado's 6-2 victory over the Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Ledesma had a tougher time, twice striking out with one out and
a runner at third.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
