<DOCNO> APW20000327.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Offering Fund-Raising Reforms  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA SOBIERAJ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- When Vice President Al Gore dished up
new-and-improved versions of stale campaign finance reforms on
Monday, he pledged to fight to see them enacted, beseeching
Americans: ''You have to take my word for this.''
</P>
<P>
	   Reform activists said his word was not good enough.
</P>
<P>
	   ''He faces a serious credibility problem about how much he's
committed to this, how much political capital he's willing to spend
on it,'' said Scott Harshbarger, president of Common Cause, which
lobbies for changes in the campaign finance system.
</P>
<P>
	   Harshbarger said Gore has to prove he can do better than Bill
Clinton, who campaigned in 1992 on the issue, ''said all the right
things about giving it priority and did nothing -- except create the
1996 fund-raising scandals.''
</P>
<P>
	   On stage at Marquette University in Milwaukee, Gore proposed
creating a $7.1 billion endowment to pay for House and Senate
campaigns, new disclosure rules for lobbyists and outside groups
that pay for political ads and mandatory free ''rebuttal'' time for
candidates targeted by such third-party ads.
</P>
<P>
	   He acknowledged he was an ''imperfect messenger'' and invoked
purer reformers -- Republican Sen. John McCain, Minnesota Gov. Jesse
Ventura and former Democratic presidential candidate Bill Bradley --
in promising to lead a bipartisan charge for change.
</P>
<P>
	   ''Although you have to take my word for this next point, I
promise you,'' Gore said, campaigning with Wisconsin Sen. Russell
Feingold, sponsor with McCain of the premier campaign finance
reform bill languishing in Congress.
</P>
<P>
	   '' ... Don't doubt for a minute, we can do it, we can do it. We
WILL do it,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
	   Larry Makinson, executive director of the Center for Responsive
Politics, which tracks political money, saw Gore's latest
initiative as ''a big attempt to get the monkey off his back''
before Republican rival George W. Bush inflicts irreparable damage
on the issue.
</P>
<P>
	   Even before Gore spoke Monday, Bush circulated a written
statement pressing Gore anew to release details of his 1996
''mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
	   Without full disclosure of the vice president's fund-raising
phone calls from the White House and cash reception at a Buddhist
temple, ''any promise to reform our campaign finance system will
ring hollow,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore's speech, which he carefully read from a prepared text,
sounded empty to Matt Binsfeld, a 22-year-old engineering senior at
Marquette. ''I think he thinks he can pick up a lot of votes this
way.''
</P>
<P>
	   And although Don Bina, a 68-year-old beef and hog farmer from
Coon Valley, found Gore credible enough on campaign finance reform
-- because, ''Nobody can be perfect all the time,'' he said -- some
political opportunism rang through for him, too.
</P>
<P>
	   ''As the campaign progresses, (Gore and Bush) are out to win the
election and they're going to use whatever they have to do that,''
Bina said.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain, whose battle cry against the corrupting influence of
money in politics nearly toppled Bush in the GOP primaries, piled
on with a statement from his Senate office.
</P>
<P>
	   ''While parts of his proposal merit serious consideration, to
convince a skeptical public that his efforts are sincere and not an
election-year conversion, the vice president needs to back his
words with meaningful, bipartisan action as well as call for a
complete and open investigation of 1996 campaign finance
irregularities,'' McCain said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
	   Elaine Kamarck, policy adviser to the Gore campaign, said Gore
recognized that taxpayer financing of federal elections, the object
of one of his first bills as a freshman congressman from Tennessee
in 1978, has long been a dead-end issue.
</P>
<P>
	   So, said Kamarck, Gore ''carefully crafted the 'Democracy
Endowment' to try to deal with the political impasse.''
</P>
<P>
	   The fund, envisioned as a $7.1 billion pot whose interest income
would finance congressional races, would operate like a university
endowment, collecting corporate and foundation money in exchange
for a 100 percent tax deduction.
</P>
<P>
	   Harshbarger cheered the proposal for meeting ''a lot of the
objections that have been posed to public financing.'' And Makinson
said, Gore ''deserves points for coming up with an idea no one ever
thought of before on an issue that's pretty old.''
</P>
<P>
	   But Makinson doubted that businesses would hand over endowment
contributions ''without a very specific IOU.''
</P>
<P>
	   And the reliance of Gore's plan on free TV air time as a
condition for broadcast licenses is naive, both experts agreed.
</P>
<P>
	   ''I started off this morning thinking this was a great idea but
by this afternoon I'm beginning to find holes in it. Broadcasters
are not going to embrace this with open arms,'' said Makinson.
</P>
<P>
	   ''TV broadcasters have been the most powerful special interest
in defeating even (free air time), which you might think would be
the easiest of campaign reforms,'' Harshbarger said.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore's earlier campaign proposal to reject ''soft money''
spending and replace presidential campaign TV ads with twice weekly
issue debates has been well received by the public, according to a
CBS News poll released Monday. More than six in 10 Americans said
they approved of the idea.
</P>
<P>
	   In the poll, conducted before Gore announced his newest
proposals, people were equally divided on whether the vice
president really wants to change campaign laws or keep them as they
are now.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Associated Press writer Sarah Wyatt contributed
to this report from Wisconsin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-27-00 2000 </TRAILER>
