<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush To Outline Education Proposals  </HEADLINE>
By GLEN JOHNSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- New plans for reading and teacher recruitment
and retention are part of an expanded education focus for George W.
Bush this week, aides to the presumed Republican presidential
nominee said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals also are aimed at fleshing out the Texas
governor's pledge to make education his top priority if elected
president, a contrast to Vice President Al Gore's promise to make
campaign finance his centerpiece.
</P>
<P>
   Education is an issue that polls especially well with women, a
traditionally Democratic group that Bush is courting in his race
against Gore, the Democrats' likely nominee.
</P>
<P>
   During a speech Tuesday at the Reston, Va., headquarters of
Sallie Mae, the nation's largest issuer of student loans, Bush
planned to outline a new reading program and how he would pay for
it.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the federal government offers Even Start, which
provides literacy training to both preschoolers and their parents.
There also is a literacy component to Head Start, as well as adult
literacy training provided under the Vocational Education Act.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a sign of how important reading is, education is and
how both are fundamental parts of the governor's agenda,'' said
Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer.
</P>
<P>
   The governor was detailing the plan to recruit, retrain and
retain teachers on Thursday in Pewaukee, Wis., during a two-day
campaign and fund-raising swing through the state.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who took a day off Monday, was heading out Tuesday for a
two-day East Coast swing through northern Virginia; Parsippany,
N.J.; New York and Baltimore. He also planned to visit Eau Claire,
Milwaukee and Green Bay, Wis., while in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's fund-raisers were expected to raise more than $1.3
million, including $500,000 at a New York luncheon, $450,000 across
the Hudson River in New Jersey and $250,000 in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has delivered three major education speeches since
last fall.
</P>
<P>
   His plans call for spending $5.5 billion over five years,
although its cornerstone is not spending but accountability through
locally designed and administered tests.
</P>
<P>
   He also proposes taking away federal Title I money from poorly
performing schools and giving it to families to help defray the
cost of educating their children elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Gore has proposed spending $115 billion over 10
years to continue President Clinton's program aimed at reducing
class sizes by providing more money to hire teachers. So far, about
30,000 have been hired, with a goal of 100,000. Gore also wants to
triple the number of charter schools, make preschool available to
every 4-year-old and expand Head Start.
</P>
<P>
   Fleischer said Bush will provide the resources to ensure his
focus on accountability.
</P>
<P>
   Without getting into specifics, Fleischer said: ''Accountability
alone won't get the job done. It requires resources. It requires a
new approach. It requires carrots and sticks. If money alone would
improve our schools, we'd already have the best schools in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bush and Gore battle for the title of ''Education
President,'' the two have taken different approaches when it comes
to using public education for their own children.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's children are taught at private schools, while Bush's twin
daughters attend a public high school in Austin, Texas, after
previously studying at private schools.
</P>
<P>
   The audience Tuesday for Bush's speech is an Asian-American
business group, a follow-up to the Hispanic business audience that
sat for his first education speech in California.
</P>
<P>
   ''The governor feels that education is the key to getting a good
job, and these business groups will be the first to tell you that
what they look for in a prospective employee is a good education,
good work habits, good discipline,'' Fleischer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
