<HEADLINE> Governing Party Leads in Mexico  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- The party that has governed Mexico for 71
years still holds a narrow lead in this year's presidential race,
according to two polls published Monday by local newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Both polls showed Francisco Labastida of the Institutional
Revolutionary Party, or PRI, at least slightly ahead of Vicente Fox
of the center-right National Action Party. That represents
relatively little movement from earlier polls heading toward the
July 2 election.
</P>
<P>
   The poll published by the daily Refoma showed Labastida favored
by 39 percent of eligible voters and Fox by 32 percent. That was
the same result as a February survey and almost the same as one in
January, when Labastida had a 40-32 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, conducted March 17-20, had a margin of error 2.5
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The daily El Universal showed Labastida favored by 39.6 percent
-- up slightly from 38 percent in February. Fox was favored by 35
percent, an insignificant slip from 35.3 percent in February. That
poll, conducted March 2-14, also reported a 2.5 percent margin of
error.
</P>
<P>
   Cuauhtemoc Cardenas of the center-left Democratic Revolution
Party was favored by about 11 percent of voters in both polls.
</P>
<P>
   El Universal said that about 12 percent of those questioned
failed to answer its poll. Reforma reported a 17 percent
non-response rate.
</P>
<P>
   A third poll, published over the weekend by the national
magazine Milenio, showed Labastida at 42 percent, Fox at 39 and
Cardenas at 16. Conducted March 17-19, it reported a 2.8 percent
margin of error. It disregarded non-respondents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
