<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Still Hopes for Syrian Accord  </HEADLINE>
By DINA KRAFT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Despite disappointment at the failure of a
U.S.-Syria summit to restart talks between Syria and Israel, Prime
Minister Ehud Barak said Monday he won't close the door on the
prospects of peace with his country's longtime foe.
</P>
<P>
   With a self-imposed July deadline for an Israeli withdrawal from
Lebanon, Barak cannot afford to give up. The Syrians, on the other
hand, are willing to wait instead of take what they call a partial
and unjust withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have not closed the door even today on the continuation of
talks with the Syrians,'' Barak told lawmakers from his One Israel
bloc. He said later that the coming days would reveal whether a
peace deal was possible.
</P>
<P>
   Barak said in an interview with Israel's Channel Two TV Monday
said disagreements centered on whether a withdrawal should give
Syria access to the Sea of Galilee, and security arrangements,
including an Israeli early-warning station on Mount Hermon in the
Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
   In saying so, he indirectly confirmed what has been reported for
months -- that he is willing to meet Assad's demand to return all
land captured in the 1967 Mideast War, except for the shores of the
Galilee.
</P>
<P>
   The Syrians are likely to wait rather than take any deal that
doesn't include some of the shore, according to a Syrian source
close to the talks.
</P>
<P>
   At the weekend summit, President Clinton reportedly told Syrian
President Hafez Assad that a peace settlement may take years if no
deal was reached in the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   ''President Assad responded, 'I am not in a hurry. We are ready
to wait all those years,''' said the source, speaking on condition
of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president won't give up the Sea of Galilee. He has swum in
it, he has had meals by its shore and he has had fish from it,''
said the source. ''Like thousands of Syrian citizens, he has got
links to it.''
</P>
<P>
   A withdrawal from Lebanon without an agreement with Syria, the
main power broker there, is likely to be bloody.
</P>
<P>
   Both Lebanon and Syria have warned that they will not prevent
attacks on Israel from south Lebanon, if there is no comprehensive
peace agreement. Israel and Syria resumed peace talks in December
after a hiatus of nearly four years but they were suspended in
January.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Army chief Shaul Mofaz said that if Israel withdraws
unilaterally from the ''security zone'' it occupies in Lebanon, it
will not give up outposts along the border -- some of which protrude
up to a few hundred yards into Lebanese territory.
</P>
<P>
   Barak said he was aware of the risks of a unilateral withdrawal,
but said that ''in the long run, it will calm the situation.'' He
warned of a harsh Israeli retaliation if Israel is attacked after a
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Mideast envoy Dennis Ross met with Barak Monday to brief
him on Sunday's failed Geneva summit between Clinton and Assad.
</P>
<P>
   Syria's Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa said the summit was
part of U.S. efforts that have so far ''not achieved the hoped for
results.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We were surprised that the U.S. president was not carrying
anything new from the Israeli side, but was asking from Syria what
might help Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak in his difficult
position, which we think is of his own making,'' Sharaa told the
Lebanese newspaper As-Safir.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-27-00 2040 </TRAILER>
