<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feds To Review R.I. Cop Shooting  </HEADLINE>
By JULIE GOODMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) -- Rep. Patrick Kennedy said Monday that a
federal review is under way into the shooting death of a black
policemen shot by two white officers who mistook him for a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Invoking the words of his uncle, President Kennedy, the
Democratic congressman delivered remarks punctuated by clapping,
prayer and song in a crowded Baptist church.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said he spoke with two Department of Justice officials
about Sgt. Cornel Young Jr., the off-duty black officer fatally
shot Jan. 28 by two white officers who mistook him for a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ''Without hesitation ... both men gave me every assurance that
there will be an undeniable and thorough federal review of this
senseless shooting,'' he said of Deputy Attorney General Eric
Holder and Acting Assistant Attorney General for Civil Rights, Bill
Lann Lee.
</P>
<P>
   The long term review will go beyond the preliminary inquiry the
FBI has already opened, Kennedy said. At the end of the review,
officials could enforce civil rights laws even if the state grand
jury investigating the case does not find any criminal wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   At the Congdon Street Baptist Church, the congressman quoted a
1963 speech by President Kennedy, saying ''If an American, because
his skin is dark cannot enjoy the full and free life which all of
us want, then who among us would be content to have the color of
his skin changed and stand in his place?''
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights leaders have repeatedly demanded an independent
investigation into the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-27-00 2044 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000327.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Air Pilots Strike Over Wages  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Pilots at Japan Airlines Co., the nation's largest
carrier, entered a 24-hour strike Tuesday to demand a wage
increase, pilot union officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The walkout will not cause any flight cancellations because
higher-ranking senior pilots will replace the striking pilots for
all scheduled flights for Tuesday, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Phone calls to JAL went unanswered early Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's strike by the 1,330-member JAL Flight Crew Union
affected only flights departing from the international airport at
Narita, just outside Tokyo, and from Haneda airport inside the
capital.
</P>
<P>
   As part of so-called ''spring labor offensive'' negotiations
held annually by Japanese labor unions, the pilots demanded a more
than 3 percent raise, but JAL management refused to comply, said a
union official who demanded anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The striking pilots also demanded that JAL abandon plans to
reduce costs by cutting retirement allowances, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots have threatened to strike again Wednesday if their
demands are not met, a union statement said.
</P>
<P>
   The union declined to disclose average pilot salaries.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese media have in recent weeks reported that JAL, under
pressure to reduce debt, plans to lower salaries in a companywide
cost-cutting program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
