<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Airline, Cargo Handler Plead Guilty  </HEADLINE>
By CATHERINE WILSON, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- A freight airline and a cargo handler pleaded
guilty Monday and agreed to pay $5 million in criminal fines after
an investigation into a 1997 crash that killed five people near
Miami International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Fine Air and cargo handler Aeromar pleaded guilty to a total of
five counts of obstruction of justice and making false statements
during the crash investigation. Attorneys for both stressed that
the pleas do not cover the cause of the crash, attributed to
inexperienced cargo loaders.
</P>
<P>
   The pleas were the first signal that an investigation into the
crash had produced criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   ''These convictions soundly defeat the contention that aircraft
accidents should not be the subject of criminal prosecutions,''
said U.S. Attorney Tom Scott.
</P>
<P>
   In its plea, Fine Air admitted its supervisors ordered
subordinates to change flight weight charts and manifests in the
days after the crash and lied to the FAA about mandated inspections
and corrosion on components.
</P>
<P>
   Aeromar admitted taping over a warehouse surveillance tape
showing crews preparing pallets for the flight and destroying forms
on cargo weight. Although the cargo handler also acknowledged
falsifying pallet weight sheets by at least 3 tons, the DC-8 crash
was blamed on the in-flight movement of unsecured pallets rather
than overweight cargo.
</P>
<P>
   About 45 tons of fabric destined for a blue jeans factory
shifted seconds after takeoff Aug. 7, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Fine Air was responsible for loading the aircraft, but
investigators found Aeromar employees did it at the direction of a
security guard.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plea agreement, no company officers or employees will
be charged, regulators will not pursue additional charges, and both
companies stay in business. U.S. District Judge Joan Lenard can
accept or reject the plea at sentencing June 20.
</P>
<P>
   ''The totality and the finality of the plea made it attractive
to the company,'' said Aeromar attorney Richard Sharpstein. ''It
ends years of speculation after what was purely a tragic
accident.''
</P>
<P>
   Criminal investigations have been rare after commercial crashes.
</P>
<P>
   In December, an aircraft maintenance company implicated in the
1996 ValuJet crash became the first convicted at trial of criminal
charges involving a U.S. commercial jet crash.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Fine Air: http://www.fineair.com/
</P>
<P>
   Federal Aviation Administration: http://www.faa.gov/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
