<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, March 27, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Offering Fund-Raising Reforms
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- At Marquette University in Milwaukee, Vice President Al
Gore proposed creating a $7.1 billion endowment to pay for House and Senate
campaigns, new disclosure rules for lobbyists and outside groups that pay for
political ads and mandatory free ''rebuttal'' time for candidates targeted by
such third-party ads. He acknowledged he was an ''imperfect messenger'' and
invoked purer reformers -- Republican Sen. John McCain and former Democratic
presidential candidate Bill Bradley -- in promising to lead a bipartisan charge
for change.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
OPEC Strives For Production Boost
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- After the first day of meetings, the OPEC oil
ministers failed to reach a consensus about how much crude oil to add to global
supplies. Iran is seen as the chief obstacle to reaching an agreement. Iranian
Oil Minister Bijan Namdar Zangeneh said that although he agrees that a boost is
needed, he does not think that the amount Iran is willing to produce would help
reduce petroleum prices, which have reaches a nine-year high. Iran, OPEC's
second-largest producer, is known to favor boosting output by about 1.2 million
barrels a day -- an amount that probably would do little to reduce world oil
prices.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Israeli-Palestinian Talks Closing
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Israel and the Palestinian Authority are to conclude eight
days of negotiations on Tuesday with little to show in the way of results except
a decision to reconvene here in a few weeks. Still on the table after the
private deliberations at Bolling Air Force Base are the issues that must be part
of an overall settlement and the details of Israel's next scheduled pullback on
the West Bank in June. The two sides are aiming at Sept. 13 as the deadline for
deciding the future of Jerusalem -- the Palestinians want part of the city as a
capital -- and whether Israel will consent to the establishment of a Palestinian
state.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Report: Poor Paying Much for Housing
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- A federal report released today shows that a record number of
working-poor families -- at least 5.4 million -- were paying more than half
their income for housing or living in substandard conditions in 1997. That's an
increase of 12 percent since 1991. The report is being presented to Congress,
which is considering a bill that includes $690 million for 120,000 new rental
assistance vouchers to be distributed in cities nationwide. Housing and Urban
Development officials said incomes for average Americans are growing at a rate
roughly 30 percent greater than incomes for the poorest Americans.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Chemical Plant Explosion Injures 52
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PASADENA, Texas (AP) -- An explosion today rocked a Phillips Petroleum
chemical plant near the Houston Ship Channel, injuring at least 52 people and
sparking a fire that send thick smoke over the area. One man was missing.
Fifty-two people were taken to hospitals with injuries that included burns,
smoke inhalation and anxiety-related disorders. Workers in neighboring plants
and residents in the area were urged to remain indoors while schoolchildren were
kept inside after the bell rang.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Vitamin C May Hurt Cancer Patients
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- Cancer patients who take large doses of vitamin C in the
hope of a cure might actually make their disease worse by inadvertently
protecting their tumors from radiation and chemotherapy, new research suggests.
Doctors caution they cannot prove the vitamin is harmful during cancer
treatment. But they say there are strong biological reasons to think megadoses
could be bad. The concern is based on the discovery that cancer cells actually
contain large amounts of vitamin C, which appears to protect them from oxygen
damage. Many cancer treatments, especially radiation therapy, work by triggering
oxygen damage to the genes of cancer cells.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Off 86.87; Nasdaq Off 4.47
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Microsoft deflated every major stock market index today,
falling steeply after the government reportedly rejected the company's offer to
settle their antitrust case. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 86.87 to
close at 11,025.85. On the NYSE, losers led gainers 1,704-1,284. The Nasdaq
composite index fell 4.47 to 4,958.56. Microsoft, the most actively traded
Nasdaq stock, fell 7| to 104 1/16.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Canucks' Brashear Back at Practice
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BURNABY, British Columbia (AP) -- Donald Brashear practiced today for the
first time since Boston defenseman Marty McSorley's stick attack left the
Vancouver forward with a concussion. Brashear, a 6-foot-2, 225-pound left
winger, hasn't played since McSorley hit him over the head in the closing
seconds of a Feb. 21 game. Canucks coach Marc Crawford said Brashear will join
the team for a three-game road trip that opens Wednesday in Detroit and could
play as early as next week.
</P>
