<HEADLINE> Monday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Bernardo's Hopes for New Trial Dashed
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Paul Bernardo's hopes for a new trial were
abruptly dashed Monday as a three-judge panel dismissed the
notorious sex killer's appeal of his 1995 first-degree murder
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   After a full day of arguments from a battery of defense lawyers,
it took just 15 minutes for the Ontario Court of Appeal to dismiss
the case without so much as a word of rebuttal from the other side.
</P>
<P>
   ''None of us was persuaded that we needed to hear from the
Crown,'' Justice John Laskin told court as Debbie Mahaffy, whose
daughter Leslie was murdered by Bernardo in 1991, smiled broadly.
</P>
<P>
   ''This appeal is dismissed.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel was left unmoved by a series of complicated and often
meandering arguments on supposed errors in law by Justice Patrick
LeSage during Bernardo's four-month trial in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Manning Launches Leadership Bid in Canadian Alliance
</P>
<P>
   CALGARY (AP) -- Calling himself an agent of change who can lead
the Canadian Alliance to power in Ottawa, Preston Manning began the
fight of his political life Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Manning, who led the Reform party from obscurity to official
Opposition in 10 years, is now seeking control of the Alliance --
which he hopes will become a new national small-c conservative
coalition able to defeat the Liberals.
</P>
<P>
   ''The campaign for the leadership of the Canadian Alliance is
more than a campaign to choose a leader for a new political
party,'' Manning said to about 150 cheering supporters, including
several MPs.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a campaign to choose our next prime minister and the
leader of a new government.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Chretien Not Worried About Fate of Federal Referendum
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- Prime Minister Jean Chretien dismissed fears of a
Senate revolt Monday and said he's confident the upper house will
ratify his proposed federal ground rules for the next Quebec
referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative senators who oppose the so-called clarity bill hope
to win over enough Liberals to stall or amend the legislation that
passed the Commons last week.
</P>
<P>
   Their chief complaint is that the bill doesn't give the Senate
enough of a say in deciding whether the question and majority are
clear in any future plebiscite on Quebec separation.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberals have a comfortable working majority in the Senate,
where they hold 53 seats to 41 for the Tories and five
Independents.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Convicted Murderer Won't Reveal Role in String of Murders
</P>
<P>
   FREDERICTON (AP) -- Convicted killer Michael Wayne McGray is now
refusing to reveal his self-proclaimed role in a string of murders
that could establish him as the worst serial killer in Canadian
history.
</P>
<P>
   McGray, serving a life sentence in Renous, New Brunswick, for
the 1998 murder of a Newfoundland woman, has clammed up after
giving interviews to the news media last week in which he claimed
to have been involved in as many as 16 murders across North
America.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's not talking, so there's not a whole lot anyone can do
right now,'' Const. Roland Cormier of the RCMP in Moncton said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   RCMP investigators from Halifax had hoped to speak with McGray
on Monday but that has been put off until later in the week.
</P>
<P>
   A source in the New Brunswick legal community said Monday that
McGray wants time to himself and is unhappy about the way his
comments were treated by the news media. The source said McGray
believes he was misquoted, so he has decided to say nothing. ---
Red Cross Having Trouble Selling Compensation Plan to Hepatitis C
Victims
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- The Canadian Red Cross is having trouble selling
its plan to compensate tainted blood victims and there's
speculation the agency, which has already lost its blood business,
may be forced into bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross has been under court protection since July 20,
1998 and has requested several deadline extensions as it struggled
to satisfy creditors and tainted blood claimants.
</P>
<P>
   The society's compensation package, to be made public April 10,
is aimed at victims excluded from the $1.2-billion
federal-provincial plan announced two years ago for those infected
between 1986 and 1990.
</P>
<P>
   To qualify for the Red Cross offer, victims would have to waive
their right to sue the agency and some victims feel they'd be
better off in court.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross must submit its compensation package to a vote by
victims. If it's rejected, claimants will likely proceed with
damage claims of billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Red Cross spokesman Bob Rae insisted Monday that talk of
bankruptcy is premature, saying the agency is still negotiating
with governments and victims.
</P>
