<HEADLINE> Japan Insurance Cos. To Merge  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Sumitomo Marine &AMP; Fire Insurance Co. and Mitsui
Marine &AMP; Fire Insurance Co. plan to complete their previously
disclosed merger in October 2001 and eliminate 20.7 percent of
their combined work force by 2005 to cut costs.
</P>
<P>
   The merger between Sumitomo Marine, Japan's fourth-largest
non-life insurer, and Mitsui Marine, the nation's third-largest
non-life insurer, would create Japan's largest non-life insurance
company.
</P>
<P>
   The companies said Monday they expect to eliminate 3,000 of the
combined company's 14,500 jobs by 2005 through attrition,
postponing the hiring of new employees and transferring others to
affiliated companies.
</P>
<P>
   The companies expect to have $55.4 billion in assets at the time
of the merger, and said are setting a market share target of more
than 18 percent over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   The current leader among non-life insurance companies in Japan
is Tokio Marine &AMP; Fire Insurance Co. with $50.72 billion in assets.
</P>
<P>
   Mitsui Marine decided to merge with Sumitomo Marine in February,
after it canceled a planned combination with Nippon Fire &AMP; Marine
Insurance Co. and Koa Fire &AMP; Marine Insurance Co.
</P>
</TEXT>
