<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bill would increase pay for lawmakers, constitutional officers  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- The governor's salary would nearly double
and legislators would get their second pay raise in three years
under a bill approved Monday by a legislative committee.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would hike the governor's pay from $78,000 to $150,000
in 2003, the first pay raise for that office since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. John G. Rowland has not taken a public stance on the
proposed raises.
</P>
<P>
   ''At this point, it's in the hands of the Legislature,'' said
Dean Pagani, Rowland's spokesman. ''The governor will make a
decision if it passes the General Assembly and comes to his desk.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill would also boost the salaries of the lieutenant
governor, secretary of the state, attorney general and treasurer,
which were last raised in January, 1999. Rank-and-file members of
the state's part-time General Assembly received a $5,100 raise last
year, to $21,788. Under the bill, those salaries would be raised to
$28,000 in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Genuario, R-Norwalk, said he's uncomfortable with
the proposed raises, said it is too soon for lawmakers to be taking
home more cash for their elected jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe that the constitutional officers are woefully
underpaid and entitled to a raise,'' said Genuario. ''I'm a little
troubled with legislative raises because we passed a significant
raise for legislators last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Genuario voted for the bill -- which passed 41-7 to the House --
but said he would not support it on the floor if it still includes
a raise for members of the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Terry Backer, D-Stratford, said the pay raises are
needed for the part-time lawmakers who put in full-time hours.
</P>
<P>
   ''The longer you're in office, the more responsibilities you
pick up and the more time you spend here,'' Backer said. ''And you
become more dependent on your wages here because you're working
fewer hours and making less money at whatever your other job is.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to their salaries, House members receive $4,500 a
year in travel expenses. Senators get $5,500.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative leaders, who already receive more money than rank
and file, would also get a raise. The salaries of the Senate
president pro tempore and House speaker would be raised from
$30,108 to $38,689. Minority leaders would also get $8,000 raises.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also would increase the salaries of judges. The Supreme
Court chief justice's pay would be raised in 2002 from $140,582 to
$149,582, and the chief court administrator's salary would be
boosted from $134,738 to $143,738. Superior Court judges would make
$125,000 in 2002, $9,000 more than they will earn in 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
