<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda Suspects' Lawyers Want Report  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Lawyers for suspects in Rwanda's 1994 genocide
called Monday on the U.N. Tribunal for Rwanda to turn over a
confidential document that they say could have bolstered their
clients' defense.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers also questioned the ethics of the U.N. prosecutors
who, for nearly 2{ years, failed to comply with attorneys' requests
for the document, which they say could help counter charges that
their clients planned the massacres.
</P>
<P>
   ''As a lawyer, I'm extremely concerned that an event that
obviously has been considered to be this relevant for the United
Nations was not shared with the defense, and in fact its existence
was denied,'' said Attorney Tiphaine Dickson.
</P>
<P>
   The report concerns the April 6, 1994 death of Rwandan President
Juvenal Habyarimana, a Hutu, which sparked the violence that led to
the genocide of an estimated 500,000 people, most of them Tutsis
and politically moderate Hutus.
</P>
<P>
   Hutu extremists in the former army and the government have long
been thought responsible for downing Habyarimana's airplane in a
bid to sabotage his efforts to implement a power-sharing deal with
the Tutsi-led Rwandan Patriotic Front.
</P>
<P>
   A Canadian newspaper reported March 1 that three Tutsi
informants had told U.N. investigators in 1997 that they were part
of an elite strike team that downed the plane.
</P>
<P>
   Citing a confidential U.N. report, The National Post quoted the
three informants as saying the killing was carried out under the
command of Paul Kagame, who headed the Rwandan Patriotic Front and
is currently the Rwandan vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Rwandan officials have rejected the report as false and said the
tribunal's refusal to pursue the investigation proved that the
report was untrue.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has now said it would turn over a copy of the
report for the tribunal, which would then decide whether to release
it. Tribunal prosecutors have maintained that their mandate only
covered crimes committed during the genocide itself, not before.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the accused say any such report would have helped
undermine one of the prosecution's main arguments: that the
genocide was premeditated by Hutus.
</P>
<P>
   The three-page report, dated Aug. 1, 1997, was not turned over
to the U.N. tribunal because it was an internal document, the U.N.
Office of Legal Affairs said in a March 22 letter.
</P>
<P>
   But the office said its contents were discussed with the chief
prosecutor, Louise Arbour, in September 1997. Arbour is now a
Supreme Court Justice in Canada and has not responded to requests
for comment about the report.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard has said the tribunal would have no
comment on leaked documents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-27-00 2151 </TRAILER>
