<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 49ers 'No. 1 Fan' Dies at 79  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Lido Starelli, who attended every San
Francisco 49ers home game except one and was honored as the team's
top fan, is dead of cancer. He was 79.
</P>
<P>
   Starelli, who died Sunday, was tagged the team's No. 1 fan in
1998 by the 49ers, and was rewarded with a trip to the Pro Football
Hall of Fame in Canton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Starelli's remarkable run began at the team's first home game,
Sept. 1, 1946, at Kezar Stadium against the Chicago Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's all it took,'' he said in 1996. ''From there I just
went.''
</P>
<P>
   The only game Starelli missed was on Dec. 5, 1959 -- the day his
father died.
</P>
<P>
   While Starelli said he liked the teams from the '40s and '50s
best, his favorite play was ''The Catch,'' Dwight Clark's 1981
touchdown reception that sent the team to its first Super Bowl,
ending years of futility.
</P>
<P>
   ''When Clark made that catch, I was crying like a baby,''
Starelli said. ''Tears of agony had become tears of ecstasy.''
</P>
<P>
   Starelli was always superstitious where his favorite team was
concerned. He took a city bus to every game, wore the same clothes
and would enter Candlestick Park through the same gate, handing his
ticket to the same employee.
</P>
<P>
   Starelli is believed to have the only complete set of programs
from every game the team has played, home and away. He kept them in
a basement room at his San Francisco home that became a shrine to
the team.
</P>
<P>
   Starelli also collected every 49ers media guide, lapel pin,
stationery Christmas card and pocket schedule from the last half
century.
</P>
<P>
   ''Receiving the No. 1 fan award was the thrill of his life,''
his son John told the San Francisco Examiner on Sunday. ''He lived
and breathed the 49ers since 1946.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-27-00 2154 </TRAILER>
