<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, March 27, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tensions Rise Over Cuban Boy
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- With the Justice Department threatening to take Elian Gonzalez
from his Miami relatives, a crowd gathered outside the boy's Little Havana home
today, holding a vigil and ready to form a human chain if necessary. The risk of
a confrontation over the 6-year-old boy appeared to grow as the government and
the Miami relatives traded accusations. Attorney General Janet Reno has demanded
that the Miami relatives pursue any court appeals rapidly and promise to
surrender Elian for return to his father in Cuba if they lose. Today, the
relatives filed their latest appeal.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Oil Producers Meet in Vienna
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- OPEC oil ministers on Monday cited Iran as the one
hurdle to get over in order for them to reach an agreement about how much crude
oil to add to the global supplies. Iran accepts the need for OPEC to boost
output, the Iranian Oil Minister Bijan Namdar Zangeneh said, but the amount of
an increase favored by his country might not be enough to reduce petroleum
prices from nine-year highs. Iran, OPEC's second-largest producer, is known to
favor boosting output by about 1.2 million barrels a day -- an amount that
probably would do little to reduce world oil prices.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Putin Takes on New Role
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- After solidifying his position as the new president of Russia,
Vladimir Putin admitted to voters Mondays that he had no swift solutions to
poverty and corruption that plague his nation. Putin ordered the government to
pay off wage debts to state workers, and said a first order of business after
his convincing victory in Sunday's election would be selecting a prime minister.
Putin has promised to protect democratic freedoms, but has yet to indicate how
he would carry the sprawling nation into the post-Boris Yeltsin era. Putin, 47,
was named acting president when Yeltsin resigned Dec. 31.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Ties Up Goods Headed for Iraq
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Even as the United States announced it was allowing
$100 million in equipment to go to Iraq through the U.N. humanitarian program,
Washington tied up $7.6 million in new goods, U.N. figures showed today. The
figures also showed that most of the equipment that Washington released on
Friday included cranes, forklift trucks, car batteries and refrigeration
equipment. The United States has tied up over $1 billion worth of goods in the
U.N. sanctions committee arguing that it wants to make sure it cannot be used
for military purposes.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Offering Fund-Raising Reforms
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- At Marquette University in Milwaukee, Vice President Al
Gore proposed creating a $7.1 billion endowment to pay for House and Senate
campaigns, new disclosure rules for lobbyists and outside groups that pay for
political ads and mandatory free ''rebuttal'' time for candidates targeted by
such third-party ads. He acknowledged he was an ''imperfect messenger'' and
invoked purer reformers -- Republican Sen. John McCain and former Democratic
presidential candidate Bill Bradley -- in promising to lead a bipartisan charge
for change.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Sen. Kennedy Backs Biotech Industry
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Sen. Edward M. Kennedy pledged political support today to the
biotech industry, saying genetic engineering has the ability to dramatically
improve people's lives -- if it's done right. Kennedy spoke just hours after
protesters dumped 30 gallons of ''genetically altered'' soybeans outside the
convention center, where biotech executives and researchers are holding the
largest gathering of its kind this week to discuss developments in the industry.
The industry is exploring ways of altering genes to create, for example,
lifesaving medicines, pest-resistent foods and animal organs suitable for human
transplantation.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japan Stocks Fall Moderately
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 148.46 points to
20,132.57 in early trading on Tuesday. In New York, the Dow Jones industrial
average fell 86.87 to close at 11,025.85.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Connecticut Beats LSU 86-71
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Connecticut struggled against sharp-shooting LSU for a
half before pulling out an 86-71 victory tonight in the NCAA East Regional
women's basketball final. All-American Svetlana Abrosimova led the Huskies with
25 points and was the regional's most valuable player. Sue Bird added 16 points
and Shea Ralph had seven of her 15 late in the second half. April Brown had 25
points and Marie Ferdinand 17 for LSU.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Penn St. Tops Louisiana Tech 86-65
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Lisa Shepherd scored 20 of her 25 points in the
first half to put Penn State in control and the Lady Lions beat top-seeded
Louisiana Tech 86-65 tonight in the NCAA Midwest Regional women's basketball
final. Penn State shot 54 percent from 3-point range and dominated the play
inside. Helen Darling and Philadelphia native Andrea Garner each scored 15
points for Penn State.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by PAULINE M. MILLARD
