<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Questions in Salvadoran Deaths  </HEADLINE>
By MARCOS ALEMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) -- A Jesuit-run university
formally asked prosecutors Monday to re-invesigate the murders of
six priests and two women in 1989, alleging that a former president
and other top officials were negligent in the deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint by the Universidad CentroAmericana did not accuse
President Alfredo Cristiani of direct involvement in the slayings,
but said he and former Defense Minister Rafael Humberto Larios
shared guilt because they could have prevented the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Father Jose Maria Tojeira told a news conference that the school
is urging that officials bring charges against the men in
connections with the slayings, amongs the most notorious atrocities
in the country's 12-year civil war.
</P>
<P>
   The school's complaint did accuse five former army generals of
direct responsibility for the murders.
</P>
<P>
   Aides at Cristiani's office said the former president, who left
office in 1994, had no comment. Phone numbers for the retired
generals were not immediately available.
</P>
<P>
   The six priests, who worked at the university, allegedly had
been suspected of sympathy for the country's rebel movement.
</P>
<P>
   They, along with a housekeeper and her daughter, were rousted
from their beds at and shot by soldiers on Nov. 16, 1989, a U.S.
congressional investigation concluded.
</P>
<P>
   A colonel, two lieutenants, a second lieutenant and five other
soldiers were accused of the slayings, but only two were convicted.
Col. Guillermo Alfredo Benavides and Lt. Yusshy Mendoza were freed
in 1992 due to an amnesty law passed to accompany a peace treaty
ending the war.
</P>
<P>
   Tojeira said that if Salvadoran officials do not act on the
complaint, the university might file a similar action abroad --
possibly in Spain, where a court recently sought the extradition of
former Chilean dictator Augusto Pinochet for alleged crimes against
Spanish citizens.
</P>
<P>
   The Human Rights Commission of the Organization of American
States recently issued a report blaming the government for the
slaying of the priests and saying it had failed to adequately
investigate the incident.
</P>
<P>
   In January, President Francisco Flores -- a member of Cristiani's
party -- said he opposed reopening the case, saying it ''would be to
open the door on a conflict that we have left behind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-27-00 2212 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
