<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alleged Castle Thief Extradited  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A man wanted in France for allegedly stealing
nine castles was extradited Monday to face charges of fraud and
forgery.
</P>
<P>
   Magistrate Judge Douglas Eaton had ordered Jean-Paul Renoir, 53,
extradited to France on Feb. 25, 1998, but an extradition treaty
between the two nations also required approval from the U.S.
Department of State.
</P>
<P>
   That approval came on March 8, authorizing U.S. marshals to
deliver Renoir to French authorities for extradition.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Stillman, a lawyer for Renoir, said the defendant gave
up his appeals and decided to go to France because ''he needed to
put this behind him.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The simple fact is that he's totally innocent of any of these
matters,'' he said. ''He felt the best thing to do was to go to
France.''
</P>
<P>
   In France, the New York resident and his wife, Kiiko Nakahara,
are accused of fraud and forgery for allegedly assuming ownership
of nine chateaus worth an estimated $22.45 million.
</P>
<P>
   Nakahara, who is already in France, has been under court order
to remain there. Her father, Hideki Yokoi, sued the couple in 1994
in state Supreme Court in Manhattan for allegedly stealing his
share of the Empire State Building. Yokoi bought part of the
building in 1991 for $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   Stillman said all of the disputes between the wife and her
family have been settled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
