<HEADLINE> Japan Stocks Fall  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The Tokyo Stock Exchange's main index fell Tuesday
morning on profit-taking following sharp gains the previous day.
The dollar was lower against the yen.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 209.57 points,
or 1.03 percent, to 20,071.46 at the end of the morning session. On
Monday, the average closed up 322.95 points, or 1.61 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar bought 106.58 yen in late morning, down 0.32 yen from
late Monday in Tokyo and also below its late New York level of
106.87 yen.
</P>
<P>
   On the stock market, the Nikkei index lost as investors locked
in profits after Monday's sharp gains.
</P>
<P>
   ''Profit-taking was seen among lower-priced domestic shares that
rallied Monday,'' said Kunihiro Hatae, general manager at Tokyo
Securities Co.
</P>
<P>
   However, shares in Mitsubishi Motors rose after the Japanese
automaker and DaimlerChrysler AG announced Monday that the German
automaker will take a 34 percent stake in Mitsubishi.
</P>
<P>
   In currency dealings, the dollar slipped against the yen,
affected by the yen's relative strength against the euro.
</P>
<P>
   The euro's slide against the yen came after Deutsche Bundesbank
President Ernst Welteke said he didn't see any reason to raise
European interest rates now.
</P>
<P>
   The euro was traded at 103.02 yen, down from 104.35 yen late
Monday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was up 0.32 points to 1,654,15 points. The TOPIX
closed up 13.32 points, or 0.81 percent, the day before.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond was
unquoted in late morning. On Monday, it settled at 1.8950 percent
and its price stood at 100.04.
</P>
</TEXT>
