<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reggie Harris, WWOR-TV reporter/anchor, dies at 46  </HEADLINE>
AP Photo
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEANECK, N.J. (AP) -- Reggie Harris, a reporter and anchor at
WWOR-TV, died Monday while exercising at home. He was 46.
</P>
<P>
   Harris died of an apparent heart attack a few hours before he
was to report to work for his 3:30 p.m. shift at the television
station, known in the New York area as Channel 9.
</P>
<P>
   He was working out on an aerobics machine when he collapsed,
said his wife, Diane. Harris had an irregular heartbeat but no
other known heart disease, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, who had won six Emmy Awards in his career, had been a
lead reporter and anchor at Secaucus-based WWOR-TV since January
1997, and before that a reporter for 10 years at WCBS-TV in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   WWOR-TV news director Will Wright said Harris was known for
relentlessly pursuing a story up until the minute he was scheduled
to deliver a nightly newscast, searching for new information or
leads.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was always breathless in his delivery. He would never let a
story stand still,'' Wright said. ''Sometimes it would drive us
crazy, because we'd be up to the countdown and he'd be out
digging.''
</P>
<P>
   Channel 9 anchor Ernie Anastos called Harris a ''true
professional.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He was the kind of guy that felt a sense of purpose about what
he was doing. He will be sorely missed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Harris was involved in a literacy program in schools throughout
the New York metropolitan area, Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   A native of St. Petersburg, Fla., Harris graduated from Florida
State University and went on to become a reporter in Dallas before
coming to WCBS in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife; a daughter, 19-year-old Rachel
Harris; and a son, 16-year-old Darren.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral plans have not yet been made.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
