<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-27 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Czar's Dagger Stolen  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- A jewel-encrusted dagger and sheath
that belonged to Czar Alexander III of Russia disappeared Sunday
from an exhibit on the Queen Mary, a spokeswoman for the historic
ocean liner-turned-hotel said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The 19th-century dagger, worth an estimated $50,000, is about 11
inches long with a curved steel blade and a gold hilt set with
emerald and turquoise.
</P>
<P>
   It was part of an exhibit on loan from the Russian Museum of
Ethnography in St. Petersburg consisting of presents given to the
last czars of imperial Russia. Alexander III received the dagger in
1883 as a gift from the Emir of Bukhara, in the mountains northeast
of Iran and Iraq, an area now called Uzbekistan.
</P>
<P>
   A security guard discovered the dagger was missing from its
Plexiglas case Sunday afternoon, said Lovetta Kramer, Queen Mary
marketing vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The case had a security camera trained on it, but because of
security concerns, Kramer refused to say how the dagger was
removed. Police Officer David Marander said detectives are
reviewing videotape. He had no other information on the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the exhibit remains open through April 22, and an
additional guard had been added, Kramer said.
</P>
<P>
   Queen Mary officials are offering a $10,000 reward for return of
the dagger and sheath in good condition.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Queen Mary site: http://www.queenmary.com/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
